const SEC_ENGLISH=[{"id":"sde71001","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E1","q":"Read: 'The Apprenticeship\n\nMarcus had worked in his uncle's bicycle repair shop every Saturday for two years, but he had never been allowed to touch a customer's bike without supervision. That changed on a wet Tuesday afternoon when his uncle was called away to a family emergency, leaving Marcus alone with a queue of impatient customers and a workshop full of half-finished repairs.\n\nThe first job looked simple enough: a loose chain on an old mountain bike. Marcus had watched his uncle fix dozens of these. His hands, however, seemed clumsier than usual, fumbling with the tension screws as the owner hovered nearby, checking his watch every few minutes. When the chain finally clicked back into place, Marcus felt a flush of pride that lasted exactly as long as it took to notice the brake cable he'd accidentally loosened in the process.\n\nBy the third customer, something shifted. Marcus stopped trying to remember exactly what his uncle would do and started actually looking at the bike in front of him — really looking, the way his uncle always told him to but he'd never quite understood until now. The gears weren't shifting because of a bent derailleur, not a worn cable as he'd first assumed. He fixed it in under ten minutes.\n\nHis uncle returned just as Marcus was wiping down his tools, surprised to find the workshop quieter than he'd left it and every customer gone, apparently satisfied. \"Slow day?\" his uncle asked, glancing at the empty queue. Marcus considered explaining everything that had happened, then decided against it. \"Something like that,\" he said, and went back to sweeping the floor, allowing himself a small, private smile.'\n\nWhy was Marcus left alone in the workshop?","options":["his uncle had gone on holiday","his uncle was called away to a family emergency","his uncle wanted to test him deliberately","the shop had run out of customers"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage states his uncle 'was called away to a family emergency'."},{"id":"sde71002","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat went wrong with the first repair?","options":["Marcus fixed the wrong bike entirely","Marcus accidentally loosened the brake cable","the customer refused to pay","Marcus couldn't find the right tools"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage states that while fixing the chain, Marcus accidentally loosened the brake cable."},{"id":"sde71003","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Inference","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat caused the shift in Marcus's approach by the third customer?","options":["he called his uncle for help","he started actually examining each bike properly, rather than just recalling what his uncle would do","he gave up and sent the customer away","he used a manual to look up each repair"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage states Marcus 'stopped trying to remember exactly what his uncle would do and started actually looking at the bike in front of him'."},{"id":"sde71004","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat was the actual cause of the gear problem on the third bike?","options":["a worn cable, as Marcus first assumed","a bent derailleur","a loose chain","a flat tyre"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage states the gears weren't shifting 'because of a bent derailleur, not a worn cable as he'd first assumed'."},{"id":"sde71005","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Inference","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhy does Marcus decide not to tell his uncle everything that happened?","options":["he is too embarrassed to speak","the passage doesn't explicitly say, but it suggests quiet pride and confidence rather than a need for approval","he is afraid of being punished","he doesn't remember what happened"],"answer":1,"exp":"Marcus's 'private smile' and brief reply suggest a quiet, personal satisfaction that doesn't need his uncle's recognition to be meaningful."},{"id":"sde71006","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Vocabulary in Context","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat does the word 'fumbling' suggest about Marcus's hands in the second paragraph?","options":["they were moving confidently and precisely","they were moving clumsily and with difficulty","they were perfectly steady","they were not moving at all"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Fumbling\" suggests clumsy, uncertain movements, which fits with the description of his hands seeming 'clumsier than usual'."},{"id":"sde71007","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Text Structure","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhich best describes the overall structure of this passage?","options":["a character struggles, then gradually grows more capable through experience","a character succeeds easily from the very start","two characters have an ongoing argument","a process is explained in a list of numbered steps"],"answer":0,"exp":"The passage follows Marcus from early mistakes to a moment of genuine competence, reflecting gradual growth through experience."},{"id":"sde71008","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Inference","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat is suggested by Marcus's uncle saying 'Slow day?' upon returning?","options":["he immediately suspects something went wrong","he is unaware of everything Marcus dealt with, and assumes little happened","he is angry at Marcus","he already knew what Marcus did before arriving"],"answer":1,"exp":"His uncle's casual question suggests he has no idea how much actually happened, simply noticing the empty queue and assuming a quiet day."},{"id":"sde71009","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E1","q":"Read: 'Why Lights-Out Curfews for Phones Might Actually Help Teenagers Sleep\n\nSleep researchers have spent the last decade investigating a question many parents have asked for years: does using a phone before bed actually affect how well a teenager sleeps? A growing body of evidence suggests the answer is yes — and the reasons are more complex than simple distraction.\n\nThe most commonly cited factor is blue light, the type of light emitted by phone and tablet screens. Blue light exposure in the evening can suppress the body's production of melatonin, a hormone that signals to the brain that it's time to sleep. Even short exposure, researchers have found, can shift a person's natural sleep cycle later by 30 minutes or more.\n\nHowever, blue light is only part of the picture. Equally significant is what researchers call \"cognitive arousal\" — the mental stimulation caused by scrolling through social media, replying to messages, or watching engaging videos. Unlike reading a physical book, which tends to be calming, these activities can keep the brain alert and engaged well past the point when a person intends to fall asleep.\n\nSome schools and families have experimented with simple phone curfews — for example, requiring phones to be switched off or placed in another room an hour before bedtime. Early results from several small studies are promising, showing modest improvements in both how quickly teenagers fall asleep and how rested they report feeling the next day. Critics point out that these studies are often small and short-term, and that enforcing such curfews in practice can be difficult, particularly when teenagers use their phones as alarm clocks.\n\nWhatever the eventual policy implications, the underlying science is becoming difficult to ignore. As more research accumulates, it seems increasingly likely that the hour before bed matters far more than most teenagers — or their parents — currently assume.'\n\nAccording to the text, what does blue light exposure suppress?","options":["adrenaline","melatonin","caffeine","serotonin"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage states blue light exposure 'can suppress the body's production of melatonin'."},{"id":"sde71010","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat is 'cognitive arousal', according to the passage?","options":["a type of blue light","the mental stimulation caused by engaging activities like scrolling or messaging","a medical condition affecting teenagers only","a type of sleep curfew"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage defines cognitive arousal as 'the mental stimulation caused by scrolling through social media, replying to messages, or watching engaging videos'."},{"id":"sde71011","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Writer's Craft","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhy does the writer mention that reading a physical book 'tends to be calming'?","options":["to argue that books should replace all phones","to contrast it with the more stimulating effect of phone activities","to suggest that reading is now outdated","to prove that phones are never useful before bed"],"answer":1,"exp":"This comparison highlights the contrast between calming activities and the more mentally stimulating effect of typical phone use before bed."},{"id":"sde71012","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat criticism do critics raise about the phone curfew studies?","options":["the studies cost too much money","the studies are often small and short-term","the studies were conducted only on adults","the studies have been proven completely false"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage states critics 'point out that these studies are often small and short-term'."},{"id":"sde71013","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat practical difficulty does the passage mention regarding phone curfews?","options":["phones are too expensive to replace","teenagers often use their phones as alarm clocks","schools refuse to allow any phone use","parents are not interested in trying curfews"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage notes that enforcing curfews can be difficult 'particularly when teenagers use their phones as alarm clocks'."},{"id":"sde71014","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Author's Purpose","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat is the writer's overall stance by the end of the passage?","options":["phone curfews are completely proven and should be mandatory everywhere","the science increasingly suggests the hour before bed matters more than most people assume","there is no real evidence connecting phones to sleep at all","blue light is the only factor that matters"],"answer":1,"exp":"The final paragraph states it 'seems increasingly likely that the hour before bed matters far more than most teenagers — or their parents — currently assume', without claiming the matter is fully settled."},{"id":"sde71015","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Vocabulary in Context","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat does the word 'modest' mean in the phrase 'modest improvements' in the fourth paragraph?","options":["extremely large","embarrassing","small but noticeable","completely absent"],"answer":2,"exp":"In this context, \"modest\" means small but still noticeable improvements, not dramatic or huge ones."},{"id":"sde71016","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Text Structure","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhich best describes the text type of this passage?","options":["a persuasive opinion piece with no evidence","an informative report presenting research findings and differing perspectives","a fictional short story","a set of step-by-step instructions"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage presents research findings, defines key terms, and acknowledges criticism — characteristic of an informative report rather than fiction or pure persuasion."},{"id":"sde71017","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Author's Purpose","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhy might the writer have included the critics' viewpoint in the fourth paragraph?","options":["to completely undermine the rest of the passage","to present a balanced view by acknowledging limitations in the research","because the writer disagrees with everything stated earlier","by accident, with no real purpose"],"answer":1,"exp":"Including critics' viewpoints alongside the research findings reflects a balanced, evidence-based approach to reporting on a developing area of science."},{"id":"sde71018","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E1","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'apprehensive'?","options":["confident","anxious","relaxed","indifferent"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Anxious\" means worried or nervous, similar in meaning to 'apprehensive'."},{"id":"sde71019","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E1","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'meticulous'?","options":["careless","careful and precise","quick","forgetful"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Careful and precise\" matches the meaning of 'meticulous', which describes great attention to detail."},{"id":"sde71020","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E1","q":"Which word is the opposite of 'reluctant'?","options":["hesitant","willing","unsure","nervous"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Willing\" is the opposite of 'reluctant', which means unwilling or hesitant."},{"id":"sde71021","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E1","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'candid'?","options":["secretive","honest and direct","confused","silent"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Honest and direct\" matches the meaning of 'candid', which describes truthful, frank speech."},{"id":"sde71022","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E1","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'skeptical'?","options":["doubtful","trusting","excited","confident"],"answer":0,"exp":"\"Doubtful\" matches the meaning of 'skeptical', which describes having doubts about something."},{"id":"sde71023","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E1","q":"Which word is the opposite of 'concise'?","options":["brief","wordy","clear","simple"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Wordy\" is the opposite of 'concise', which describes speech or writing that is brief and to the point."},{"id":"sde71024","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E1","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'diligent'?","options":["lazy","hardworking","forgetful","careless"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Hardworking\" matches the meaning of 'diligent', which describes careful and persistent effort."},{"id":"sde71025","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E1","q":"Which word is the opposite of 'ambiguous'?","options":["unclear","confusing","clear","vague"],"answer":2,"exp":"\"Clear\" is the opposite of 'ambiguous', which describes something open to more than one interpretation."},{"id":"sde72001","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Sentence Types","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E2","q":"Which sentence is a compound sentence?","options":["The dog barked loudly.","Although it was raining, we went outside.","The dog barked, and the cat ran away.","Running quickly, she caught the bus."],"answer":2,"exp":"A compound sentence joins two independent clauses with a coordinating conjunction (like 'and'). \"The dog barked, and the cat ran away\" contains two complete ideas joined by 'and'."},{"id":"sde72002","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Sentence Types","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E2","q":"Which sentence is a complex sentence?","options":["The sun was shining.","The sun was shining, and the birds were singing.","Because the sun was shining, we decided to go for a walk.","The sun shone brightly."],"answer":2,"exp":"A complex sentence contains an independent clause and at least one dependent clause. \"Because the sun was shining\" is a dependent clause attached to the independent clause \"we decided to go for a walk\"."},{"id":"sde72003","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Clauses","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E2","q":"Identify the dependent clause in this sentence: 'After the movie ended, we walked home in the rain.'","options":["we walked home","in the rain","After the movie ended","we walked home in the rain"],"answer":2,"exp":"\"After the movie ended\" cannot stand alone as a complete sentence, making it the dependent clause."},{"id":"sde72004","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Parts of Speech — Conjunctions","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E2","q":"Which word is a coordinating conjunction?","options":["because","although","but","since"],"answer":2,"exp":"\"But\" is one of the coordinating conjunctions (along with for, and, nor, but, or, yet, so), used to join independent clauses of equal importance."},{"id":"sde72005","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Active and Passive Voice","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E2","q":"Which sentence uses the passive voice?","options":["The chef cooked the meal.","The meal was cooked by the chef.","The chef is cooking the meal.","The chef will cook the meal."],"answer":1,"exp":"In the passive voice, the subject receives the action rather than performing it. \"The meal was cooked by the chef\" places the meal (the receiver of the action) as the subject."},{"id":"sde72006","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Punctuation — Apostrophes","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E2","q":"Which sentence correctly uses an apostrophe to show possession?","options":["The dogs bone was buried.","The dog's bone was buried.","The dogs' bone was buried, if there is only one dog.","The dogs's bone was buried."],"answer":1,"exp":"For a single dog, the apostrophe goes before the 's': \"the dog's bone\"."},{"id":"sde72007","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Punctuation — Apostrophes","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E2","q":"Which sentence correctly uses an apostrophe for a plural possessive?","options":["The students' books were left on the desks.","The student's books were left on the desks, if there are several students.","The students books were left on the desks.","The studentss' books were left on the desks."],"answer":0,"exp":"For a plural noun already ending in 's' (students), the apostrophe goes after the 's': \"the students' books\"."},{"id":"sde72008","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Punctuation — Semicolons","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E2","q":"Which sentence uses a semicolon correctly?","options":["I love reading; especially mystery novels.","I love reading; my sister prefers watching movies.","I love reading, my sister prefers watching movies; instead.","I love; reading mystery novels."],"answer":1,"exp":"A semicolon can join two related independent clauses. \"I love reading\" and \"my sister prefers watching movies\" are both complete ideas, correctly joined with a semicolon."},{"id":"sde72009","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Parts of Speech — Prepositions","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E2","q":"Which word in this sentence is a preposition? 'The cat jumped over the fence.'","options":["cat","jumped","over","fence"],"answer":2,"exp":"\"Over\" shows the relationship between the cat's action and the fence, making it a preposition."},{"id":"sde72010","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Direct and Indirect Speech","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E2","q":"Which sentence is written in direct speech?","options":["She said that she was tired.","She said, \"I am tired.\"","She mentioned being tired.","She told us she felt tired."],"answer":1,"exp":"Direct speech uses quotation marks to show someone's exact spoken words: \"I am tired.\""},{"id":"sde72011","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Direct and Indirect Speech","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E2","q":"Convert this direct speech to indirect (reported) speech: 'I am going to the shop,' said Tom.","options":["Tom said, \"I am going to the shop.\"","Tom said that he was going to the shop.","Tom is going to the shop, he said.","Tom asked if he could go to the shop."],"answer":1,"exp":"Indirect speech reports what was said without quotation marks, often changing the tense: \"Tom said that he was going to the shop.\""},{"id":"sde72012","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Clauses","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E2","q":"Which sentence contains a relative clause?","options":["The book was interesting.","The book, which I borrowed from the library, was interesting.","The book was on the table.","I read the book quickly."],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Which I borrowed from the library\" is a relative clause, giving extra information about 'the book'."},{"id":"sde72013","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Parts of Speech — Conjunctions","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E2","q":"Which word correctly completes the sentence: 'Neither the teacher ___ the students were ready for the test.'","options":["or","nor","and","but"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Neither... nor...\" is a correlative conjunction pair used to connect two negative alternatives."},{"id":"sde72014","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Punctuation — Commas","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E2","q":"Which sentence uses correct comma placement in a list?","options":["I packed shoes socks and a hat.","I packed shoes, socks and a hat.","I packed shoes socks, and a hat.","I packed, shoes, socks, and a hat."],"answer":1,"exp":"Commas separate items in a list, with the final comma before 'and' being optional (the Oxford comma): \"shoes, socks and a hat.\""},{"id":"sde72015","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Punctuation — Commas","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E2","q":"Which sentence correctly uses a comma after an introductory clause?","options":["After the storm passed the town began to clean up.","After the storm passed, the town began to clean up.","After, the storm passed the town began to clean up.","After the storm, passed the town began to clean up."],"answer":1,"exp":"A comma should follow an introductory dependent clause, before the main clause begins: \"After the storm passed, the town began to clean up.\""},{"id":"sde72016","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Sentence Structure","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E2","q":"What is the subject of this sentence? 'The brightly coloured kite soared above the trees.'","options":["brightly","coloured","kite","trees"],"answer":2,"exp":"\"Kite\" is the noun performing the action of soaring, making it the subject of the sentence."},{"id":"sde72017","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Grammar — Subject-Verb Agreement","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E2","q":"Which sentence demonstrates correct subject-verb agreement?","options":["The list of names were posted on the board.","The list of names was posted on the board.","The list of names is being posted on the boards, were they.","The lists of name was posted."],"answer":1,"exp":"The subject is \"the list\" (singular), so the verb must also be singular: \"was posted\", even though 'names' (plural) comes between them."},{"id":"sde72018","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Parts of Speech — Adverbs","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E2","q":"Which word in this sentence is an adverb? 'She spoke quietly during the meeting.'","options":["spoke","quietly","during","meeting"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Quietly\" describes how she spoke, making it an adverb modifying the verb 'spoke'."},{"id":"sde72019","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Punctuation — Colons","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E2","q":"Which sentence uses a colon correctly?","options":["I need: milk, eggs, and bread.","I need the following items: milk, eggs, and bread.","I need the following items, milk, eggs, and bread.","I need: the following items milk, eggs, and bread."],"answer":1,"exp":"A colon introduces a list after a complete independent clause: \"I need the following items: milk, eggs, and bread.\""},{"id":"sde72020","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Punctuation — Apostrophes","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E2","q":"Identify the correct plural possessive form: the toys belonging to several children.","options":["childrens' toys","children's toys","childrens toys","childrens's toys"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Children\" is already plural without an 's', so the possessive simply adds 's after it: \"children's toys\"."},{"id":"sde72021","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Grammar — Modifiers","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E2","q":"Which sentence contains a dangling modifier (an error)?","options":["Running quickly, Sam caught the bus.","Running quickly, the bus was caught by Sam.","Sam, running quickly, caught the bus.","Sam ran quickly and caught the bus."],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Running quickly, the bus was caught by Sam\" incorrectly suggests the bus was running, since the modifier should describe Sam, not the bus."},{"id":"sde72022","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Parts of Speech — Pronouns","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E2","q":"Which word in this sentence is a pronoun? 'Maria finished the book and gave it to him.'","options":["finished","book","it","gave"],"answer":2,"exp":"\"It\" stands in for the noun 'the book', making it a pronoun. (\"Him\" is also a pronoun in this sentence, but only 'it' was offered as an option here.)"},{"id":"sde72023","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Grammar — Verb Tense","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E2","q":"Which sentence is in the past perfect tense?","options":["She had finished her homework before dinner.","She finishes her homework before dinner.","She will finish her homework before dinner.","She is finishing her homework before dinner."],"answer":0,"exp":"Past perfect tense uses 'had' plus a past participle to show an action completed before another past action: \"She had finished her homework before dinner.\""},{"id":"sde72024","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Punctuation — Quotation Marks","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E2","q":"Which sentence correctly uses quotation marks for a quote within a quote?","options":["She said, \"My favourite line is 'to be or not to be'.\"","She said, 'My favourite line is \"to be or not to be\".'","She said \"My favourite line is to be or not to be\".","She said, \"My favourite line is to be or not to be.\""],"answer":0,"exp":"When a quote appears inside another quote, single quotation marks are used for the inner quote, within double quotation marks for the outer quote."},{"id":"sde72025","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Commonly Confused Words","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E2","q":"Which sentence uses the correct form of 'fewer' or 'less'?","options":["There are less students in this class than last year.","There are fewer students in this class than last year.","There is fewer student in this class.","There are less student in this class."],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Fewer\" is used for countable nouns (like 'students'), while 'less' is used for uncountable quantities."},{"id":"sde73001","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E3","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'reluctant'?","options":["eager","hesitant","confident","relaxed"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Hesitant\" matches the meaning of 'reluctant', describing unwillingness or hesitation."},{"id":"sde73002","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E3","q":"Which word is the opposite of 'abundant'?","options":["plentiful","scarce","huge","common"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Scarce\" is the opposite of 'abundant', which means existing in large quantities."},{"id":"sde73003","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Word Origins — Prefixes","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E3","q":"The prefix 'bi-' usually relates to which number?","options":["one","two","three","ten"],"answer":1,"exp":"The prefix 'bi-' relates to the number two, as in 'bicycle' (two wheels) or 'bilingual' (two languages)."},{"id":"sde73004","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Word Origins — Roots","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E3","q":"The root word 'chron' relates to which concept?","options":["colour","time","sound","light"],"answer":1,"exp":"The root 'chron' relates to time, as in 'chronological' (in time order) or 'chronicle' (a record over time)."},{"id":"sde73005","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E3","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'persuade'?","options":["confuse","convince","ignore","forbid"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Convince\" matches the meaning of 'persuade', meaning to cause someone to believe or do something through reasoning."},{"id":"sde73006","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Persuasive Techniques","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E3","q":"A writer asks, 'Do we really want our city's history paved over for another car park?' What persuasive technique is this an example of?","options":["a statistic","a rhetorical question","an anecdote","a direct command"],"answer":1,"exp":"A rhetorical question is asked to make a point or provoke thought, rather than to genuinely seek an answer."},{"id":"sde73007","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Persuasive Techniques","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E3","q":"A persuasive text states: 'Studies show that 78% of residents oppose the new development.' What technique is this?","options":["repetition","a statistic","emotive language","a rhetorical question"],"answer":1,"exp":"Citing a specific number ('78%') is an example of using a statistic to support an argument."},{"id":"sde73008","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Persuasive Techniques","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E3","q":"A persuasive text repeats the phrase 'We deserve better' three times across a paragraph. What technique is this?","options":["repetition","alliteration","a statistic","a counter-argument"],"answer":0,"exp":"Repeating the same phrase multiple times is an example of repetition, used to reinforce a key message."},{"id":"sde73009","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Persuasive Techniques","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E3","q":"Which phrase is the best example of emotive language in a persuasive text?","options":["The council reviewed the proposal.","Families will be devastated if this heartless decision goes ahead.","The meeting was held on Tuesday.","The proposal received 40 votes."],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Devastated\" and \"heartless\" are emotionally charged words designed to provoke a strong feeling in the reader, which is the purpose of emotive language."},{"id":"sde73010","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E3","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'inevitable'?","options":["avoidable","unlikely","unavoidable","surprising"],"answer":2,"exp":"\"Unavoidable\" matches the meaning of 'inevitable', describing something certain to happen."},{"id":"sde73011","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Word Origins — Prefixes","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E3","q":"The prefix 'tri-' usually relates to which number?","options":["two","three","four","five"],"answer":1,"exp":"The prefix 'tri-' relates to the number three, as in 'triangle' (three angles) or 'tricycle' (three wheels)."},{"id":"sde73012","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Word Origins — Roots","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E3","q":"The root word 'photo' relates to which concept?","options":["sound","light","water","movement"],"answer":1,"exp":"The root 'photo' relates to light, as in 'photograph' (recorded using light) or 'photosynthesis' (using light energy)."},{"id":"sde73013","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E3","q":"Which word is the opposite of 'transparent' (when describing honesty)?","options":["open","secretive","clear","obvious"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Secretive\" is the opposite of 'transparent' in this context, which describes being open and honest."},{"id":"sde73014","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Persuasive Techniques","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E3","q":"A persuasive speaker says, 'Imagine your own child going without food tonight.' What technique is being used here?","options":["a statistic","an appeal to emotion","a counter-argument","alliteration"],"answer":1,"exp":"Asking the audience to imagine a personal, emotional scenario is designed to create an emotional connection, which is an appeal to emotion."},{"id":"sde73015","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E3","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'scrutinise'?","options":["ignore","examine closely","approve","summarise"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Examine closely\" matches the meaning of 'scrutinise', which means to inspect something carefully."},{"id":"sde73016","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Persuasive Techniques","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E3","q":"A writer acknowledges 'Some argue this policy is too expensive' before responding with reasons why it's still worthwhile. What technique is this?","options":["addressing a counter-argument","using alliteration","repetition","a rhetorical question"],"answer":0,"exp":"Raising and then responding to an opposing view is the technique of addressing a counter-argument, which can make a writer's position seem more reasonable."},{"id":"sde73017","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Word Origins — Suffixes","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E3","q":"The suffix '-phobia' usually relates to which concept?","options":["love","fear","knowledge","speed"],"answer":1,"exp":"The suffix '-phobia' relates to fear, as in 'arachnophobia' (fear of spiders) or 'claustrophobia' (fear of confined spaces)."},{"id":"sde73018","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E3","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'futile'?","options":["successful","pointless","urgent","simple"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Pointless\" matches the meaning of 'futile', which describes something incapable of achieving any result."},{"id":"sde73019","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Persuasive Techniques","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E3","q":"A slogan reads: 'Save our streets, save our future.' What technique combines repetition with structure here?","options":["onomatopoeia","parallelism (repeated sentence structure)","a simile","a direct quote"],"answer":1,"exp":"Repeating the same sentence structure ('Save our ___') creates parallelism, making the slogan more memorable and rhythmic."},{"id":"sde73020","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E3","q":"Which word is the opposite of 'verbose'?","options":["wordy","concise","detailed","loud"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Concise\" is the opposite of 'verbose', which describes using more words than necessary."},{"id":"sde73021","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Word Origins — Roots","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E3","q":"The root word 'aud' relates to which concept?","options":["sight","hearing","taste","touch"],"answer":1,"exp":"The root 'aud' relates to hearing, as in 'audience' (those who listen) or 'audible' (able to be heard)."},{"id":"sde73022","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E3","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'pragmatic'?","options":["impractical","idealistic","practical and realistic","emotional"],"answer":2,"exp":"\"Practical and realistic\" matches the meaning of 'pragmatic', describing a sensible, results-focused approach."},{"id":"sde73023","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Persuasive Techniques","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E3","q":"A persuasive text uses the line, 'Don't just sit there — act now!' What technique is this an example of?","options":["a direct command (imperative)","a simile","alliteration","a counter-argument"],"answer":0,"exp":"\"Act now\" is a direct command (an imperative sentence), urging the audience to take immediate action."},{"id":"sde73024","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Word Origins — Prefixes","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E3","q":"The prefix 'auto-' usually relates to which concept?","options":["self","many","far","fast"],"answer":0,"exp":"The prefix 'auto-' relates to self, as in 'autobiography' (a story of one's own life) or 'automatic' (operating by itself)."},{"id":"sde73025","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E3","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'ambivalent'?","options":["certain","having mixed feelings","angry","excited"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Having mixed feelings\" matches the meaning of 'ambivalent', describing uncertainty between two viewpoints or feelings."},{"id":"sde74001","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Author's Purpose","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E4","q":"Read: 'Why Every School Needs a Later Start Time\n\nIt's 7:15 am, and somewhere across the country, a tired teenager is being shaken awake for school, despite having fallen asleep only six hours earlier. This scene repeats itself in millions of households every single morning — and it's a problem we have the power to fix.\n\nThe science on this issue is no longer in dispute. Adolescent brains undergo a natural shift during the teenage years, delaying the release of melatonin until later in the evening. This isn't laziness, and it isn't a lifestyle choice — it's basic biology. Forcing teenagers to wake before 7 am, when their bodies are biologically still in deep sleep, is the equivalent of waking an adult at 4 am every single day.\n\nCritics will say that later start times simply shift the problem, pushing bedtimes later instead of solving anything. But multiple large-scale studies tell a different story: when schools delay start times by even 30 to 60 minutes, average sleep duration increases, not decreases. Students aren't staying up later to compensate — they're finally getting the sleep their changing bodies actually need.\n\nThe benefits extend far beyond simply feeling less tired. Schools that have shifted to later start times report measurable improvements in student attendance, mood, and even road safety, with fewer car accidents among newly licensed teenage drivers during the early morning commute. Academic performance, too, shows modest but consistent improvement, particularly in first-period classes.\n\nOf course, change is never without complications. Bus schedules need adjusting. After-school sports and part-time jobs may need to shift. Working parents may need to rethink their morning routines. These are genuine, practical concerns — but they are logistical puzzles to be solved, not reasons to ignore an entire body of medical evidence. We would never tell a diabetic patient to ignore their condition because adjusting their diet is inconvenient. We shouldn't treat adolescent sleep biology any differently.'\n\nWhat is the writer's main argument?","options":["that teenagers are simply lazy and need more discipline","that schools should start later because of biological changes in teenage sleep patterns","that all schools should remove early morning classes entirely","that parents are responsible for teenagers' tiredness"],"answer":1,"exp":"The writer argues throughout that school start times should be later, specifically because of biological changes affecting teenage sleep, not due to laziness or poor choices."},{"id":"sde74002","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Writer's Craft","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E4","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhy does the writer compare an early teenage start time to 'waking an adult at 4 am'?","options":["to make a literal, scientific comparison","to use exaggeration that helps readers feel how disruptive this schedule is for teenagers","to suggest adults should also wake up earlier","to provide an unrelated fact"],"answer":1,"exp":"This comparison is a persuasive technique that helps readers emotionally grasp how disruptive an early start feels for a teenager's altered sleep cycle, even though it's not a literal scientific equivalence."},{"id":"sde74003","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Persuasive Techniques","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E4","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat is the writer's response to the criticism that later start times just shift bedtimes later?","options":["the writer agrees and offers no response","studies show sleep duration actually increases, rather than students simply staying up later","the writer ignores this criticism entirely","the writer admits the criticism is completely valid"],"answer":1,"exp":"The writer directly counters this criticism by citing studies showing 'average sleep duration increases, not decreases' when start times are delayed."},{"id":"sde74004","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E4","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhich of these is presented as a benefit of later school start times, according to the passage?","options":["increased road accidents","reduced road accidents among new teen drivers","reduced school attendance","worse academic performance"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage states schools with later start times report 'fewer car accidents among newly licensed teenage drivers during the early morning commute'."},{"id":"sde74005","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Persuasive Techniques","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E4","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhy does the writer compare this issue to telling 'a diabetic patient to ignore their condition'?","options":["to argue that diabetes and sleep are the same medical condition","to argue that practical inconvenience shouldn't override clear medical evidence","to confuse the reader with an unrelated topic","to suggest that schools should ignore all health issues"],"answer":1,"exp":"This analogy supports the writer's argument that practical difficulties (like bus schedules) shouldn't be used as an excuse to dismiss clear biological evidence, just as we wouldn't dismiss a medical condition for being inconvenient to manage."},{"id":"sde74006","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E4","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhich practical concerns does the writer acknowledge in the final paragraph?","options":["bus schedules, after-school activities, and parents' routines","only bus schedules","only academic performance","none — the writer claims there are no real concerns"],"answer":0,"exp":"The final paragraph lists several practical concerns: bus schedules, after-school sports and jobs, and parents' morning routines."},{"id":"sde74007","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Vocabulary in Context","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E4","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat does the word 'dispute' mean in the second paragraph?","options":["agreement","disagreement or debate","celebration","explanation"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"In dispute\" means under disagreement or debate. The writer states the science is 'no longer in dispute', meaning it's now widely agreed upon."},{"id":"sde74008","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Interpreting Mood","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E4","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhich best describes the overall tone of this passage?","options":["uncertain and apologetic","confident and persuasive","humorous and light-hearted","angry and aggressive"],"answer":1,"exp":"The writer makes firm claims, cites evidence, and directly counters criticism throughout, reflecting a confident and persuasive tone."},{"id":"sde74009","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E4","q":"Read: 'The Last Bell\n\nThe corridor empties in a rush of noise,\nbackpacks swinging, voices rising loud,\nfive years of mornings spent in these same halls\ncollapsing now into one final crowd.\n\nI used to count the days until this one,\nmark them off in red across the wall,\nand now the number's gone to nothing, none,\nand I'm not sure I wanted it at all.\n\nMr. Hendricks waves from his classroom door,\nthe one who failed me once, then let me try again,\nand somewhere in that quiet second chance\nI learned more than he likely meant to teach me then.\n\nThe bell that rings is just a bell, of course,\na small mechanical, unremarkable sound,\nbut something in my chest goes strangely still\nas if the whole world paused to look around.\n\nI thought I'd run the moment I was free.\nInstead I'm standing here, in no great hurry,\nwatching five years fold themselves away\ninto a hallway I won't see in any worry —\n\nexcept I will. I know that even now.\nSome doors don't close as cleanly as they seem.\nI'll think of this same hallway, oddly enough,\nlong after it's reduced to just a dream.'\n\nWhat event is the speaker describing in this poem?","options":["the first day of school","a fire drill","the final day at a school the speaker is leaving","a school holiday"],"answer":2,"exp":"The poem describes 'the last bell' and 'five years' collapsing into one final crowd, indicating this is the speaker's final day at this school."},{"id":"sde74010","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Interpreting Mood","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E4","q":"Read the same poem.\n\nIn the second stanza, what does the speaker reveal about their feelings towards this day?","options":["they had always dreaded this day","they had been counting down to it eagerly, but now feel surprisingly uncertain","they feel nothing at all","they are angry about leaving"],"answer":1,"exp":"The speaker describes counting down the days, but now says \"I'm not sure I wanted it at all\", revealing unexpected uncertainty."},{"id":"sde74011","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E4","q":"Read the same poem.\n\nWhat does the third stanza reveal about Mr. Hendricks?","options":["he was a strict teacher who never helped anyone","he gave the speaker a second chance after failing them once, leading to an unexpected lesson","he is leaving the school as well","he never spoke to the speaker"],"answer":1,"exp":"The poem describes Mr. Hendricks as 'the one who failed me once, then let me try again', and the speaker learned something valuable from that experience."},{"id":"sde74012","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Writer's Craft","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E4","q":"Read the same poem.\n\nWhat literary device is used in the phrase 'a small mechanical, unremarkable sound'?","options":["simile","description that downplays the bell's true emotional significance","onomatopoeia","rhyme only"],"answer":1,"exp":"By describing the bell as 'small' and 'unremarkable', the poet creates an ironic contrast with the deep emotional impact it actually has on the speaker, shown in the next lines."},{"id":"sde74013","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Inference","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E4","q":"Read the same poem.\n\nWhat does the phrase 'something in my chest goes strangely still' suggest about the speaker?","options":["they are having a medical emergency","they feel a sudden, quiet emotional reaction to the moment","they are bored","they are about to fall asleep"],"answer":1,"exp":"This physical description reflects a quiet, internal emotional reaction — a moment of stillness and reflection rather than a literal physical problem."},{"id":"sde74014","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Inference","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E4","q":"Read the same poem.\n\nWhat does the final stanza suggest about the speaker's true feelings about leaving?","options":["they will forget about the school completely and immediately","they suspect they will continue thinking about this place long after leaving","they regret every moment spent at the school","they are excited to never think about it again"],"answer":1,"exp":"The lines \"I'll think of this same hallway, oddly enough, long after it's reduced to just a dream\" suggest the speaker expects this place to stay meaningful long after leaving."},{"id":"sde74015","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Writer's Craft","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E4","q":"Read the same poem.\n\nWhich best describes the rhyme pattern used within each four-line stanza?","options":["every line rhymes with every other line","the first and third lines rhyme, and the second and fourth lines rhyme (an ABAB-style pattern)","there is no rhyme at all","only the first two lines rhyme"],"answer":1,"exp":"Looking at each stanza, the first and third lines share an end rhyme, and the second and fourth lines share a different end rhyme, forming an ABAB-style pattern."},{"id":"sde74016","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Author's Purpose","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E4","q":"Read the same poem.\n\nWhat is the overall theme of this poem?","options":["the excitement of starting a new school","the bittersweet, complicated feelings of leaving somewhere familiar","the importance of arriving to school on time","a description of a typical school day"],"answer":1,"exp":"The poem explores mixed, complex emotions — eagerness to leave alongside unexpected nostalgia — reflecting the bittersweet nature of moving on from somewhere familiar."},{"id":"sde74017","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Figurative Language","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E4","q":"Which sentence contains a simile?","options":["The wind howled through the trees.","Her smile was as bright as the morning sun.","The car was fast.","He ran quickly to the door."],"answer":1,"exp":"A simile compares two things using 'like' or 'as'. \"As bright as the morning sun\" compares her smile to the sun using 'as'."},{"id":"sde74018","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Figurative Language","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E4","q":"Which sentence contains a metaphor?","options":["The classroom was a zoo by the end of the day.","The classroom was noisy.","The classroom was like a zoo.","The classroom had many students."],"answer":0,"exp":"A metaphor states that one thing IS another, without using 'like' or 'as'. \"The classroom was a zoo\" directly equates the two, rather than comparing them."},{"id":"sde74019","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Figurative Language","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E4","q":"Which phrase is an example of personification?","options":["The dog ran fast.","The wind whispered secrets through the trees.","The car was red.","The book was heavy."],"answer":1,"exp":"Personification gives human qualities to non-human things. \"The wind whispered secrets\" gives the wind a human ability (whispering)."},{"id":"sde74020","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Figurative Language","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E4","q":"Which phrase is an example of alliteration?","options":["The big brown bear blundered by.","The cat sat on the mat.","She ran to the shop.","The sky was blue today."],"answer":0,"exp":"Alliteration repeats the same starting consonant sound in nearby words. \"Big brown bear blundered\" repeats the 'b' sound."},{"id":"sde74021","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Figurative Language","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E4","q":"Which phrase is an example of onomatopoeia?","options":["The bee buzzed past my ear.","The bee flew past my ear.","The bee was yellow and black.","The bee landed on a flower."],"answer":0,"exp":"Onomatopoeia uses words that imitate sounds. \"Buzzed\" imitates the actual sound a bee makes."},{"id":"sde74022","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Figurative Language","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E4","q":"What is hyperbole?","options":["a quiet, calm tone","an extreme exaggeration not meant to be taken literally","a type of rhyme","a factual statement"],"answer":1,"exp":"Hyperbole is deliberate, extreme exaggeration used for emphasis or effect, such as saying \"I've told you a million times.\""},{"id":"sde74023","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Figurative Language","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E4","q":"Which sentence is an example of hyperbole?","options":["I'm a little hungry.","I could eat a horse, I'm so hungry.","I would like a sandwich.","I haven't eaten since breakfast."],"answer":1,"exp":"\"I could eat a horse\" is an extreme exaggeration not meant literally, used to emphasise how hungry the speaker feels."},{"id":"sde74024","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Writer's Craft","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E4","q":"What effect does repeating a consonant sound (alliteration) usually have on a piece of writing?","options":["it makes the writing harder to understand","it can create rhythm and draw attention to a phrase","it always makes writing sound sad","it has no real effect on the reader"],"answer":1,"exp":"Alliteration often creates rhythm and can make a phrase more memorable or emphatic by drawing the reader's attention to it."},{"id":"sde74025","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Poetry Terms","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E4","q":"In poetry, what is a 'stanza'?","options":["a single word","a group of lines forming a unit, similar to a paragraph in prose","the title of the poem","the rhyme scheme only"],"answer":1,"exp":"A stanza is a group of lines grouped together within a poem, functioning similarly to a paragraph in prose writing."},{"id":"sde81001","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E1","q":"Read: 'The Inheritance\n\nAunt Ruth's house had been empty for three months before anyone worked up the courage to sort through it, and even then, it was only because the real estate agent kept calling about the sale. Priya volunteered, partly out of genuine affection for her great-aunt and partly to escape a family group chat that had become unbearable with arguments over who should get what.\n\nThe house smelled exactly as she remembered — old books, lavender, something faintly like burnt toast that Priya suspected was just the smell of the ancient stove. She'd expected the sorting to take an afternoon. It took four days, not because there was so much to go through, but because every drawer seemed to contain something that stopped her mid-task: photographs of relatives she'd never met, letters in handwriting too elegant to belong to anyone she knew personally, a recipe card stained with what might have been forty years of the same spilled ingredient.\n\nIt was in the bottom drawer of an unremarkable writing desk that Priya found the journal. Aunt Ruth had apparently kept one consistently from age nineteen until just a few years before her death — decades of entries, some only a single line, others sprawling across multiple pages. Priya hadn't intended to read more than a few entries. She ended up sitting on the dusty floor for three hours, utterly unaware of the cramping in her legs.\n\nWhat struck her most wasn't any single revelation, though there were a few surprising ones. It was the accumulation — watching a person's entire adult life unfold in fragments, contradictions intact, certainties from one decade quietly abandoned in the next. Ruth at twenty-five had been furious about something Priya now understood, decades later, to be almost trivial. Ruth at sixty had written, with startling clarity, about regrets she'd apparently spent thirty years avoiding. By the final entry, dated just two years before her death, she sounded, if anything, at peace — amused, even, by her younger selves.\n\nPriya didn't take much from the house in the end. A few photographs, the recipe card, and the journal, which she has not yet finished reading, three months later. She tells herself this is because she's been busy. She suspects, somewhere beneath that excuse, it's actually because finishing it will mean Aunt Ruth is more thoroughly gone than the empty house already made her feel.'\n\nWhy did Priya volunteer to sort through her aunt's house?","options":["she needed the money from selling items","out of genuine affection for her aunt, and partly to escape a difficult family group chat","her parents forced her to do it","she had no other reason given in the text"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage states she volunteered 'partly out of genuine affection for her great-aunt and partly to escape a family group chat that had become unbearable'."},{"id":"sde81002","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhy did the sorting process take four days instead of an afternoon?","options":["there was an overwhelming amount of furniture to move","every drawer contained something that stopped her, even though there wasn't actually that much to go through","she kept getting interrupted by phone calls","the house was too large to search quickly"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage explicitly states it wasn't because there was 'so much to go through', but because items kept stopping her mid-task emotionally."},{"id":"sde81003","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Inference","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat does the phrase 'utterly unaware of the cramping in her legs' suggest about Priya while reading the journal?","options":["she had fallen asleep","she was so absorbed in reading that she lost track of physical discomfort","she was in serious pain","she didn't enjoy reading the journal at all"],"answer":1,"exp":"This detail suggests Priya was so deeply absorbed in the journal that she didn't notice the physical discomfort of sitting still for so long."},{"id":"sde81004","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Inference","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat change does the passage describe in Aunt Ruth between her twenties and her final years?","options":["she became angrier and more bitter over time","she moved from youthful certainty and frustration toward a sense of peace and even amusement","she completely forgot her younger experiences","there is no real change described"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage contrasts Ruth's youthful fury over something now seen as trivial with her later, peaceful, even amused reflection in her final journal entry."},{"id":"sde81005","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Inference","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhy hasn't Priya finished reading the journal, according to the final paragraph?","options":["she lost the journal","she claims she's been busy, but suspects the real reason is that finishing it would make her aunt's death feel more final","she didn't find the journal interesting","she gave the journal away to another relative"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage states her stated excuse is being busy, but suggests the deeper reason is an unwillingness to confront the finality of her aunt's death."},{"id":"sde81006","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Vocabulary in Context","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat does the word 'accumulation' mean in the fourth paragraph?","options":["a single, dramatic event","the gradual gathering or build-up of many things over time","a sudden loss of something","a type of furniture"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Accumulation\" refers to the gradual gathering of many small things over time — in this case, the build-up of journal entries across decades."},{"id":"sde81007","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Text Structure","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhich best describes the overall structure of this passage?","options":["a character discovers an object that leads to a deeper emotional reflection on a relative's life","a straightforward set of instructions for sorting a house","an argument for and against keeping family possessions","a comedic story with no serious themes"],"answer":0,"exp":"The passage follows Priya's discovery of the journal and her resulting reflection on her aunt's life and her own feelings about loss."},{"id":"sde81008","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Inference","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat is suggested by Ruth's final journal entry being described as showing she was 'amused, even, by her younger selves'?","options":["Ruth had forgotten her younger years entirely","Ruth had gained a sense of perspective and gentle humour about her own past","Ruth regretted her entire life","Ruth was confused in her final years"],"answer":1,"exp":"Being 'amused' by her younger selves suggests Ruth had gained enough distance and perspective to look back on her past with gentle humour rather than regret or confusion."},{"id":"sde81009","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E1","q":"Read: 'Should Schools Ban Energy Drinks on Campus?\n\nWalk through the halls of many secondary schools today, and you'll likely spot at least one brightly coloured energy drink can poking out of a student's bag. What was once a niche product marketed to extreme athletes has become a normalised part of teenage life, and a growing number of schools are now grappling with whether to ban them outright.\n\nThe case for banning these drinks rests largely on health concerns. A single can of many popular energy drinks contains caffeine levels comparable to two or three cups of coffee, alongside significant amounts of sugar. Paediatric health experts have raised concerns about the effects of this combination on developing adolescent bodies, citing potential impacts on heart rate, sleep patterns, and anxiety levels. Some students, researchers note, are consuming multiple cans per day — a pattern far removed from the occasional treat these products are often marketed as.\n\nOpponents of a ban raise a different set of concerns, focused less on the drinks themselves and more on the precedent such bans might set. If schools begin banning specific food and drink products based on health concerns, where exactly does that line get drawn? Sugary soft drinks, some heavily processed snack foods, and even certain sports drinks could arguably fall under similar scrutiny. Critics also point out that determined students will simply consume these drinks before arriving at school or immediately after leaving, undermining the practical impact of any on-campus ban.\n\nA middle-ground approach, adopted by a number of schools, involves restricting sales on school premises while stopping short of an outright ban on bringing drinks from home. This allows schools to avoid directly profiting from a product they consider unhealthy, while sidestepping some of the enforcement and consistency concerns raised by critics of a full ban.\n\nUltimately, the debate reflects a broader, recurring tension in school policy: balancing genuine concern for student wellbeing against the practical limits of what a school can realistically control once students leave its gates each afternoon.'\n\nAccording to the passage, what health concern is associated with energy drinks?","options":["they contain too much protein","high caffeine and sugar levels affecting heart rate, sleep, and anxiety","they cause permanent memory loss","they are too expensive for most families"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage states concerns about 'effects of this combination on developing adolescent bodies, citing potential impacts on heart rate, sleep patterns, and anxiety levels'."},{"id":"sde81010","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat concern do opponents of a ban raise about where 'the line gets drawn'?","options":["they worry that banning one product could lead to questions about banning many other similar products","they believe energy drinks are completely harmless","they think schools have no right to make any rules at all","they argue energy drinks should be mandatory in schools"],"answer":0,"exp":"The passage states critics worry about where the line would be drawn, noting that 'sugary soft drinks, some heavily processed snack foods, and even certain sports drinks could arguably fall under similar scrutiny'."},{"id":"sde81011","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat is the practical criticism made about banning energy drinks specifically on school campuses?","options":["students would simply switch to coffee instead","determined students could just consume the drinks before or after school, limiting the ban's actual impact","schools cannot legally enforce any food rules","the drinks would become more popular if banned"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage notes that critics point out 'determined students will simply consume these drinks before arriving at school or immediately after leaving'."},{"id":"sde81012","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat is the 'middle-ground approach' described in the fourth paragraph?","options":["banning all sugary drinks and snacks","restricting on-campus sales while still allowing students to bring drinks from home","requiring parental permission for all drinks","completely banning all drinks from school grounds"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage describes this approach as 'restricting sales on school premises while stopping short of an outright ban on bringing drinks from home'."},{"id":"sde81013","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Author's Purpose","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat is the overall purpose of this passage?","options":["to persuade readers that energy drinks should definitely be banned","to persuade readers that energy drinks should never be restricted","to present multiple perspectives on a genuinely debated policy question","to provide step-by-step instructions for writing a school policy"],"answer":2,"exp":"The passage presents arguments both for and against a ban, along with a compromise approach, rather than arguing strongly for one single position."},{"id":"sde81014","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Vocabulary in Context","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat does the word 'precedent' mean in the third paragraph?","options":["an example or decision that influences future similar situations","a type of energy drink ingredient","a school's daily schedule","a legal requirement with no flexibility"],"answer":0,"exp":"\"Precedent\" refers to a decision or example that could influence how similar situations or decisions are handled in the future."},{"id":"sde81015","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Author's Purpose","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhich best describes the final paragraph's main point?","options":["the debate is simple and easily resolved","the debate reflects a genuine, ongoing tension between student wellbeing and practical limits on what schools can control","schools should give up trying to manage this issue entirely","energy drinks are entirely the responsibility of parents, not schools"],"answer":1,"exp":"The final paragraph describes this as 'a broader, recurring tension... balancing genuine concern for student wellbeing against the practical limits of what a school can realistically control'."},{"id":"sde81016","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Text Structure","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhich text type best describes this passage?","options":["a personal narrative","a balanced informative/discussion text exploring multiple perspectives","a strict set of school rules","a poem"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage presents factual information and multiple perspectives on a genuine debate, characteristic of a balanced discussion or informative text."},{"id":"sde81017","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E1","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'niche' (as in a 'niche product')?","options":["mainstream","specialised or limited to a particular group","worthless","expensive"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Specialised or limited to a particular group\" matches the meaning of 'niche', describing something appealing to a small, specific audience."},{"id":"sde81018","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E1","q":"Which word is the opposite of 'normalised'?","options":["common","unusual or unaccepted","popular","widespread"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Unusual or unaccepted\" is the opposite of 'normalised', which describes something that has become standard or widely accepted."},{"id":"sde81019","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E1","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'grappling' (as in 'grappling with a decision')?","options":["ignoring","struggling to deal with","celebrating","avoiding entirely"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Struggling to deal with\" matches the meaning of 'grappling', describing wrestling with a difficult issue."},{"id":"sde81020","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E1","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'sidestepping' (as in 'sidestepping a problem')?","options":["confronting directly","avoiding cleverly","solving completely","ignoring rudely"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Avoiding cleverly\" matches the meaning of 'sidestepping', describing skilfully avoiding a difficulty."},{"id":"sde81021","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E1","q":"Which word is the opposite of 'unremarkable'?","options":["ordinary","plain","extraordinary","forgettable"],"answer":2,"exp":"\"Extraordinary\" is the opposite of 'unremarkable', which describes something not worth noticing or commenting on."},{"id":"sde81022","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E1","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'startling' (as in 'startling clarity')?","options":["boring","strikingly surprising","gentle","slow"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Strikingly surprising\" matches the meaning of 'startling', which describes something that causes sudden surprise."},{"id":"sde81023","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E1","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'trivial'?","options":["extremely important","unimportant or minor","dangerous","confusing"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Unimportant or minor\" matches the meaning of 'trivial', describing something of little significance."},{"id":"sde81024","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E1","q":"Which word is the opposite of 'genuine' (as in 'genuine affection')?","options":["sincere","real","fake","honest"],"answer":2,"exp":"\"Fake\" is the opposite of 'genuine', which describes something authentic and real."},{"id":"sde81025","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E1","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'recurring' (as in a 'recurring tension')?","options":["happening only once","happening again and again","completely resolved","forgotten"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Happening again and again\" matches the meaning of 'recurring', describing something that keeps reappearing over time."},{"id":"sde82001","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Grammar — Mood","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E2","q":"Which sentence uses the subjunctive mood correctly?","options":["If I was rich, I would travel the world.","If I were rich, I would travel the world.","If I am rich, I would travel the world.","If I will be rich, I would travel the world."],"answer":1,"exp":"The subjunctive mood uses 'were' (not 'was') to describe hypothetical or unreal situations: \"If I were rich...\""},{"id":"sde82002","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Active and Passive Voice","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E2","q":"Which sentence demonstrates correct use of the passive voice?","options":["The committee approved the proposal.","The proposal was approved by the committee.","The committee is approving the proposal.","The committee will approve the proposal."],"answer":1,"exp":"In the passive voice, the subject receives the action. \"The proposal was approved by the committee\" places the proposal (the receiver of the action) as the subject."},{"id":"sde82003","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Clauses","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E2","q":"Identify the type of clause underlined in this sentence: 'The author, who won several awards, spoke at the conference.'","options":["independent clause","relative (adjective) clause","adverbial clause","noun clause"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Who won several awards\" is a relative clause, giving extra information about the noun 'the author'."},{"id":"sde82004","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Clauses","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E2","q":"Identify the type of clause in this sentence: 'Whoever finishes first will receive a prize.'","options":["adjective clause","adverbial clause","noun clause acting as the subject","independent clause only"],"answer":2,"exp":"\"Whoever finishes first\" functions as the subject of the sentence, acting as a noun clause."},{"id":"sde82005","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Clauses","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E2","q":"Which sentence contains an adverbial clause?","options":["The book, which I borrowed, was excellent.","Whatever you decide is fine with me.","Although it was raining, the match continued.","The dog that barked loudly ran away."],"answer":2,"exp":"\"Although it was raining\" is an adverbial clause, providing information about the circumstances of the main clause (the match continuing)."},{"id":"sde82006","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Punctuation — Colons","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E2","q":"Which sentence uses a colon correctly to introduce an explanation?","options":["She had one goal: to win the championship.","She had one goal, to win: the championship.","She had: one goal to win the championship.","She had one goal to win, the championship."],"answer":0,"exp":"A colon can introduce an explanation or elaboration after a complete clause: \"She had one goal: to win the championship.\""},{"id":"sde82007","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Punctuation — Dashes","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E2","q":"Which sentence correctly uses a dash to add an aside or interruption?","options":["The plan — which seemed simple at first — quickly fell apart.","The plan, which seemed simple — at first quickly fell apart.","The plan which seemed — simple at first, quickly fell apart.","The — plan seemed simple at first quickly fell apart."],"answer":0,"exp":"Dashes can be used to set off an aside or additional comment within a sentence, similar to brackets: \"The plan — which seemed simple at first — quickly fell apart.\""},{"id":"sde82008","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Parts of Speech — Conjunctions","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E2","q":"Which word in this sentence is a subordinating conjunction? 'We stayed inside because it was raining.'","options":["stayed","inside","because","raining"],"answer":2,"exp":"\"Because\" introduces a dependent clause explaining the reason for the main clause, making it a subordinating conjunction."},{"id":"sde82009","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Direct and Indirect Speech","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E2","q":"Which sentence correctly converts direct speech into reported (indirect) speech? Direct: 'I will finish the project tomorrow,' said Maya.","options":["Maya said, \"I will finish the project tomorrow.\"","Maya said that she would finish the project the next day.","Maya said I will finish the project tomorrow.","Maya asked if she would finish the project tomorrow."],"answer":1,"exp":"In reported speech, 'will' often changes to 'would', 'I' changes to 'she', and 'tomorrow' may change to 'the next day': \"Maya said that she would finish the project the next day.\""},{"id":"sde82010","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Grammar — Modifiers","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E2","q":"Which sentence demonstrates a misplaced modifier (an error)?","options":["Walking to school, Liam saw a rainbow.","Liam saw a rainbow walking to school.","Liam, walking to school, saw a rainbow.","While walking to school, Liam saw a rainbow."],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Liam saw a rainbow walking to school\" incorrectly suggests the rainbow was walking to school, since the modifier is placed too far from the word it should describe (Liam)."},{"id":"sde82011","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Grammar — Parallel Structure","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E2","q":"Which sentence uses parallel structure correctly?","options":["She likes hiking, swimming, and to read.","She likes hiking, swimming, and reading.","She likes to hike, swimming, and reading.","She likes hiking, to swim, and reading."],"answer":1,"exp":"Parallel structure requires items in a list to use the same grammatical form: \"hiking, swimming, and reading\" all use the '-ing' form consistently."},{"id":"sde82012","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Grammar — Who vs Whom","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E2","q":"Which sentence correctly uses 'who' versus 'whom'?","options":["Who did you give the book to?","Whom did you give the book to?","Whom gave the book to you?","Who's book did you give away?"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Whom\" is correct here because it is the object of the verb 'give' (you gave the book TO whom), while 'who' is used for subjects."},{"id":"sde82013","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Grammar — Verb Tense","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E2","q":"Which sentence is written in the past progressive (continuous) tense?","options":["She walked to school.","She was walking to school when it started to rain.","She walks to school every day.","She will walk to school tomorrow."],"answer":1,"exp":"Past progressive tense uses 'was/were' plus a present participle (-ing) to show an ongoing past action: \"She was walking to school...\""},{"id":"sde82014","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Punctuation — Ellipses","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E2","q":"Which sentence correctly uses an ellipsis to show an omission or pause?","options":["I was going to say something, but... never mind.","I was going... to say something, but never mind...","I was... going to say... something but never mind.","I was going to say, something but never mind..."],"answer":0,"exp":"An ellipsis (three dots) can show a pause or trailing off in thought: \"...but... never mind.\" placed naturally where the thought is interrupted."},{"id":"sde82015","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Punctuation — Commas","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E2","q":"Which sentence demonstrates correct comma usage with a non-restrictive (non-essential) clause?","options":["My brother who lives in Sydney is visiting next week.","My brother, who lives in Sydney, is visiting next week.","My brother who, lives in Sydney is visiting, next week.","My brother lives, in Sydney who, is visiting next week."],"answer":1,"exp":"A non-restrictive clause (extra, non-essential information) should be set off with commas on both sides: \"My brother, who lives in Sydney, is visiting next week.\""},{"id":"sde82016","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Grammar — Gerunds","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E2","q":"Which word in this sentence functions as a gerund? 'Swimming is her favourite hobby.'","options":["is","her","favourite","Swimming"],"answer":3,"exp":"\"Swimming\" functions as a noun here (the subject of the sentence), making it a gerund — a verb form ending in '-ing' used as a noun."},{"id":"sde82017","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Grammar — Verb Tense","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E2","q":"Which sentence uses the present perfect tense correctly?","options":["I have visited Paris three times.","I visit Paris three times.","I am visiting Paris three times.","I will have visit Paris three times."],"answer":0,"exp":"Present perfect tense uses 'have/has' plus a past participle to describe an action that happened at an unspecified time in the past, often relevant to the present: \"I have visited Paris three times.\""},{"id":"sde82018","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Grammar — Subject-Verb Agreement","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E2","q":"Which sentence correctly demonstrates subject-verb agreement with a collective noun?","options":["The team are celebrating their win.","The team is celebrating its win.","The team is celebrating their win.","The teams is celebrating its win."],"answer":1,"exp":"In Australian English, collective nouns like 'team' are typically treated as singular, taking a singular verb ('is') and singular pronoun ('its')."},{"id":"sde82019","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Clauses","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E2","q":"Which sentence contains a noun clause functioning as the object of the verb?","options":["I believe that he is telling the truth.","The man who called is my uncle.","She left because she was tired.","Running quickly, she caught the bus."],"answer":0,"exp":"\"That he is telling the truth\" functions as the object of the verb 'believe', making it a noun clause."},{"id":"sde82020","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Punctuation — Semicolons","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E2","q":"Which sentence demonstrates the correct use of a semicolon to separate items in a complex list?","options":["I have lived in Sydney, Australia; Auckland, New Zealand; and Suva, Fiji.","I have lived in Sydney; Australia, Auckland; New Zealand, and Suva; Fiji.","I have lived in, Sydney Australia; Auckland New Zealand; and Suva Fiji.","I have lived in Sydney, Australia, Auckland, New Zealand, and Suva, Fiji; only."],"answer":0,"exp":"When list items themselves contain commas, semicolons can separate the larger items clearly: \"Sydney, Australia; Auckland, New Zealand; and Suva, Fiji.\""},{"id":"sde82021","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Grammar — Verb Tense","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E2","q":"Which sentence correctly uses the future perfect tense?","options":["By next year, I will have graduated from university.","By next year, I graduate from university.","By next year, I am graduating from university.","By next year, I will graduate from university."],"answer":0,"exp":"Future perfect tense uses 'will have' plus a past participle to describe an action that will be completed before a specific point in the future: \"I will have graduated...\""},{"id":"sde82022","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Punctuation — Comma Splices","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E2","q":"Which sentence avoids a comma splice (an error joining two independent clauses with only a comma)?","options":["I was tired, I went to bed early.","I was tired; I went to bed early.","I was tired I went to bed early.","I was, tired, I went, to bed, early."],"answer":1,"exp":"A semicolon (or a coordinating conjunction) correctly joins two independent clauses, avoiding the comma splice error of joining them with only a comma."},{"id":"sde82023","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Commonly Confused Words","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E2","q":"Which sentence uses 'its' and \"it's\" correctly?","options":["Its a beautiful day, and the dog wagged it's tail.","It's a beautiful day, and the dog wagged its tail.","Its a beautiful day, and the dog wagged its tail.","It's a beautiful day, and the dog wagged it's tail."],"answer":1,"exp":"\"It's\" (a contraction of 'it is') correctly starts the sentence, while \"its\" (showing possession, no apostrophe) correctly describes the dog's tail."},{"id":"sde82024","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Grammar — Participial Phrases","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E2","q":"Which sentence demonstrates correct use of a participial phrase?","options":["Exhausted from the long hike, the hikers collapsed onto their sleeping bags.","The hikers, exhausted from the long, hike collapsed onto their sleeping bags.","Exhausted, from the long hike the hikers collapsed onto, their sleeping bags.","The hikers collapsed exhausted, from the long hike onto their sleeping bags."],"answer":0,"exp":"\"Exhausted from the long hike\" is a participial phrase correctly placed at the start, clearly modifying 'the hikers' who follow it."},{"id":"sde82025","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Grammar — Appositives","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E2","q":"Which sentence correctly uses an appositive (a noun phrase that renames another noun)?","options":["My teacher, Mrs Chen, assigned extra homework.","My teacher Mrs Chen, assigned, extra homework.","My, teacher Mrs Chen assigned extra homework.","My teacher Mrs, Chen assigned extra, homework."],"answer":0,"exp":"\"Mrs Chen\" is an appositive renaming 'my teacher', correctly set off with commas on both sides: \"My teacher, Mrs Chen, assigned extra homework.\""},{"id":"sde83001","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E3","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'pragmatic'?","options":["idealistic","sensible and practical","emotional","careless"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Sensible and practical\" matches the meaning of 'pragmatic', describing a realistic, results-focused approach."},{"id":"sde83002","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E3","q":"Which word is the opposite of 'redundant'?","options":["unnecessary","essential","repetitive","excessive"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Essential\" is the opposite of 'redundant', which describes something no longer needed because it's unnecessary or excessive."},{"id":"sde83003","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Word Origins — Roots","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E3","q":"The root word 'mal-' usually relates to which concept?","options":["good","bad","large","small"],"answer":1,"exp":"The root 'mal-' relates to something bad or wrong, as in 'malfunction' (to function badly) or 'malnutrition' (poor nutrition)."},{"id":"sde83004","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Word Origins — Suffixes","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E3","q":"The suffix '-cracy' usually relates to which concept?","options":["government or rule","speed","colour","sound"],"answer":0,"exp":"The suffix '-cracy' relates to government or rule, as in 'democracy' (rule by the people) or 'autocracy' (rule by one person)."},{"id":"sde83005","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Persuasive and Rhetorical Techniques","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E3","q":"A speaker uses the phrase 'Let us rise, let us fight, let us win' in a speech. What persuasive technique combines repetition with a building intensity here?","options":["a tricolon (a group of three parallel phrases)","onomatopoeia","a simile","a counter-argument"],"answer":0,"exp":"A tricolon uses three parallel phrases in succession, often building intensity, as seen in \"let us rise, let us fight, let us win\"."},{"id":"sde83006","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E3","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'cynical'?","options":["hopeful","distrustful of others' motives","generous","naive"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Distrustful of others' motives\" matches the meaning of 'cynical', describing a sceptical view of people's sincerity."},{"id":"sde83007","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Persuasive and Rhetorical Techniques","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E3","q":"A writer states, 'Every parent who truly cares about their child's future will support this policy.' What persuasive (and potentially flawed) technique is this?","options":["a statistic","a false dilemma, implying only one reasonable position exists","alliteration","a direct quote"],"answer":1,"exp":"This statement implies that disagreeing means not caring about your child, creating a false dilemma that unfairly narrows the options to just two extremes."},{"id":"sde83008","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E3","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'vindicate'?","options":["to accuse falsely","to clear of blame or justify","to confuse","to ignore"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"To clear of blame or justify\" matches the meaning of 'vindicate', which means to show that someone or something was right or justified."},{"id":"sde83009","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Word Origins — Prefixes","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E3","q":"The prefix 'omni-' usually relates to which concept?","options":["none","all or everywhere","one","far away"],"answer":1,"exp":"The prefix 'omni-' relates to 'all' or 'everywhere', as in 'omnivore' (eats all types of food) or 'omnipresent' (present everywhere)."},{"id":"sde83010","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E3","q":"Which word is the opposite of 'benevolent'?","options":["kind","generous","malevolent","helpful"],"answer":2,"exp":"\"Malevolent\" is the opposite of 'benevolent', which describes a kind, well-meaning disposition."},{"id":"sde83011","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Persuasive and Rhetorical Techniques","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E3","q":"A politician says, 'My opponent wants to bankrupt this country' without addressing the actual details of their opponent's policy. What technique is this?","options":["a straw man argument, misrepresenting the opponent's actual position","a statistic","an appeal to authority","onomatopoeia"],"answer":0,"exp":"A straw man argument misrepresents or exaggerates an opponent's position to make it easier to attack, rather than engaging with their actual policy."},{"id":"sde83012","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E3","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'eloquent'?","options":["clumsy with words","fluent and persuasive in speech or writing","silent","confused"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Fluent and persuasive in speech or writing\" matches the meaning of 'eloquent', describing skilful, expressive communication."},{"id":"sde83013","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Persuasive and Rhetorical Techniques","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E3","q":"A persuasive text claims, 'Renowned scientists agree this approach is best' without naming any specific scientist or study. What technique is this an example of?","options":["a vague appeal to authority","a rhetorical question","repetition","a counter-argument"],"answer":0,"exp":"This is a vague appeal to authority, referencing unnamed experts to add credibility without providing any specific, checkable evidence."},{"id":"sde83014","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Word Origins — Roots","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E3","q":"The root word 'dict' relates to which concept?","options":["speaking or saying","seeing","hearing","moving"],"answer":0,"exp":"The root 'dict' relates to speaking or saying, as in 'dictate' (to speak aloud for someone to write down) or 'predict' (to say beforehand)."},{"id":"sde83015","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E3","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'ubiquitous'?","options":["rare","present everywhere","hidden","dangerous"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Present everywhere\" matches the meaning of 'ubiquitous', describing something found absolutely everywhere."},{"id":"sde83016","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Persuasive and Rhetorical Techniques","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E3","q":"A speaker repeatedly raises their voice and uses urgent language about a 'crisis' to discourage careful, calm analysis of an issue. What technique is this most closely associated with?","options":["fear-based persuasion (appeal to fear)","a logical syllogism","an objective summary","a neutral comparison"],"answer":0,"exp":"Using urgent, alarming language to provoke fear and discourage calm analysis is a recognised persuasive technique known as an appeal to fear."},{"id":"sde83017","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E3","q":"Which word is the opposite of 'meticulous'?","options":["careful","precise","careless","thorough"],"answer":2,"exp":"\"Careless\" is the opposite of 'meticulous', which describes great attention to detail and precision."},{"id":"sde83018","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Word Origins — Suffixes","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E3","q":"The suffix '-ology' usually relates to which concept?","options":["the study of a subject","the size of something","a type of disease only","a measurement of time"],"answer":0,"exp":"The suffix '-ology' relates to the study of a subject, as in 'biology' (the study of living things) or 'geology' (the study of the Earth)."},{"id":"sde83019","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E3","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'conviction' (as in 'spoke with conviction')?","options":["confusion","firm belief or certainty","hesitation","apology"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Firm belief or certainty\" matches the meaning of 'conviction' in this context, describing speaking with strong, confident belief."},{"id":"sde83020","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Persuasive and Rhetorical Techniques","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E3","q":"A writer compares a complex tax policy to 'a recipe with too many confusing ingredients' to help readers understand it. What technique is this?","options":["an analogy","a statistic","an appeal to fear","onomatopoeia"],"answer":0,"exp":"An analogy compares something unfamiliar (a tax policy) to something familiar (a recipe), helping readers understand a complex idea more easily."},{"id":"sde83021","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E3","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'arbitrary'?","options":["carefully planned","based on random choice rather than reason","extremely rare","completely fair"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Based on random choice rather than reason\" matches the meaning of 'arbitrary', describing a decision made without clear logical basis."},{"id":"sde83022","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Word Origins — Prefixes","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E3","q":"The prefix 'inter-' usually relates to which concept?","options":["between or among","above","below","after"],"answer":0,"exp":"The prefix 'inter-' relates to 'between' or 'among', as in 'international' (between nations) or 'interact' (to act between/among people)."},{"id":"sde83023","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E3","q":"Which word is the opposite of 'concur'?","options":["agree","disagree","decide","explain"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Disagree\" is the opposite of 'concur', which means to agree with an opinion or decision."},{"id":"sde83024","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Persuasive and Rhetorical Techniques","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E3","q":"A persuasive speech ends with the line, 'The time for talk is over. The time for action is now.' What technique is being used here?","options":["a logical fallacy only","an antithesis (contrasting two ideas in a balanced structure)","an irrelevant statistic","a direct quote from research"],"answer":1,"exp":"This is an antithesis, contrasting two ideas ('talk' versus 'action') in a balanced grammatical structure for persuasive effect."},{"id":"sde83025","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E3","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'tenuous' (as in a 'tenuous connection')?","options":["extremely strong","weak or flimsy","completely certain","obvious"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Weak or flimsy\" matches the meaning of 'tenuous', describing something only loosely or weakly connected."},{"id":"sde84001","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E4","q":"Read: 'The Disappearing Languages\n\nOf the roughly 7,000 languages spoken around the world today, linguists estimate that nearly half are at risk of disappearing entirely within the next century. Some have only a handful of fluent speakers remaining, often elderly, with no younger generation learning to speak them fluently in turn.\n\nThe causes of language loss are varied, but a common pattern emerges: as smaller communities are drawn into larger economic and social systems, children increasingly grow up speaking the dominant regional or national language, finding fewer practical reasons to learn their grandparents' language fluently. Schools, media, and employment opportunities overwhelmingly favour dominant languages, creating powerful incentives that smaller languages simply cannot compete with on practical grounds alone.\n\nWhy does this matter, beyond a vague sense of cultural loss? Linguists argue that each language encodes unique ways of categorising the world — distinct grammatical structures, specialised vocabulary for local plants, animals, and weather patterns, and culturally specific concepts that don't translate neatly into other languages. When a language disappears, this entire framework for understanding the world disappears with it, not simply a collection of words that could, in theory, be translated elsewhere.\n\nEfforts to document and revive endangered languages have grown substantially in recent decades. Linguists now race to record fluent elderly speakers before knowledge is lost entirely, while some communities have established immersion schools specifically aimed at raising new generations of fluent speakers. Hawaiian and Māori are often cited as partial success stories, having seen meaningful revival after periods of serious decline, though both remain considerably less widely spoken than they once were.\n\nThese efforts face real obstacles, however. Documentation alone cannot replace genuine, everyday fluency, and revival programs require sustained funding, community commitment, and time — resources not every endangered language community can access. Whether these efforts can meaningfully slow the broader, global pattern of language loss remains, even among optimistic linguists, a genuinely open question.'\n\nWhat proportion of the world's languages are estimated to be at risk of disappearing within the next century?","options":["a small fraction","nearly half","almost all of them","only languages with no written form"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage states linguists estimate that 'nearly half are at risk of disappearing entirely within the next century'."},{"id":"sde84002","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E4","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nAccording to the passage, why do children in many communities increasingly grow up not speaking their grandparents' language fluently?","options":["they are forbidden from learning it","dominant languages offer stronger practical incentives through schools, media, and employment","they find the language too difficult to pronounce","grandparents refuse to teach them"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage states that 'schools, media, and employment opportunities overwhelmingly favour dominant languages, creating powerful incentives that smaller languages simply cannot compete with'."},{"id":"sde84003","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E4","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nAccording to linguists quoted in the passage, why does losing a language matter beyond a 'vague sense of cultural loss'?","options":["it only affects tourism revenue","each language encodes a unique way of categorising and understanding the world","languages have no real practical value at all","it only matters for written literature"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage states that linguists argue 'each language encodes unique ways of categorising the world', which is lost along with the language itself."},{"id":"sde84004","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E4","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat are Hawaiian and Māori described as examples of in the fourth paragraph?","options":["languages that have completely disappeared","languages that have never been at risk","partial revival success stories, despite remaining less widely spoken than before","languages spoken only by linguists"],"answer":2,"exp":"The passage describes them as 'partial success stories, having seen meaningful revival after periods of serious decline, though both remain considerably less widely spoken than they once were'."},{"id":"sde84005","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E4","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat obstacles to language revival are mentioned in the final paragraph?","options":["a lack of interest from linguists","documentation alone cannot replace genuine fluency, and programs require funding, commitment, and time","governments actively prevent all revival efforts","there are no real obstacles mentioned"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage states that 'documentation alone cannot replace genuine, everyday fluency, and revival programs require sustained funding, community commitment, and time'."},{"id":"sde84006","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Vocabulary in Context","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E4","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat does the word 'encodes' mean in the third paragraph?","options":["destroys completely","contains or represents in a particular structured form","translates directly","ignores entirely"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Encodes\" means to contain or represent something in a particular structured form — in this case, a language containing unique ways of understanding the world."},{"id":"sde84007","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Interpreting Mood","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E4","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhich best describes the writer's overall tone regarding the future of endangered languages?","options":["entirely optimistic, with no concerns raised at all","balanced, acknowledging both genuine revival efforts and real ongoing challenges","completely pessimistic, suggesting nothing can be done","dismissive of the entire issue as unimportant"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage acknowledges genuine revival efforts and partial successes, while also honestly noting 'real obstacles' and describing the overall outcome as 'a genuinely open question'."},{"id":"sde84008","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Author's Purpose","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E4","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat is the main purpose of this passage?","options":["to persuade readers that only Hawaiian and Māori deserve government funding","to inform readers about the causes, significance, and challenges of language loss and revival","to provide a step-by-step guide to learning an endangered language","to argue that language loss has no real consequences"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage provides balanced factual information about why languages disappear, why this matters, and the challenges and partial successes of revival efforts."},{"id":"sde84009","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E4","q":"Read: 'Migration\n\nEvery autumn, my grandmother says,\nthe birds outside her window simply know —\nno map unfolded across a kitchen table,\nno compass needle trembling north to go.\n\nI think of her at twenty-three, one suitcase,\na language she half-knew folded in her mouth,\narriving somewhere colder than she'd pictured,\nfurther from whatever she once called south.\n\nDid she know, the way the swallows seem to know,\nsome certainty pulling at an inner thread?\nOr was it simpler — closer to just hoping,\na single step before the next instead.\n\nForty years on, she watches autumn gather\nthe same birds rising over the same grey roofs,\nand says, again, that they simply know the way,\nas if she'd half-forgotten her own proof —\n\nthat knowing, mostly, comes after the arriving,\nstitched together backward, made to seem\nlike something always certain, always simple,\nthe kind of story only distance lets you dream.'\n\nWhat does the speaker's grandmother claim about the birds in the first stanza?","options":["that they get lost every year","that they simply know where to go, without any tools to guide them","that they are guided by a kitchen map","that they never actually migrate"],"answer":1,"exp":"The poem states the grandmother believes the birds 'simply know' the way, with 'no map' and 'no compass'."},{"id":"sde84010","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Inference","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E4","q":"Read the same poem.\n\nWhat event from the grandmother's past does the second stanza describe?","options":["a holiday she took for fun","her migration/move to a new country as a young woman, with only one suitcase","her wedding day","a dream she once had"],"answer":1,"exp":"The second stanza describes her 'at twenty-three, one suitcase' arriving 'somewhere colder than she'd pictured', suggesting a significant migration to a new place."},{"id":"sde84011","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Inference","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E4","q":"Read the same poem.\n\nIn the third stanza, what question does the speaker raise about the grandmother's original journey?","options":["whether she regrets the journey","whether she knew where she was going with certainty, or was simply hoping and taking it one step at a time","whether she ever returned home","whether she travelled alone or with others"],"answer":1,"exp":"The speaker wonders whether the grandmother had 'some certainty pulling at an inner thread' like the birds, or whether 'it was simpler — closer to just hoping'."},{"id":"sde84012","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Inference","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E4","q":"Read the same poem.\n\nWhat does the final stanza suggest about how we understand our own past decisions?","options":["our past decisions are always perfectly clear at the time we make them","understanding or 'knowing' often comes only afterward, reshaped by hindsight into something that feels more certain than it was","memory is always completely accurate","the grandmother regrets her entire journey"],"answer":1,"exp":"The final stanza suggests \"knowing, mostly, comes after the arriving, stitched together backward\", implying our sense of certainty about past decisions is often constructed in hindsight."},{"id":"sde84013","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Writer's Craft","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E4","q":"Read the same poem.\n\nWhat is the effect of comparing the grandmother's migration to the birds' migration throughout the poem?","options":["it suggests her journey was meaningless","it draws a parallel between instinctive natural behaviour and a deeply uncertain, very human decision, questioning whether her journey was as 'instinctive' as it now seems","it proves that humans and birds migrate for identical reasons","it has no real purpose in the poem"],"answer":1,"exp":"This comparison invites the reader to question whether the grandmother's journey was truly as instinctive and certain as the birds' migration seems, or whether that certainty was only added in hindsight."},{"id":"sde84014","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Writer's Craft","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E4","q":"Read the same poem.\n\nWhat literary device is used in the phrase 'a language she half-knew folded in her mouth'?","options":["a literal description with no figurative meaning","a metaphor, describing an unfamiliar language as something physically folded inside her","onomatopoeia","alliteration only"],"answer":1,"exp":"This metaphor describes the unfamiliar language as something physically 'folded' inside her mouth, capturing the awkward, compact, half-formed nature of speaking a language she didn't yet fully know."},{"id":"sde84015","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Author's Purpose","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E4","q":"Read the same poem.\n\nWhich best describes the overall theme of this poem?","options":["the simple joy of watching birds migrate each year","the way certainty and meaning in difficult decisions are often only constructed afterward, through the distance of time and memory","the importance of owning a good suitcase when travelling","a factual account of bird migration patterns"],"answer":1,"exp":"The poem explores how a sense of certainty about difficult past decisions (like migration) is often only created in hindsight, reshaped by memory and distance."},{"id":"sde84016","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Evaluating Evidence","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E4","q":"Read the same poem.\n\nWhich phrase from the poem best supports the idea that the grandmother's journey involved genuine uncertainty, not pure instinct?","options":["\"the birds outside her window simply know\"","\"a single step before the next instead\"","\"the same birds rising over the same grey roofs\"","\"no map unfolded across a kitchen table\""],"answer":1,"exp":"\"A single step before the next instead\" suggests a tentative, uncertain process of moving forward without full certainty, contrasting with the birds' instinctive knowing."},{"id":"sde84017","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Figurative Language","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E4","q":"What is an extended metaphor?","options":["a single brief comparison used once","a metaphor that is developed and continued across multiple lines or an entire piece of writing","a comparison using 'like' or 'as'","a metaphor that only appears in poetry titles"],"answer":1,"exp":"An extended metaphor is developed and continued across multiple lines, or even an entire poem, rather than appearing as a single brief comparison."},{"id":"sde84018","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Figurative Language","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E4","q":"Which of these is an example of irony?","options":["A fire station burns down.","A dog barks loudly at night.","Rain falls during a storm.","A student studies for a test."],"answer":0,"exp":"It is ironic for a fire station — a place meant to prevent and fight fires — to itself burn down, creating a contrast between expectation and reality."},{"id":"sde84019","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Vocabulary and Meaning","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E4","q":"What is the term for the implied or suggested meaning of a word, beyond its literal dictionary definition?","options":["denotation","connotation","alliteration","onomatopoeia"],"answer":1,"exp":"Connotation refers to the implied or emotional meaning associated with a word, beyond its literal dictionary definition (denotation)."},{"id":"sde84020","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Vocabulary and Meaning","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E4","q":"Which word would have a more negative connotation than 'frugal', despite a similar literal meaning?","options":["thrifty","economical","stingy","careful"],"answer":2,"exp":"\"Stingy\" carries a more negative connotation than 'frugal', even though both relate to being careful with money."},{"id":"sde84021","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Literary Terms","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E4","q":"What is a 'motif' in literature?","options":["the main character of a story","a recurring image, symbol, or idea that appears throughout a text","the setting of a story","the final twist in a plot"],"answer":1,"exp":"A motif is a recurring image, symbol, or idea that appears repeatedly throughout a text, often reinforcing a theme."},{"id":"sde84022","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Poetry Terms","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E4","q":"In poetry, what is 'enjambment'?","options":["a rhyme at the end of every line","when a sentence or phrase continues onto the next line without a pause or punctuation mark","a poem with no title","a type of metaphor only"],"answer":1,"exp":"Enjambment occurs when a sentence or phrase runs on from one line of poetry to the next without a pause, rather than ending neatly at the line break."},{"id":"sde84023","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Writer's Craft","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E4","q":"What is the effect of using short, fragmented sentences in a tense scene of a story?","options":["it usually slows the pace and creates a relaxed mood","it can create urgency, tension, or a feeling of breathlessness","it always indicates a happy ending","it has no real effect on the reader"],"answer":1,"exp":"Short, fragmented sentences often speed up the pace of reading, which can create a sense of urgency, tension, or breathlessness in a scene."},{"id":"sde84024","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Literary Terms","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E4","q":"What is a 'symbol' in literature?","options":["a word that rhymes with another","an object, person, or image that represents a deeper meaning beyond its literal self","the title of a poem","a type of punctuation mark"],"answer":1,"exp":"A symbol is an object, person, or image that represents a deeper meaning or idea beyond its literal, surface-level self."},{"id":"sde84025","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Writer's Craft","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E4","q":"Which sentence demonstrates juxtaposition (placing two contrasting ideas close together for effect)?","options":["The cat sat quietly on the warm windowsill.","The bustling, chaotic market square sat beside the silent, empty cathedral.","She walked slowly down the street.","The sky was a clear, pale blue."],"answer":1,"exp":"Placing the 'bustling, chaotic market square' directly beside the 'silent, empty cathedral' creates juxtaposition, highlighting the contrast between the two scenes."},{"id":"sde91001","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E1","q":"Read: 'The Substitute\n\nEli had covered for absent colleagues a hundred times before, but never for a subject he'd actively avoided since his own school years. \"It's just supervision,\" the principal had said, not quite meeting his eyes. \"The students are working through a unit independently. You won't need to teach anything.\" This had turned out to be only partially true.\n\nWithin ten minutes, a girl in the back row raised her hand with a question about quadratic functions that Eli understood, in the abstract, was something he should know. He didn't. He said as much, which surprised her more than his answer would have. \"Most subs just make something up,\" she said, not unkindly. \"Or they pretend they're 'letting us figure it out ourselves.'\"\n\nWhat followed was not, by any reasonable measure, a successful lesson. Eli admitted his own confusion, then suggested they work through the problem together, using nothing but the textbook and a willingness to be visibly, uncomfortably wrong in front of fifteen sceptical fourteen-year-olds. Several students seemed to find this more interesting than any actual lesson on the topic. One pointed out, with the particular cruelty of teenagers, that he was \"worse at this than literally anyone in this room.\" She wasn't wrong.\n\nBy the end of the period, they had not fully solved the original problem, but had made what Eli considered genuine progress, partly through the textbook and partly through a particularly patient student named Marcus, who seemed to enjoy the novel experience of explaining something to an adult who was paying real attention. Eli left the classroom with no illusions about having taught mathematics that day. He had, perhaps, taught something else — though he couldn't have said exactly what, and suspected it wouldn't show up on any test.'\n\nWhy did Eli initially expect the substitute role to be straightforward?","options":["he had taught this exact subject many times before","the principal told him it was 'just supervision' and that he wouldn't need to teach anything","he had specifically requested this assignment","the students had warned him it would be easy"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage states the principal told him 'it's just supervision' and that 'you won't need to teach anything'."},{"id":"sde91002","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Inference","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat does the student's comment about subs 'pretending they're letting us figure it out ourselves' suggest about her past experiences?","options":["she has never had a substitute teacher before","she has previously encountered substitutes who disguised their own lack of knowledge","she believes all substitute teachers are highly skilled","she has no opinion about substitute teachers"],"answer":1,"exp":"This comment suggests she has seen this evasive pattern before, recognising it as a common cover for a substitute's own uncertainty."},{"id":"sde91003","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nHow did Eli respond when he didn't know the answer to the student's question?","options":["he made up an answer to avoid embarrassment","he admitted his confusion honestly and suggested working through it together","he refused to engage with the question at all","he sent the student to another teacher"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage states Eli 'admitted his own confusion, then suggested they work through the problem together'."},{"id":"sde91004","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat role did Marcus play in the events of the passage?","options":["he caused the disruption in class","he patiently helped explain the problem to Eli","he was the principal's assistant","he refused to participate in the lesson"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage describes Marcus as 'a particularly patient student... who seemed to enjoy the novel experience of explaining something to an adult who was paying real attention'."},{"id":"sde91005","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Inference","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat does the final paragraph suggest Eli actually accomplished that day, despite not teaching mathematics successfully?","options":["nothing at all of value","something harder to define, possibly related to honesty or genuine engagement, though the passage doesn't specify exactly what","he successfully taught the entire unit on quadratic functions","he convinced the students to dislike mathematics even more"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage states he 'had, perhaps, taught something else — though he couldn't have said exactly what', suggesting an intangible but real outcome distinct from the maths content itself."},{"id":"sde91006","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Writer's Craft","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat is the effect of the phrase 'with the particular cruelty of teenagers' in the third paragraph?","options":["it suggests genuine, serious cruelty intended to harm Eli","it uses a knowing, slightly humorous tone to describe a typically blunt teenage comment, without implying real malice","it proves the student hated Eli personally","it has no real effect on the reader"],"answer":1,"exp":"This phrase uses a knowing, wry tone to describe the bluntness typical of teenage honesty, without suggesting the comment was meant with genuine malice."},{"id":"sde91007","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Text Structure","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhich best describes the overall structure of this passage?","options":["a character fails completely with no redeeming outcome","a character experiences an unexpected, humbling situation that leads to an ambiguous but meaningful outcome","a straightforward, successful lesson with no complications","an argument for why substitute teachers should always know every subject"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage follows Eli through an unexpected, humbling classroom experience that, despite not achieving its original academic goal, leads to a genuine if hard-to-define positive outcome."},{"id":"sde91008","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Vocabulary in Context","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat does the word 'sceptical' mean in the third paragraph?","options":["fully trusting and convinced","doubtful or unconvinced","extremely excited","completely indifferent"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Sceptical\" means doubtful or unconvinced, describing the students' likely attitude toward Eli's ability to help them."},{"id":"sde91009","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E1","q":"Read: 'Should Voting Be Compulsory for Young People?\n\nAustralia is one of a relatively small number of countries with compulsory voting, a system that has shaped its political culture in ways often invisible to those who have never experienced the alternative. As debates continue in various countries about lowering the voting age to sixteen, a related question deserves equal attention: should voting itself be made compulsory for younger citizens once they become eligible?\n\nProponents of compulsory voting for young people argue it would address one of the most persistent patterns in electoral politics worldwide: chronically low youth turnout in voluntary voting systems. When voting is optional, younger citizens — busy, often transient, frequently less attached to a fixed electorate — vote at consistently lower rates than older generations. This creates a feedback loop, proponents argue: politicians, rationally responding to who actually votes, tend to prioritise the concerns of older, more reliable voting blocs, further alienating younger citizens who see their interests consistently deprioritised.\n\nCritics raise a more fundamental objection: that voting is properly understood as a right, and rights, almost by definition, include the right not to exercise them. Forcing political participation, they argue, sits uneasily with the broader principle of individual liberty in a democracy, regardless of whether the policy goal (higher youth engagement) is laudable. Some critics also question whether compulsion produces genuine engagement at all, or merely produces uninformed, resentful votes cast purely to avoid a fine — arguably worse for democratic health than honest abstention.\n\nDefenders of compulsory voting counter that this critique, while philosophically coherent, may overstate the practical distinction between a 'right' and a 'civic duty'. Jury duty, they note, is compulsory in many democracies despite also being framed as participation in a fundamental civic institution; few object to this on the same philosophical grounds. Whether voting is meaningfully different from jury duty in this respect remains genuinely contested, rather than self-evident.\n\nWhat seems clearest, amid this disagreement, is that the debate over compulsory voting for young people sits at the intersection of two legitimate democratic values — broad political participation, and individual liberty — that do not always point in the same direction. Resolving this tension may say as much about a society's underlying political philosophy as it does about voter turnout statistics.'\n\nWhat pattern do proponents of compulsory voting for young people identify in voluntary voting systems?","options":["young people vote at higher rates than older generations","youth turnout is chronically low compared to older generations","voting rates are identical across all age groups","compulsory voting has never been tried anywhere"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage states proponents point to 'chronically low youth turnout in voluntary voting systems' as a persistent pattern."},{"id":"sde91010","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat 'feedback loop' do proponents describe regarding politicians' behaviour?","options":["politicians ignore all voters equally","politicians prioritise the concerns of older, more reliable voting blocs, further alienating younger citizens","politicians always favour younger voters","there is no connection between voter turnout and political priorities"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage describes politicians 'rationally responding to who actually votes', tending 'to prioritise the concerns of older, more reliable voting blocs, further alienating younger citizens'."},{"id":"sde91011","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat is the critics' more 'fundamental objection' to compulsory voting, beyond practical concerns?","options":["that voting takes too much time","that voting is properly understood as a right, which inherently includes the right not to exercise it","that young people are incapable of voting responsibly","that compulsory voting is too expensive to administer"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage states critics argue 'voting is properly understood as a right, and rights, almost by definition, include the right not to exercise them'."},{"id":"sde91012","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Persuasive Techniques","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhy do defenders of compulsory voting bring up jury duty in the fourth paragraph?","options":["to argue that jury duty should also be abolished","to suggest that compulsory civic duties (like jury duty) are widely accepted elsewhere, challenging the idea that voting must be entirely voluntary as a 'right'","to prove that voting and jury duty are completely unrelated","to argue that young people should be exempt from jury duty"],"answer":1,"exp":"By comparing voting to jury duty (another compulsory civic institution that's widely accepted), defenders challenge the idea that compulsion is automatically incompatible with something being a 'right'."},{"id":"sde91013","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Author's Purpose","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat is the writer's own conclusion in the final paragraph?","options":["compulsory voting for young people is clearly correct and should be implemented immediately","the debate involves a genuine tension between two legitimate democratic values, without an obviously correct resolution","critics of compulsory voting are entirely wrong","the issue has nothing to do with political philosophy"],"answer":1,"exp":"The writer concludes that the debate 'sits at the intersection of two legitimate democratic values... that do not always point in the same direction', without declaring one side simply correct."},{"id":"sde91014","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Vocabulary in Context","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat does the word 'laudable' mean in the third paragraph?","options":["worthy of praise","completely false","extremely loud","controversial and divisive"],"answer":0,"exp":"\"Laudable\" means worthy of praise, describing how critics acknowledge the GOAL of higher youth engagement, even while objecting to the method of compulsion."},{"id":"sde91015","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Text Structure","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhich best describes the overall structure of this passage?","options":["a one-sided persuasive essay arguing strongly for one position","a balanced exploration of multiple perspectives on a genuinely contested issue, without declaring a single 'winner'","a simple factual report with no differing viewpoints","a personal narrative about the writer's own voting experience"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage presents both proponents' and critics' arguments, along with a response and counter-response, concluding that the tension reflects genuinely competing values rather than declaring one side simply correct."},{"id":"sde91016","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E1","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'transient' (as in 'transient lifestyle')?","options":["permanent","temporary or short-lived","extremely wealthy","completely settled"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Temporary or short-lived\" matches the meaning of 'transient', describing something that doesn't last or stay in one place long."},{"id":"sde91017","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E1","q":"Which word is the opposite of 'coherent'?","options":["logical","clear","confusing or disjointed","organised"],"answer":2,"exp":"\"Confusing or disjointed\" is the opposite of 'coherent', which describes something logical and clearly connected."},{"id":"sde91018","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E1","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'contested' (as in a 'contested issue')?","options":["universally agreed upon","disputed or argued over","completely irrelevant","clearly resolved"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Disputed or argued over\" matches the meaning of 'contested', describing something still actively debated."},{"id":"sde91019","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E1","q":"Which word is the opposite of 'self-evident'?","options":["obvious","clear","requiring proof or argument to establish","instantly recognisable"],"answer":2,"exp":"\"Requiring proof or argument to establish\" is the opposite of 'self-evident', which describes something obviously true without needing explanation."},{"id":"sde91020","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E1","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'deprioritised'?","options":["given top priority","given lower priority or importance","completely ignored forever","celebrated"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Given lower priority or importance\" matches the meaning of 'deprioritised', describing something pushed down the list of importance."},{"id":"sde91021","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E1","q":"Which word is the opposite of 'alienating'?","options":["welcoming or including","excluding","confusing","distancing"],"answer":0,"exp":"\"Welcoming or including\" is the opposite of 'alienating', which describes making someone feel excluded or distant."},{"id":"sde91022","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E1","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'philosophically coherent'?","options":["logically consistent within a system of ideas","completely random","emotionally driven only","scientifically proven"],"answer":0,"exp":"\"Logically consistent within a system of ideas\" matches the meaning here, describing an argument that holds together logically within its own framework."},{"id":"sde91023","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E1","q":"Which word is the opposite of 'compulsory'?","options":["mandatory","required","optional","essential"],"answer":2,"exp":"\"Optional\" is the opposite of 'compulsory', which describes something required rather than a free choice."},{"id":"sde91024","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E1","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'persistent' (as in a 'persistent pattern')?","options":["temporary","continuing over a long time, without stopping","completely random","rare"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Continuing over a long time, without stopping\" matches the meaning of 'persistent', describing something that keeps occurring repeatedly."},{"id":"sde91025","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E1","q":"Which word is the opposite of 'genuine' (as in 'genuine engagement')?","options":["authentic","sincere","fake or insincere","honest"],"answer":2,"exp":"\"Fake or insincere\" is the opposite of 'genuine', which describes something authentic and real."},{"id":"sde92001","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Grammar — Subjunctive Mood","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E2","q":"Which sentence correctly demonstrates the use of the subjunctive mood in a formal recommendation?","options":["I recommend that he attends the meeting.","I recommend that he attend the meeting.","I recommend that he will attend the meeting.","I recommend that he attended the meeting."],"answer":1,"exp":"After verbs like 'recommend' expressing a wish or suggestion, the subjunctive uses the base form of the verb regardless of subject: \"I recommend that he attend the meeting.\""},{"id":"sde92002","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Clauses","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E2","q":"Identify the type of clause in this sentence: 'What she said surprised everyone in the room.'","options":["adjective clause","adverbial clause","noun clause functioning as the subject","independent clause only"],"answer":2,"exp":"\"What she said\" functions as the subject of the sentence, acting as a noun clause."},{"id":"sde92003","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Active and Passive Voice","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E2","q":"Which sentence demonstrates correct use of the passive voice to emphasise the action over the actor?","options":["The committee rejected the proposal.","The proposal was rejected.","The committee is rejecting the proposal.","The committee will reject the proposal."],"answer":1,"exp":"\"The proposal was rejected\" uses the passive voice and omits the actor entirely, placing full emphasis on the action and its result rather than who performed it."},{"id":"sde92004","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Clauses","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E2","q":"Which sentence contains a non-finite clause?","options":["She finished her homework before dinner.","To succeed in this field requires patience and persistence.","She is finishing her homework now.","She finished her homework, and then she relaxed."],"answer":1,"exp":"\"To succeed in this field\" is a non-finite clause (using an infinitive verb form), functioning as the subject of the sentence."},{"id":"sde92005","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Punctuation — Dashes","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E2","q":"Which sentence demonstrates the correct use of an em dash to indicate an abrupt change in thought?","options":["She was about to leave — then the phone rang.","She was, about to leave then, the phone — rang.","She was about — to leave then the phone rang.","She was about to leave then — the — phone rang."],"answer":0,"exp":"An em dash can indicate an abrupt break or change in thought, placed naturally where the interruption occurs: \"She was about to leave — then the phone rang.\""},{"id":"sde92006","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Grammar — Infinitives","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E2","q":"Which word in this sentence is functioning as an infinitive? 'She wants to travel next year.'","options":["wants","to travel","next","year"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"To travel\" is an infinitive — the base form of a verb preceded by 'to', functioning here as the object of 'wants'."},{"id":"sde92007","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Punctuation — Semicolons","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E2","q":"Which sentence correctly uses a semicolon to join two closely related independent clauses?","options":["The weather improved; we decided to go for a hike.","The weather improved, we decided to go for a hike.","The weather improved; and we decided to go for a hike.","The weather; improved we decided to go for a hike."],"answer":0,"exp":"A semicolon correctly joins two closely related independent clauses without needing a conjunction: \"The weather improved; we decided to go for a hike.\""},{"id":"sde92008","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Grammar — Gerunds","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E2","q":"Which sentence demonstrates correct use of a gerund phrase as the subject?","options":["Swimming every morning improved her fitness significantly.","She improved her fitness by swimming every morning.","Improved fitness, swimming every morning, was her goal.","Her fitness improved, swimming every morning was the cause."],"answer":0,"exp":"\"Swimming every morning\" functions as a gerund phrase acting as the subject of the sentence."},{"id":"sde92009","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Grammar — Parallel Structure","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E2","q":"Which sentence correctly demonstrates parallel structure in a complex list?","options":["The plan requires careful budgeting, clear communication, and to monitor progress regularly.","The plan requires careful budgeting, clear communication, and regular progress monitoring.","The plan requires to budget carefully, clear communication, and regular monitoring.","The plan requires careful budgeting, communicating clearly, and to monitor regularly."],"answer":1,"exp":"Parallel structure requires consistent grammatical form throughout the list: \"careful budgeting, clear communication, and regular progress monitoring\" all use a noun-phrase structure consistently."},{"id":"sde92010","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Grammar — Subjunctive Mood","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E2","q":"Which sentence demonstrates the correct use of the past subjunctive in a hypothetical statement?","options":["If she was taller, she would have made the team.","If she were taller, she would have made the team.","If she is taller, she would have made the team.","If she will be taller, she would have made the team."],"answer":1,"exp":"For hypothetical or contrary-to-fact statements introduced by 'if', the subjunctive uses 'were' rather than 'was': \"If she were taller...\""},{"id":"sde92011","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Grammar — Appositives","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E2","q":"Which sentence correctly demonstrates the use of an appositive phrase to add information concisely?","options":["My colleague Sarah, an experienced surgeon, led the operation.","My colleague, Sarah an experienced, surgeon led the operation.","My colleague Sarah an experienced surgeon, led, the operation.","My colleague, Sarah, an experienced, surgeon led the operation."],"answer":0,"exp":"\"An experienced surgeon\" is an appositive phrase, correctly set off with a comma, renaming and adding information about 'Sarah'."},{"id":"sde92012","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Grammar — Sentence Fragments","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E2","q":"Which sentence demonstrates a sentence fragment (an error)?","options":["Because the storm hit suddenly.","The storm hit suddenly.","Because the storm hit suddenly, we evacuated immediately.","The storm, which hit suddenly, caused significant damage."],"answer":0,"exp":"\"Because the storm hit suddenly\" is a sentence fragment — a dependent clause presented alone, without a main clause to complete the thought."},{"id":"sde92013","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Grammar — Who vs Whom","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E2","q":"Which sentence correctly uses the word 'whom' as the object of a preposition?","options":["To whom should I address this letter?","To who should I address this letter?","Whom should address this letter?","To whom did address this letter?"],"answer":0,"exp":"\"Whom\" is correct as the object of the preposition 'to': \"To whom should I address this letter?\""},{"id":"sde92014","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Punctuation — Colons","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E2","q":"Which sentence demonstrates the correct use of a colon to introduce a formal list?","options":["The committee approved three measures: funding, staffing, and oversight.","The committee approved three measures, funding: staffing, and oversight.","The committee approved: three measures funding, staffing, and oversight.","The committee approved three: measures funding, staffing, and oversight."],"answer":0,"exp":"A colon correctly introduces a formal list after a complete independent clause: \"The committee approved three measures: funding, staffing, and oversight.\""},{"id":"sde92015","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Grammar — Verb Tense","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E2","q":"Which sentence demonstrates correct use of the present perfect continuous tense?","options":["She has been working on this project for three months.","She works on this project for three months.","She worked on this project for three months.","She will work on this project for three months."],"answer":0,"exp":"Present perfect continuous tense uses 'has/have been' plus an '-ing' verb form to describe an ongoing action that started in the past and continues: \"She has been working...\""},{"id":"sde92016","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Grammar — Modifiers","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E2","q":"Which sentence avoids a dangling modifier?","options":["Having finished the report, the manager submitted it for approval.","Having finished the report, it was submitted for approval by the manager.","The report was submitted by the manager, having finished it.","Having finished, the report was submitted for approval."],"answer":0,"exp":"\"Having finished the report, the manager submitted it\" correctly places the modifying phrase next to 'the manager', who actually performed the finishing."},{"id":"sde92017","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Clauses","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E2","q":"Which sentence correctly demonstrates the use of an adverbial clause of concession?","options":["Although the evidence was weak, the jury reached a verdict.","Because the evidence was weak, the jury reached a verdict.","When the evidence was weak, the jury reached a verdict.","Where the evidence was weak, the jury reached a verdict."],"answer":0,"exp":"\"Although the evidence was weak\" is an adverbial clause of concession, acknowledging a contrasting point before the main clause."},{"id":"sde92018","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Grammar — Subject-Verb Agreement","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E2","q":"Which sentence demonstrates correct subject-verb agreement with an indefinite pronoun?","options":["Everyone in the class has submitted their assignment.","Everyone in the class have submitted their assignment.","Everyone in the class are submitting their assignment.","Everyone in the class were submitting their assignment."],"answer":0,"exp":"\"Everyone\" is treated as singular, requiring a singular verb form: \"Everyone... has submitted...\""},{"id":"sde92019","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Grammar — Sentence Structure","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E2","q":"Which sentence correctly demonstrates the use of a cleft sentence for emphasis?","options":["It was Sarah who solved the problem.","Sarah solved the problem, it was her.","It Sarah was who solved the problem.","Sarah was it who solved the problem."],"answer":0,"exp":"\"It was Sarah who solved the problem\" is a cleft sentence, restructuring the standard sentence to place emphasis specifically on 'Sarah'."},{"id":"sde92020","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Grammar — Pronoun Reference","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E2","q":"Which sentence correctly avoids ambiguous pronoun reference?","options":["When Sarah met Lucy, she gave her a book.","When Sarah met Lucy, Sarah gave Lucy a book.","She met her, and she gave her a book.","When Sarah met her, she gave her a book."],"answer":1,"exp":"Using the actual names \"Sarah gave Lucy a book\" avoids the ambiguity created by multiple unclear pronouns referring to two different female subjects."},{"id":"sde92021","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Grammar — Absolute Phrases","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E2","q":"Which sentence demonstrates the correct use of an absolute phrase?","options":["Her hands trembling, she opened the envelope.","Her hands, trembling she opened, the envelope.","Trembling her hands, she opened the envelope.","She opened the envelope, her hands trembling, was nervous."],"answer":0,"exp":"\"Her hands trembling\" is an absolute phrase, modifying the entire main clause rather than a single word, correctly placed at the start of the sentence."},{"id":"sde92022","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Commonly Confused Words","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E2","q":"Which sentence correctly demonstrates the distinction between 'affect' and 'effect'?","options":["The new policy will affect many employees, with significant effects on morale.","The new policy will effect many employees, with significant affects on morale.","The new policy will affect many employees, with significant affects on morale.","The new policy will effect many employees, with significant effects on morale, incorrectly."],"answer":0,"exp":"\"Affect\" is typically used as a verb (to influence), and \"effect\" is typically used as a noun (a result): \"will affect... with significant effects...\""},{"id":"sde92023","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Grammar — Absolute Phrases","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E2","q":"Which sentence demonstrates a correctly punctuated nominative absolute construction with no errors?","options":["The meeting concluded, everyone satisfied with the outcome.","The meeting, concluded everyone satisfied, with the outcome.","The meeting concluded everyone, satisfied with the outcome.","The meeting concluded everyone satisfied with the outcome no comma."],"answer":0,"exp":"\"The meeting concluded, everyone satisfied with the outcome\" correctly uses a comma to separate the main clause from the absolute phrase describing the resulting state."},{"id":"sde92024","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Commonly Confused Words","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E2","q":"Which sentence correctly uses 'lay' versus 'lie'?","options":["She decided to lay down for a nap.","She decided to lie down for a nap.","She decided to lied down for a nap.","She decided to laid down for a nap."],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Lie\" (meaning to recline) is correct here, since 'lay' requires a direct object (as in 'lay the book down'), which is missing in this sentence."},{"id":"sde92025","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Writer's Craft — Sentence Structure","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E2","q":"Which sentence correctly demonstrates the use of a rhetorical fragment for deliberate stylistic effect?","options":["She had one thought as the door closed. Silence.","She had one thought, as the door closed silence.","She had one, thought as the door closed silence.","She had one thought as, the door closed. Silence."],"answer":0,"exp":"\"Silence.\" used deliberately as a one-word sentence fragment can create dramatic emphasis, a stylistic technique distinct from an accidental grammatical error."},{"id":"sde93001","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E3","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'circumspect'?","options":["reckless","cautious and careful about consequences","loud","generous"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Cautious and careful about consequences\" matches the meaning of 'circumspect', describing careful, wary behaviour."},{"id":"sde93002","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E3","q":"Which word is the opposite of 'unequivocal'?","options":["clear","certain","ambiguous or unclear","definite"],"answer":2,"exp":"\"Ambiguous or unclear\" is the opposite of 'unequivocal', which describes something stated with complete clarity, leaving no room for doubt."},{"id":"sde93003","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Word Origins — Roots","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E3","q":"The root word 'morph' relates to which concept?","options":["shape or form","colour","sound","time"],"answer":0,"exp":"The root 'morph' relates to shape or form, as in 'metamorphosis' (a change in form) or 'amorphous' (without a defined shape)."},{"id":"sde93004","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Word Origins — Suffixes","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E3","q":"The suffix '-itis' usually relates to which concept?","options":["inflammation or disease, especially in medical terms","speed","a type of government","colour"],"answer":0,"exp":"The suffix '-itis' relates to inflammation or disease, as in 'arthritis' (inflammation of the joints) or 'tonsillitis'."},{"id":"sde93005","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Persuasive and Rhetorical Techniques","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E3","q":"A politician says, 'Either we pass this law immediately, or our economy collapses entirely.' What persuasive fallacy is this an example of?","options":["a false dilemma, presenting only two extreme options when other possibilities exist","a valid statistic","an appeal to authority","onomatopoeia"],"answer":0,"exp":"This is a false dilemma, presenting only two extreme outcomes as if no other possibilities exist, which oversimplifies a likely more complex situation."},{"id":"sde93006","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E3","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'capricious'?","options":["predictable","unpredictable and impulsive","extremely calm","carefully planned"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Unpredictable and impulsive\" matches the meaning of 'capricious', describing sudden, unpredictable changes in mood or behaviour."},{"id":"sde93007","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Persuasive and Rhetorical Techniques","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E3","q":"A writer argues against a policy by attacking the personal character of its supporter, rather than the policy's actual merits. What is this technique called?","options":["ad hominem (attacking the person rather than the argument)","a statistic","a rhetorical question","an analogy"],"answer":0,"exp":"An ad hominem attack targets the person making an argument, rather than addressing the substance of the argument itself."},{"id":"sde93008","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E3","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'disparage'?","options":["to praise highly","to criticise or belittle","to ignore completely","to celebrate"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"To criticise or belittle\" matches the meaning of 'disparage', describing speaking negatively about someone or something."},{"id":"sde93009","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Word Origins — Prefixes","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E3","q":"The prefix 'post-' usually relates to which concept?","options":["before","after","during","never"],"answer":1,"exp":"The prefix 'post-' relates to 'after', as in 'postpone' (to put after) or 'post-war' (after a war)."},{"id":"sde93010","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E3","q":"Which word is the opposite of 'magnanimous'?","options":["generous","forgiving","petty or mean-spirited","noble"],"answer":2,"exp":"\"Petty or mean-spirited\" is the opposite of 'magnanimous', which describes generous, noble behaviour, especially toward a rival or someone less powerful."},{"id":"sde93011","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Persuasive and Rhetorical Techniques","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E3","q":"A speaker claims, 'This policy has worked in every country that's tried it' without citing any actual examples or evidence. What is this an example of?","options":["an unsupported generalisation, presented as though it were established fact","a verified statistic","a logical syllogism","an analogy"],"answer":0,"exp":"This is an unsupported generalisation — a sweeping claim presented confidently, but without any specific, checkable evidence to support it."},{"id":"sde93012","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E3","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'vindictive'?","options":["forgiving","seeking revenge","generous","calm"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Seeking revenge\" matches the meaning of 'vindictive', describing a desire to harm someone in return for a perceived wrong."},{"id":"sde93013","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Persuasive and Rhetorical Techniques","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E3","q":"A writer uses a deliberately understated tone to describe a catastrophic event, saying only 'it was a bit of a setback'. What technique is this?","options":["hyperbole","litotes/understatement, for ironic or dramatic effect","alliteration","onomatopoeia"],"answer":1,"exp":"This is understatement (litotes), deliberately downplaying something serious for ironic or dramatic effect, the opposite of hyperbole."},{"id":"sde93014","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E3","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'equanimity'?","options":["panic","calmness, especially under pressure","excitement","confusion"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Calmness, especially under pressure\" matches the meaning of 'equanimity', describing a composed, even temperament in difficult situations."},{"id":"sde93015","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Word Origins — Roots","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E3","q":"The root word 'gen' relates to which concept?","options":["birth, origin, or production","light","sound","movement"],"answer":0,"exp":"The root 'gen' relates to birth, origin, or production, as in 'generate' (to produce) or 'genesis' (the origin of something)."},{"id":"sde93016","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E3","q":"Which word is the opposite of 'austere'?","options":["plain","strict","luxurious or indulgent","simple"],"answer":2,"exp":"\"Luxurious or indulgent\" is the opposite of 'austere', which describes a plain, strict, or self-disciplined style or lifestyle."},{"id":"sde93017","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Persuasive and Rhetorical Techniques","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E3","q":"A persuasive essay opens with a vivid personal anecdote before transitioning to statistical evidence. What is the likely purpose of starting with the anecdote?","options":["to confuse the reader before the real argument begins","to create an emotional connection with the reader before presenting more objective evidence","anecdotes have no persuasive function at all","to fill space without adding any value"],"answer":1,"exp":"Opening with a personal anecdote often creates an emotional connection with the reader, making the subsequent, more objective evidence feel more personally relevant."},{"id":"sde93018","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E3","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'obfuscate'?","options":["to clarify completely","to deliberately make something unclear or confusing","to celebrate openly","to simplify helpfully"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"To deliberately make something unclear or confusing\" matches the meaning of 'obfuscate', often used to describe deliberately vague or confusing language."},{"id":"sde93019","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Persuasive and Rhetorical Techniques","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E3","q":"A writer states, 'Critics of this plan have never actually read it in full' as a way to dismiss their objections, without addressing the objections themselves. What technique is this closest to?","options":["a straw man / ad hominem-style dismissal, deflecting from the substance of the actual criticism","a valid statistical rebuttal","a logical syllogism","an extended metaphor"],"answer":0,"exp":"This dismissal deflects from addressing the actual substance of the criticism, instead attacking the critics' credibility or knowledge — a tactic similar to both straw man and ad hominem techniques."},{"id":"sde93020","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E3","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'tenable' (as in a 'tenable argument')?","options":["impossible to defend","reasonably defensible or justifiable","completely proven beyond doubt","emotionally persuasive only"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Reasonably defensible or justifiable\" matches the meaning of 'tenable', describing a position that can be reasonably maintained or defended."},{"id":"sde93021","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Word Origins — Suffixes","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E3","q":"The suffix '-phile' usually relates to which concept?","options":["a love or strong liking for something","a fear of something","a study of something","a measurement of size"],"answer":0,"exp":"The suffix '-phile' relates to a love or strong liking for something, as in 'bibliophile' (a lover of books) or 'audiophile' (a lover of high-quality sound)."},{"id":"sde93022","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E3","q":"Which word is the opposite of 'pragmatic'?","options":["practical","realistic","idealistic, prioritising principle over practicality","sensible"],"answer":2,"exp":"\"Idealistic, prioritising principle over practicality\" is the opposite of 'pragmatic', which describes a realistic, results-focused approach."},{"id":"sde93023","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Persuasive and Rhetorical Techniques","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E3","q":"A persuasive speech ends with the line: 'History will judge us by what we do next.' What rhetorical effect does this create?","options":["it trivialises the issue being discussed","it elevates the stakes of the decision, framing it as historically significant","it provides a specific statistic","it directly insults the audience"],"answer":1,"exp":"This line elevates the perceived importance of the decision by framing it within a larger historical context, increasing the sense of stakes and urgency for the audience."},{"id":"sde93024","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E3","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'inexorable'?","options":["easily stopped","impossible to stop or prevent","extremely fast","completely random"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Impossible to stop or prevent\" matches the meaning of 'inexorable', describing something relentless and unstoppable."},{"id":"sde93025","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E3","q":"Which word is the opposite of 'ephemeral'?","options":["fleeting","temporary","permanent or lasting","brief"],"answer":2,"exp":"\"Permanent or lasting\" is the opposite of 'ephemeral', which describes something that lasts only a very short time."},{"id":"sde94001","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E4","q":"Read: 'The Quiet Cost of Constant Connectivity\n\nThere is a particular kind of exhaustion that has no obvious cause — not physical labour, not lack of sleep, but something closer to a low-grade, persistent depletion that many people struggle to name. Increasingly, researchers studying attention and digital habits suspect that constant connectivity itself may be a significant, underappreciated contributor.\n\nThe argument runs roughly as follows: human attention, unlike a renewable resource, behaves more like a finite reservoir that depletes throughout the day, particularly when subjected to frequent task-switching. Every notification checked, every brief scroll through a feed between tasks, requires a small but real cognitive cost — not just the seconds spent looking at the screen, but the additional, often unmeasured time required to re-establish focus on whatever was previously being done. Multiplied across dozens of these interruptions daily, the cumulative effect on sustained attention may be considerably larger than any individual interruption would suggest.\n\nThis is not, researchers are careful to note, an argument that technology itself is inherently harmful — a framing that risks oversimplifying a genuinely complex relationship between digital tools and wellbeing. Many of the same notifications and connectivity features that fragment attention also provide genuine value: coordination with colleagues, connection with distant family, access to information that would have been unreachable in any previous era. The relevant question is not whether to use these tools, but how their design and our habits around them might be adjusted to reduce unnecessary cognitive cost without sacrificing genuine benefit.\n\nSome proposed interventions are individual: scheduled 'focus blocks' with notifications disabled, or simply relocating a phone to another room during demanding work. Others are structural, aimed at the technology itself — design choices like reducing the urgency signalled by notification design, or building in natural points where checking a device feels less compulsive. Early evidence for both approaches is promising but limited, constrained by the practical difficulty of conducting rigorous, long-term studies on rapidly evolving technology and equally rapidly evolving habits.\n\nWhat seems least disputed, even among researchers who disagree on specific interventions, is the underlying premise: attention is a limited resource, constant interruption has a real and measurable cost, and the convenience of permanent connectivity is not, in fact, free.'\n\nWhat 'particular kind of exhaustion' does the passage describe in the opening paragraph?","options":["exhaustion clearly caused by physical labour","a low-grade, persistent depletion with no obvious physical cause","exhaustion that only affects elderly people","exhaustion caused entirely by lack of sleep"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage describes 'a low-grade, persistent depletion' that is 'not physical labour, not lack of sleep', with researchers suspecting connectivity as a contributing cause."},{"id":"sde94002","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E4","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nAccording to the second paragraph, what is the 'cumulative effect' of frequent task-switching on attention?","options":["it has no measurable effect at all","it may be considerably larger than any single interruption would suggest, due to the additional time needed to refocus","it only affects physical energy, not mental focus","it improves attention over time through practice"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage states the cumulative effect 'may be considerably larger than any individual interruption would suggest', due to the additional time needed to re-establish focus after each interruption."},{"id":"sde94003","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Author's Purpose","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E4","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhy does the writer explicitly state this is 'not an argument that technology itself is inherently harmful'?","options":["to avoid oversimplifying a genuinely complex relationship between digital tools and wellbeing, acknowledging real benefits alongside the costs","because the writer secretly believes technology is completely harmless","to contradict everything stated in the previous paragraph","because this clarification is legally required"],"answer":0,"exp":"The writer explicitly avoids this oversimplified framing 'that risks oversimplifying a genuinely complex relationship', going on to acknowledge genuine benefits of connectivity alongside its costs."},{"id":"sde94004","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E4","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat distinction does the passage draw between 'individual' and 'structural' interventions?","options":["individual interventions involve personal habit changes, while structural interventions involve changes to technology design itself","there is no real distinction between these two types of interventions","structural interventions are always more effective than individual ones","individual interventions only apply to teenagers"],"answer":0,"exp":"The passage describes individual interventions as personal habit changes (like scheduled focus blocks), while structural interventions involve changes to 'the technology itself', such as notification design."},{"id":"sde94005","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E4","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat limitation does the passage acknowledge regarding evidence for these interventions?","options":["there is no evidence at all for any intervention","evidence is promising but limited, constrained by the difficulty of studying rapidly evolving technology and habits","all interventions have been proven completely ineffective","researchers refuse to study this topic at all"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage states 'early evidence for both approaches is promising but limited, constrained by the practical difficulty of conducting rigorous, long-term studies on rapidly evolving technology'."},{"id":"sde94006","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Vocabulary in Context","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E4","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat does the word 'depletion' mean in the first paragraph?","options":["sudden increase","gradual reduction or exhaustion of a resource","complete restoration","an unrelated medical condition"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Depletion\" means a gradual reduction or exhaustion of a resource — in this context, the gradual reduction of mental attention or energy."},{"id":"sde94007","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E4","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhich claim does the writer describe as 'least disputed' even among researchers who disagree on specific interventions?","options":["that all technology should be banned immediately","that attention is a limited resource and constant interruption has a real, measurable cost","that notifications have no effect on focus whatsoever","that only individual interventions are worth pursuing"],"answer":1,"exp":"The final paragraph states the underlying premise that 'attention is a limited resource, constant interruption has a real and measurable cost' is least disputed, even amid disagreement on specific solutions."},{"id":"sde94008","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Author's Purpose","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E4","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhich best describes the overall purpose of this passage?","options":["to persuade readers to delete all social media immediately","to inform readers about a nuanced, evidence-based perspective on attention and digital connectivity, without resorting to extreme claims","to argue that connectivity has absolutely no downsides","to provide a strict, mandatory daily schedule for phone use"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage presents a nuanced, evidence-based discussion of the costs and benefits of digital connectivity, explicitly avoiding extreme claims in either direction."},{"id":"sde94009","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E4","q":"Read: 'What the Glacier Knows\n\nThey say it moves an inch a year, sometimes less,\na stillness so complete it reads as stone,\nuntil you press your palm against the white\nand feel, beneath your hand, the cold thing groan.\n\nMy grandfather walked this valley as a boy,\nwhen the ice reached further than the eye could hold.\nHe tells it now the way you'd tell a fable —\nhalf-memory, half-myth, slightly retold.\n\nI cannot prove which version is more true:\nthe boy who touched the ice where I stand now,\nor the old man's memory, worn smooth with telling,\nsoftened at the edges, somehow, somehow.\n\nWhat's certain is the line still carved in granite,\na high-water mark from a vanished century's reach —\nnot metaphor, not myth, not grandfather's fable,\njust rock, remembering what the ice used to teach.\n\nI photograph the gap between then and now,\nthe bare stone where blue ice used to gleam,\naware that what I'm framing in this picture\nis already, quietly, becoming someone's dream —\n\nthe version my own grandchild might later tell,\nhalf-myth themselves by then, slightly retold,\nof a grandparent who once stood where ice was vanishing,\nin a valley going quiet, and increasingly cold.'\n\nWhat does the speaker's grandfather describe in the second stanza?","options":["a fictional story with no basis in reality","his own memory of the glacier reaching much further when he was young","a scientific report on glacier movement","a dream he once had"],"answer":1,"exp":"The poem describes the grandfather recalling 'when the ice reached further than the eye could hold', a memory from his own youth."},{"id":"sde94010","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Inference","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E4","q":"Read the same poem.\n\nWhat does the speaker mean by saying the grandfather's memory is told 'the way you'd tell a fable — half-memory, half-myth'?","options":["the grandfather is deliberately lying about his memory","memories, especially retold many times, can blend factual recollection with embellishment over time","fables and memories are scientifically identical","the speaker doesn't trust the grandfather at all"],"answer":1,"exp":"This phrase suggests that memories, especially when retold repeatedly over time, naturally blend genuine recollection with elements of embellishment or reshaping, similar to how a fable evolves."},{"id":"sde94011","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E4","q":"Read the same poem.\n\nWhat physical evidence does the poem describe as 'certain', distinct from memory or storytelling?","options":["a photograph taken by the grandfather","a line carved in granite marking the glacier's former height","a written historical record","nothing — the poem claims nothing is certain"],"answer":1,"exp":"The poem describes 'the line still carved in granite, a high-water mark... not metaphor, not myth, not grandfather's fable, just rock' as the certain physical evidence."},{"id":"sde94012","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Inference","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E4","q":"Read the same poem.\n\nWhat does the final stanza suggest about how the speaker's own experience will eventually be remembered?","options":["it will be perfectly preserved forever, unchanged","it will likely become reshaped and partly mythologised over time, just as the grandfather's memory was, when retold by a future grandchild","it will be completely forgotten immediately","it has already been forgotten"],"answer":1,"exp":"The final stanza suggests the speaker's own present experience will similarly become 'half-myth themselves by then, slightly retold' when eventually passed down to a future grandchild."},{"id":"sde94013","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Author's Purpose","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E4","q":"Read the same poem.\n\nWhat is the overall theme of this poem?","options":["the precise scientific measurement of glacier movement","the way memory, storytelling, and physical evidence each capture different, sometimes blurred versions of truth across generations, set against irreversible environmental change","a simple description of a family hiking trip","an argument that grandparents always exaggerate their stories"],"answer":1,"exp":"The poem explores how memory, oral storytelling, and physical evidence (the carved line in granite) each capture different, sometimes blurred versions of truth across generations, set against the backdrop of the glacier's irreversible retreat."},{"id":"sde94014","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Writer's Craft","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E4","q":"Read the same poem.\n\nWhat literary device is used in the phrase 'feel, beneath your hand, the cold thing groan'?","options":["a literal, scientifically accurate description with no figurative meaning","personification, giving the glacier a human-like sound and quality","onomatopoeia only, with no other figurative meaning","a simile comparing the glacier to a person"],"answer":1,"exp":"This phrase personifies the glacier, giving it a human-like quality (groaning) to emphasise its massive, almost-alive presence despite its apparent stillness."},{"id":"sde94015","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Evaluating Evidence","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E4","q":"Read the same poem.\n\nWhich phrase best captures the poem's central tension between permanence and change?","options":["\"They say it moves an inch a year, sometimes less\"","\"the bare stone where blue ice used to gleam\"","\"a high-water mark from a vanished century's reach\"","all three phrases contribute to this tension, each highlighting a different aspect of change over time"],"answer":3,"exp":"Each phrase highlights a different aspect of the tension between apparent permanence (slow movement, solid rock) and undeniable change (vanished ice, a bare landscape where ice once was)."},{"id":"sde94016","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Writer's Craft","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E4","q":"Read the same poem.\n\nWhy might the poet have chosen to end the poem on the image of a future grandchild's retelling, rather than ending with the glacier itself?","options":["to suggest the cycle of memory and change will continue across future generations, extending the poem's themes beyond just the glacier's retreat","to abruptly change the subject with no clear purpose","because the poem ran out of things to say about the glacier","to argue that grandchildren are unreliable narrators"],"answer":0,"exp":"Ending on a future grandchild's eventual retelling extends the poem's themes of memory, change, and storytelling beyond the glacier itself, suggesting this cycle will continue indefinitely across generations."},{"id":"sde94017","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Literary Terms","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E4","q":"What is 'dramatic irony'?","options":["when a character says something funny","when the audience knows something a character does not, creating tension or insight","a type of rhyme scheme","a metaphor used in drama only"],"answer":1,"exp":"Dramatic irony occurs when the audience or reader knows something important that a character within the story does not, often creating tension or deeper meaning."},{"id":"sde94018","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Literary Terms","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E4","q":"What is a 'foil' in literature?","options":["a type of metal used in old books","a character whose traits contrast with another character, highlighting particular qualities by contrast","the main villain of a story","a type of rhyming pattern"],"answer":1,"exp":"A foil is a character whose contrasting traits highlight particular qualities in another character, often the protagonist, through comparison."},{"id":"sde94019","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Literary Terms","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E4","q":"What does 'pathos' refer to in rhetoric and literature?","options":["an appeal to logic and reason","an appeal to the emotions of the audience","an appeal to the credibility of the speaker","a type of rhyme scheme"],"answer":1,"exp":"Pathos refers to an appeal to the emotions of the audience, one of the three classical persuasive appeals alongside ethos (credibility) and logos (logic)."},{"id":"sde94020","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Literary Terms","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E4","q":"What does 'ethos' refer to in rhetoric?","options":["an appeal to emotion","an appeal based on the credibility or character of the speaker","an appeal to statistics only","a type of figurative language"],"answer":1,"exp":"Ethos refers to an appeal based on the credibility, expertise, or character of the speaker, used to persuade an audience to trust their argument."},{"id":"sde94021","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Literary Terms","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E4","q":"What does 'logos' refer to in rhetoric?","options":["an appeal to emotion","an appeal to the speaker's character","an appeal based on logic, reasoning, and evidence","a poetic rhyme scheme"],"answer":2,"exp":"Logos refers to an appeal based on logic, reasoning, and evidence, one of the three classical persuasive appeals."},{"id":"sde94022","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Literary Terms","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E4","q":"What is 'pathetic fallacy'?","options":["a logical error in an argument","attributing human emotions to nature or inanimate objects, especially to reflect a character's mood","a type of rhyme scheme","an appeal to the audience's pity"],"answer":1,"exp":"Pathetic fallacy is a specific type of personification where nature or the weather is given human emotions, often used to reflect or amplify a character's internal mood (such as a storm reflecting inner turmoil)."},{"id":"sde94023","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Literary Terms","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E4","q":"What is an 'unreliable narrator'?","options":["a narrator who tells the story in the wrong order","a narrator whose credibility or perception is compromised, leading readers to question their version of events","a narrator who never speaks","a narrator who exists only in poetry"],"answer":1,"exp":"An unreliable narrator is one whose credibility, knowledge, or honesty is compromised in some way, leading readers to question the accuracy of their account of events."},{"id":"sde94024","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Literary Terms","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E4","q":"What is 'in medias res'?","options":["starting a story in the middle of the action, rather than at the very beginning","ending a story without resolution","a type of rhyme scheme","a poem written entirely in Latin"],"answer":0,"exp":"\"In medias res\" (Latin for 'into the middle of things') describes starting a narrative in the middle of the action, rather than from the very beginning of the story's events."},{"id":"sde94025","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Literary Terms","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E4","q":"What is a 'bildungsroman'?","options":["a type of formal letter","a novel focused on the moral and psychological growth of its main character from youth to adulthood","a poem with no fixed structure","a play with only one character"],"answer":1,"exp":"A bildungsroman is a novel focused on the moral, psychological, and intellectual growth of its protagonist, typically from youth into adulthood."},{"id":"sde101001","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E1","q":"Read: 'The Renovation\n\nWhen Marisol's parents bought the old Trevino house, the real estate listing had used the word \"character\" seventeen times, which she now understood to be a euphemism for \"everything is slightly broken.\" Eight months into the renovation, she'd learned more about plumbing, structural load-bearing walls, and 1960s building codes than any sixteen-year-old should reasonably know.\n\nWhat she hadn't expected was the box.\n\nIt turned up wedged behind a wall cavity the electrician had opened up, water-damaged but mostly intact: a small collection of letters, photographs, and a child's drawing dated 1967. The letters were between two sisters, one of whom — according to the careful, looping handwriting — had lived in this exact house. Marisol read perhaps a dozen of them before her mother called her down for dinner, and found herself oddly reluctant to mention the discovery at the table.\n\nIt wasn't that the letters contained anything scandalous. They were, if anything, almost mundane — complaints about a difficult mother-in-law, updates about a vegetable garden's modest failures, a recurring joke about a neighbour's badly behaved dog. But there was something in their ordinariness that felt private in a way Marisol hadn't anticipated. These weren't dramatic secrets meant to be uncovered; they were just someone's actual life, never intended for a stranger's eyes fifty-odd years later.\n\nShe kept the box in her room for three weeks before mentioning it to anyone, turning the same question over without quite resolving it: did finding something accidentally, in a wall you happened to be renovating, grant you any right to it? The letters weren't valuable in any way she could articulate to her parents, who would likely see them as charming clutter at best. They mattered to her for a reason she struggled to explain even to herself — something about the strange intimacy of reading a stranger's grocery-list version of being alive, and the responsibility that seemed to come with that, however slight.\n\nEventually, she did what felt like the only reasonable thing: she found the sister's family — a phone number, eventually, through a genealogy website and a cousin three times removed — and mailed the box to an address in another state, keeping nothing but a single photograph of the garden, badly faded, that nobody on the other end particularly wanted back.'\n\nWhat does Marisol discover during the house renovation?","options":["a hidden room","a box of letters, photographs, and a child's drawing from 1967","a buried treasure chest","an old family photo album belonging to her own family"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage states she discovers 'a small collection of letters, photographs, and a child's drawing dated 1967'."},{"id":"sde101002","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Inference","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhy does Marisol feel 'oddly reluctant to mention the discovery at the table'?","options":["she is afraid of getting in trouble","the passage doesn't fully explain, but it's connected to the private, personal feeling the letters evoke","she had already told her father privately","she doesn't think the letters are interesting"],"answer":1,"exp":"This reluctance seems connected to the sense of privacy and intimacy she feels about the letters, which the passage explores further in the following paragraph."},{"id":"sde101003","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Inference","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat makes the letters feel 'private' to Marisol, according to the fourth paragraph?","options":["they contain shocking, scandalous secrets","their very ordinariness — mundane details of someone's actual life never meant for a stranger's eyes","they are written in a language she doesn't understand","they were locked in a safe"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage states it was 'something in their ordinariness that felt private', describing the letters as containing someone's 'actual life, never intended for a stranger's eyes'."},{"id":"sde101004","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat central question does Marisol turn over for three weeks?","options":["whether to tell her parents about the renovation budget","whether finding something accidentally grants any right to it","whether to continue the house renovation at all","whether the letters were forged"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage explicitly states her unresolved question: 'did finding something accidentally, in a wall you happened to be renovating, grant you any right to it?'"},{"id":"sde101005","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat does Marisol ultimately decide to do with the letters?","options":["she keeps them permanently in her room","she throws them away","she finds the sister's family and mails the box to them, keeping only one photograph","she sells them to a collector"],"answer":2,"exp":"The passage states she 'found the sister's family... and mailed the box to an address in another state, keeping nothing but a single photograph'."},{"id":"sde101006","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Inference","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat is the significance of the detail that the recipient family 'particularly wanted' nothing back, including the photograph Marisol kept?","options":["it shows the family was rude and ungrateful","it subtly reinforces the theme that these small, personal artefacts hold meaning mainly for those who discover and reflect on them, not necessarily for distant descendants","it proves the letters had no value at all","it suggests the family had already seen the photograph before"],"answer":1,"exp":"This detail subtly reinforces the story's exploration of how personal meaning in such artefacts can be more about the discoverer's reflection than about objective, universally recognised value."},{"id":"sde101007","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Vocabulary in Context","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat does the word 'mundane' mean in the fourth paragraph?","options":["extremely exciting","ordinary and unremarkable","secretive and hidden","valuable and rare"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Mundane\" means ordinary and unremarkable, fitting the description of the letters' everyday content (complaints, garden updates, a joke about a dog)."},{"id":"sde101008","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Author's Purpose","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhich best describes the central theme explored in this passage?","options":["the practical challenges of home renovation","the unexpected weight and responsibility of stumbling onto someone else's private, ordinary past","the importance of always returning lost property immediately","a mystery about who built the house originally"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage explores Marisol's reflection on the unexpected emotional and ethical weight of discovering someone else's private, ordinary life, and what responsibility (if any) that creates."},{"id":"sde101009","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E1","q":"Read: 'On the Ethics of Algorithmic Recommendation\n\nEvery time a streaming platform suggests what to watch next, or a social media feed decides what to show you, an algorithm has made a quiet judgment about what will keep you engaged. For most of the history of media, this judgment was made by human editors, programmers, and curators. Today, it is made largely by systems trained to optimise for one primary metric: continued attention.\n\nThis shift raises a question that often goes unexamined amid more headline-grabbing debates about technology: what obligations, if any, do these recommendation systems have toward the wellbeing of the people using them, as opposed to simply their engagement? An algorithm that maximises watch time is not, by design, equivalent to one that maximises a user's considered satisfaction, let alone their broader wellbeing. These can align, but there is no guarantee that they will.\n\nSome technology companies have begun introducing wellbeing-oriented features — screen time reports, gentle reminders to take breaks — but these exist largely alongside, rather than within, the core recommendation systems themselves. The fundamental incentive structure, which rewards continued engagement above most other outcomes, remains largely unchanged beneath these surface-level additions.\n\nDefenders of current systems sometimes argue that users retain ultimate responsibility and agency over their own media consumption, and that companies should not be expected to act paternalistically on users' behalf. This argument carries genuine weight; there is something uncomfortable about ceding judgment over what is \"good for us\" to corporations with their own commercial interests. Yet this argument becomes harder to sustain when applied to systems explicitly engineered, often using considerable behavioural research, to exploit predictable patterns in human attention and impulse control. The notion of \"agency\" assumes a contest between roughly equal parties — a assumption that strains credibility when one party has access to vast behavioural data and sophisticated optimisation techniques, and the other does not.\n\nNone of this implies that algorithmic recommendation is inherently harmful, or that human curation was somehow free of its own commercial and editorial biases. It does suggest, however, that the ethical questions surrounding these systems deserve more sustained attention than they generally receive — not as a footnote to discussions of misinformation or screen time, but as a central question about what these systems are actually designed to optimise for, and on whose behalf.'\n\nWhat metric does the writer claim most modern recommendation algorithms primarily optimise for?","options":["user wellbeing","continued attention/engagement","factual accuracy","financial cost to the user"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage states these systems are 'trained to optimise for one primary metric: continued attention'."},{"id":"sde101010","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Author's Purpose","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat is the writer's main point in the second paragraph about engagement versus wellbeing?","options":["engagement and wellbeing are always exactly the same thing","maximising engagement does not automatically equate to maximising a user's genuine wellbeing or satisfaction","wellbeing has no real connection to technology","algorithms should be banned entirely"],"answer":1,"exp":"The writer argues that 'an algorithm that maximises watch time is not, by design, equivalent to one that maximises a user's considered satisfaction, let alone their broader wellbeing', noting these 'can align, but there is no guarantee'."},{"id":"sde101011","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nAccording to the third paragraph, what limitation does the writer identify in current 'wellbeing-oriented features'?","options":["they don't exist at all","they exist alongside the core recommendation systems, rather than changing the fundamental incentive structure itself","they are too expensive for companies to implement","they have completely solved the underlying problem"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage states these features 'exist largely alongside, rather than within, the core recommendation systems', leaving 'the fundamental incentive structure... largely unchanged'."},{"id":"sde101012","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Persuasive Techniques","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat counter-argument does the writer acknowledge in the fourth paragraph, before responding to it?","options":["that algorithms are too simple to cause any real harm","that users retain ultimate responsibility and agency over their own media consumption","that all algorithms should be made completely public","that companies have no commercial interests at all"],"answer":1,"exp":"The writer acknowledges the argument 'that users retain ultimate responsibility and agency over their own media consumption, and that companies should not be expected to act paternalistically'."},{"id":"sde101013","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Persuasive Techniques","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhy does the writer argue this counter-argument 'becomes harder to sustain' in certain cases?","options":["because all algorithms are identical in their design","because some systems are explicitly engineered, using behavioural research, to exploit predictable patterns in human attention and impulse control","because users always have complete control regardless of system design","because companies never use behavioural research"],"answer":1,"exp":"The writer argues the counter-argument weakens 'when applied to systems explicitly engineered... to exploit predictable patterns in human attention and impulse control'."},{"id":"sde101014","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Vocabulary in Context","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat does the word 'paternalistically' most likely mean in the fourth paragraph?","options":["acting like a typical father in a family setting","acting in a controlling way on someone else's behalf, as if they cannot make their own decisions","acting with extreme aggression","acting with complete transparency"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Paternalistically\" describes acting in a controlling, protective way on someone else's behalf, often implying the other party is treated as incapable of deciding for themselves."},{"id":"sde101015","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Author's Purpose","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat is the writer's stated position in the final paragraph?","options":["algorithmic recommendation is inherently harmful and should be banned","the ethical questions surrounding these systems deserve more sustained, central attention, rather than being treated as a minor footnote","human curation was always completely unbiased and fair","there are no real ethical questions worth considering here"],"answer":1,"exp":"The writer concludes that 'the ethical questions surrounding these systems deserve more sustained attention than they generally receive... as a central question', while explicitly avoiding the claim that algorithms are 'inherently harmful'."},{"id":"sde101016","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Interpreting Mood","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E1","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhich best describes the writer's overall approach throughout this passage?","options":["a one-sided rant with no acknowledgment of opposing views","a careful, qualified argument that acknowledges counter-arguments and avoids overstating its claims","a purely factual, opinion-free summary with no argument at all","an angry, emotionally charged condemnation of technology companies"],"answer":1,"exp":"Throughout the passage, the writer raises counter-arguments, qualifies claims (e.g. 'none of this implies... is inherently harmful'), and avoids sweeping, unqualified conclusions, reflecting a careful, balanced argumentative approach."},{"id":"sde101017","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E1","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'ambivalence'?","options":["certainty","mixed or conflicting feelings","extreme anger","complete indifference"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Mixed or conflicting feelings\" matches the meaning of 'ambivalence', describing being torn between two opposing views or emotions."},{"id":"sde101018","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E1","q":"Which word is the opposite of 'paternalistic'?","options":["controlling","protective","respecting of others' autonomy","authoritative"],"answer":2,"exp":"\"Respecting of others' autonomy\" is the opposite of 'paternalistic', which describes acting in an overly controlling way on someone else's behalf."},{"id":"sde101019","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E1","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'sustained' (as in 'sustained attention')?","options":["brief","ongoing and continuous","interrupted","forgotten"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Ongoing and continuous\" matches the meaning of 'sustained' in this context, describing something maintained over an extended period."},{"id":"sde101020","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E1","q":"Which word is the opposite of 'mundane'?","options":["ordinary","extraordinary","boring","routine"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Extraordinary\" is the opposite of 'mundane', which describes something ordinary and unremarkable."},{"id":"sde101021","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E1","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'articulate' (as in 'struggled to articulate')?","options":["to forget completely","to express clearly in words","to ignore deliberately","to argue aggressively"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"To express clearly in words\" matches the meaning of 'articulate' as a verb, describing putting thoughts or feelings into clear language."},{"id":"sde101022","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E1","q":"Which word is the opposite of 'genuine' (as in 'genuine weight')?","options":["sincere","authentic","false","real"],"answer":2,"exp":"\"False\" is the opposite of 'genuine', which describes something real and authentic."},{"id":"sde101023","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E1","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'strains' (as in 'strains credibility')?","options":["strengthens","tests to the point of difficulty or implausibility","completely ignores","easily supports"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Tests to the point of difficulty or implausibility\" matches the meaning of 'strains' in this context, describing pushing something close to breaking point."},{"id":"sde101024","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E1","q":"Which word is the opposite of 'considerable' (as in 'considerable behavioural research')?","options":["significant","substantial","negligible","extensive"],"answer":2,"exp":"\"Negligible\" is the opposite of 'considerable', which describes something large or significant in amount."},{"id":"sde101025","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E1","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'exploit' (as in 'exploit predictable patterns')?","options":["to ignore completely","to take advantage of, often unfairly","to repair or fix","to celebrate"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"To take advantage of, often unfairly\" matches the meaning of 'exploit' in this context, describing using something (often a weakness) for one's own benefit."},{"id":"sde102001","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Essay Structure","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E2","q":"In a well-structured argumentative essay, what is the main purpose of the introduction's 'thesis statement'?","options":["to summarise every point that will be made in exhaustive detail","to clearly state the essay's central argument or position","to provide a complete list of sources used","to ask a series of unrelated questions"],"answer":1,"exp":"A thesis statement clearly states the essay's central argument or position, giving the reader a clear sense of what will be argued throughout."},{"id":"sde102002","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Essay Structure","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E2","q":"What is a 'topic sentence' within a body paragraph of an argumentative essay?","options":["the very last sentence of the entire essay","a sentence that introduces the main point or claim of that specific paragraph","a sentence containing only statistics","a sentence that has no connection to the essay's argument"],"answer":1,"exp":"A topic sentence introduces the main point or claim of a specific paragraph, usually appearing near its beginning."},{"id":"sde102003","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Essay Structure — Counter-Arguments","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E2","q":"Why is it generally considered good practice to address a counter-argument within an argumentative essay?","options":["it weakens the writer's own position","it can strengthen the overall argument by showing the writer has considered other viewpoints and can respond to them","counter-arguments should always be avoided entirely","it is only relevant in formal debates, not essays"],"answer":1,"exp":"Addressing a counter-argument shows the writer has considered other viewpoints, which can strengthen the overall argument by demonstrating a more thorough, credible analysis."},{"id":"sde102004","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Essay Structure — Counter-Arguments","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E2","q":"Which best describes 'concession' in argumentative writing?","options":["completely abandoning one's own argument","acknowledging a valid point made by the opposing side, while still maintaining one's overall position","ignoring all opposing viewpoints entirely","a technique used only in persuasive speeches, never in essays"],"answer":1,"exp":"A concession acknowledges a valid point from the opposing side, while the writer still maintains their overall position, often before responding with a rebuttal."},{"id":"sde102005","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Essay Structure — Counter-Arguments","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E2","q":"What is the purpose of a 'rebuttal' following a concession in an argumentative essay?","options":["to fully agree with the opposing argument","to respond to and counter the concern raised, reinforcing the writer's original position","to introduce a completely new, unrelated topic","rebuttals serve no real purpose in essay writing"],"answer":1,"exp":"A rebuttal responds to and counters a concern raised by the opposing view, reinforcing the writer's original position after acknowledging that concern."},{"id":"sde102006","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Logical Fallacies","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E2","q":"Which sentence demonstrates an example of a logical fallacy known as a 'slippery slope' argument?","options":["If we allow students to redo this assignment, soon no one will ever complete assignments properly, and academic standards will completely collapse.","Some students may benefit from redoing this assignment.","The teacher decided to allow one student to redo the assignment.","Most students complete their assignments on time."],"answer":0,"exp":"This is a slippery slope fallacy, suggesting an extreme, exaggerated chain of consequences will inevitably follow from a single, relatively minor decision."},{"id":"sde102007","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Logical Fallacies","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E2","q":"Which sentence demonstrates an 'ad hominem' fallacy?","options":["Her argument about the policy is flawed because she has never personally been affected by it, so we can dismiss everything she says.","The policy has both benefits and drawbacks.","The policy was introduced last year.","Several experts have reviewed the policy's effects."],"answer":0,"exp":"An ad hominem fallacy attacks the person making an argument, rather than addressing the actual argument itself — dismissing her view based on her personal circumstances rather than the argument's content."},{"id":"sde102008","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Logical Fallacies","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E2","q":"Which sentence demonstrates a 'false dichotomy' (false dilemma) fallacy?","options":["Either we ban this completely, or we're saying we don't care about safety at all — there's no middle ground.","There are several possible approaches to this issue.","Some people support the ban, while others oppose it.","The committee will vote on the proposal next week."],"answer":0,"exp":"A false dichotomy presents only two extreme options as if they were the only possibilities, ignoring any potential middle ground or alternative approaches."},{"id":"sde102009","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Grammar — Subjunctive Mood","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E2","q":"Which sentence correctly uses the subjunctive mood in a formal recommendation?","options":["I recommend that he attends the meeting.","I recommend that he attend the meeting.","I recommend that he is attending the meeting.","I recommend that he will attend the meeting."],"answer":1,"exp":"In formal recommendations, the subjunctive mood uses the base form of the verb regardless of subject: \"I recommend that he attend the meeting\" (not 'attends')."},{"id":"sde102010","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Grammar — Nominalisation","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E2","q":"Which sentence demonstrates correct use of a nominalisation (turning a verb into a noun) for formal academic tone?","options":["The committee decided to investigate the issue.","The committee's investigation of the issue began promptly.","The committee will look into the issue.","The committee investigated the issue quickly."],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Investigation\" is a nominalisation of the verb 'investigate', commonly used in formal academic writing to create a more objective, formal tone."},{"id":"sde102011","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Grammar — Sentence Structure","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E2","q":"Which sentence correctly uses a complex sentence with embedded clauses for sophisticated argumentation?","options":["The policy failed. It was poorly designed. Few people supported it.","The policy, which was poorly designed from the outset, failed largely because so few people supported it.","The policy failed and it was poorly designed and few people supported it.","The policy failed, poorly designed, few people, supported it."],"answer":1,"exp":"This sentence embeds a relative clause ('which was poorly designed from the outset') and a causal clause ('because so few people supported it') into one cohesive, sophisticated sentence."},{"id":"sde102012","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Academic Writing — Hedging","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E2","q":"Which best describes the purpose of a 'hedge' in academic or argumentative writing, such as 'it could be argued that' or 'this suggests'?","options":["to make the writer's claims sound more aggressive","to soften a claim, acknowledging it may not be absolutely certain, while still making the point","hedges are never used in formal academic writing","to confuse the reader deliberately"],"answer":1,"exp":"A hedge softens a claim, acknowledging some degree of uncertainty, while still allowing the writer to make their point — common in careful academic or argumentative writing."},{"id":"sde102013","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Academic Writing — Hedging","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E2","q":"Which sentence uses a hedge appropriately in academic writing?","options":["This proves conclusively that the policy is a complete failure.","This suggests that the policy may not be achieving its intended outcomes.","The policy is definitely a failure, without question.","Everyone agrees the policy has completely failed."],"answer":1,"exp":"\"This suggests that... may not be\" appropriately hedges the claim, acknowledging some uncertainty rather than overstating the case with absolute certainty."},{"id":"sde102014","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Logical Fallacies","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E2","q":"Which sentence demonstrates an appeal to popularity (bandwagon) fallacy?","options":["Most people support this policy, so it must be the correct approach.","Experts have studied this policy extensively.","The policy has both supporters and critics.","The policy was implemented last year."],"answer":0,"exp":"This is a bandwagon fallacy, assuming something must be correct simply because many people believe or support it, rather than evaluating the argument's actual merits."},{"id":"sde102015","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Logical Fallacies","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E2","q":"Which sentence demonstrates a 'hasty generalisation' fallacy?","options":["I met two rude people from that city, so everyone from there must be rude.","Some people from that city were unfriendly when I visited.","Cities often have diverse populations with varied personalities.","I haven't visited that city before."],"answer":0,"exp":"This is a hasty generalisation, drawing a broad conclusion about an entire group based on a very small, potentially unrepresentative sample."},{"id":"sde102016","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Punctuation — Semicolons","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E2","q":"Which sentence demonstrates effective use of a semicolon to connect two closely related independent clauses in formal writing?","options":["The evidence was compelling; the jury reached a verdict quickly.","The evidence was compelling, the jury reached a verdict quickly.","The evidence was compelling the jury reached a verdict quickly.","The evidence; was compelling, the jury reached a verdict; quickly."],"answer":0,"exp":"The semicolon correctly joins two closely related independent clauses without needing a coordinating conjunction: \"The evidence was compelling; the jury reached a verdict quickly.\""},{"id":"sde102017","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Essay Structure","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E2","q":"Which best describes an effective concluding paragraph in an argumentative essay?","options":["it should introduce several brand new arguments not previously mentioned","it should restate the thesis in fresh language and consider the argument's broader significance, without simply repeating the introduction word-for-word","it should be the shortest paragraph, with no real content","it should apologise for any weaknesses in the argument"],"answer":1,"exp":"An effective conclusion restates the thesis using fresh language and considers the argument's broader significance, rather than simply repeating the introduction."},{"id":"sde102018","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Logical Fallacies","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E2","q":"Which sentence demonstrates a straw man fallacy?","options":["My opponent wants better regulation, but apparently they want to ban this activity completely, which is clearly extreme and unworkable.","My opponent supports better regulation of this activity.","Regulation can take many different forms.","Some regulations have proven effective in similar contexts."],"answer":0,"exp":"This is a straw man fallacy, misrepresenting the opponent's actual, more moderate position ('better regulation') as something more extreme ('ban completely') in order to attack it more easily."},{"id":"sde102019","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Essay Structure — Persuasive Techniques","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E2","q":"Which sentence demonstrates an appropriate use of a rhetorical question to open an argumentative essay?","options":["What is the capital of France?","How much longer can we ignore the clear evidence of this growing crisis?","Did you have a good breakfast this morning?","What time does the library close on Sundays?"],"answer":1,"exp":"This rhetorical question is designed to provoke thought about the essay's central issue, drawing the reader in, rather than seeking a literal factual answer."},{"id":"sde102020","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Essay Structure — Cohesion","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E2","q":"Which best describes the function of a 'signpost' phrase, such as 'furthermore' or 'in contrast', within an argumentative essay?","options":["it has no real function and can be removed without consequence","it helps guide the reader through the logical structure and flow of the argument","it is only used in casual, informal writing","it always indicates the essay is concluding"],"answer":1,"exp":"Signpost phrases like 'furthermore' or 'in contrast' help guide the reader through the logical structure of the argument, signalling how each point relates to what came before."},{"id":"sde102021","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Logical Fallacies","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E2","q":"Which sentence demonstrates a circular argument (begging the question) fallacy?","options":["This law is just, because it is the law, and laws are just by definition.","This law was passed by the parliament.","Some people disagree with this particular law.","The law has been in effect for several years."],"answer":0,"exp":"This is a circular argument, where the conclusion ('this law is just') is essentially restated as its own justification ('laws are just by definition'), without providing independent supporting evidence."},{"id":"sde102022","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Essay Structure — Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E2","q":"Which best describes the purpose of using precise, topic-specific vocabulary in an argumentative essay, rather than vague, general terms?","options":["it makes the essay more difficult to understand for no real benefit","it demonstrates a stronger command of the subject and can make the argument more persuasive and credible","precise vocabulary should always be avoided in essays","vague vocabulary is always preferable in formal writing"],"answer":1,"exp":"Precise, topic-specific vocabulary demonstrates a stronger command of the subject matter, which can make an argument appear more credible and persuasive to the reader."},{"id":"sde102023","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Punctuation — Em Dashes","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E2","q":"Which sentence correctly uses an em dash to add emphasis or an abrupt interruption?","options":["The decision — and this surprised everyone — was reversed within a week.","The decision and, this surprised everyone, was reversed within — a week.","The decision—and this surprised everyone—was reversed, within a week.","The — decision and this surprised everyone was reversed within a week."],"answer":0,"exp":"The em dash correctly sets off the interrupting phrase 'and this surprised everyone' for emphasis, while the rest of the sentence remains grammatically intact."},{"id":"sde102024","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Logical Fallacies","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E2","q":"Which best describes a 'false cause' (post hoc) fallacy?","options":["assuming that because one event followed another, the first event must have caused the second","correctly identifying a clear, well-evidenced cause and effect relationship","acknowledging that correlation does not always imply causation","using a relevant statistic to support an argument"],"answer":0,"exp":"A false cause (post hoc) fallacy assumes that because one event happened before another, the first must have caused the second, without sufficient evidence for this causal link."},{"id":"sde102025","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Logical Fallacies","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E2","q":"Which sentence best demonstrates an appeal to authority used appropriately, rather than fallaciously?","options":["My friend says this medical treatment works, so it must be effective.","According to multiple peer-reviewed studies published by medical researchers, this treatment has shown measurable benefits.","Everyone knows this treatment works.","A celebrity recommended this treatment on social media."],"answer":1,"exp":"Citing peer-reviewed studies from qualified medical researchers is an appropriate use of authority, relying on relevant expertise and evidence, unlike the other options which rely on irrelevant or unverified sources."},{"id":"sde103001","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Literary Devices — Satire","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E3","q":"What is 'satire' in literature?","options":["a serious, formal style with no humour","a genre that uses humour, irony, or exaggeration to criticise or mock a subject, often social or political","a type of poem with a strict rhyme scheme","a factual report with no creative elements"],"answer":1,"exp":"Satire uses humour, irony, or exaggeration to criticise or mock a subject, often targeting social, political, or human folly."},{"id":"sde103002","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Literary Devices — Irony","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E3","q":"Which best describes 'dramatic irony'?","options":["when a character says something accidentally funny","when the audience knows something a character does not, creating tension or insight","when a story has an unexpected happy ending","when a character speaks in an overly dramatic tone"],"answer":1,"exp":"Dramatic irony occurs when the audience or reader knows something important that a character does not, often creating tension or a sense of foreboding."},{"id":"sde103003","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Literary Devices — Irony","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E3","q":"Which best describes 'situational irony'?","options":["when the outcome of a situation is the opposite of what was expected","when a character speaks sarcastically","when the audience and characters share exactly the same knowledge","when a story is told entirely out of order"],"answer":0,"exp":"Situational irony occurs when the actual outcome of a situation is strikingly different from, or the opposite of, what was expected."},{"id":"sde103004","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Literary Devices — Irony","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E3","q":"Which best describes 'verbal irony'?","options":["when a character's words mean the literal opposite of, or something quite different from, their intended meaning","when two characters speak the same language","when dialogue is written entirely in capital letters","when a narrator never speaks directly to the reader"],"answer":0,"exp":"Verbal irony occurs when someone says something that means the opposite of, or something quite different from, what they actually intend, often for sarcastic or humorous effect."},{"id":"sde103005","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Comparative Analysis","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E3","q":"In comparative analysis, what does it mean to compare the 'tone' of two texts?","options":["comparing how loudly each text would be read aloud","comparing the overall attitude or feeling conveyed by each writer toward their subject","comparing only the length of each text","comparing the font used in each text's publication"],"answer":1,"exp":"Comparing tone involves examining the overall attitude or feeling each writer conveys toward their subject — such as serious, humorous, critical, or sympathetic."},{"id":"sde103006","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Comparative Analysis","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E3","q":"When comparing two persuasive texts on the same topic, why might examining each writer's choice of evidence be useful?","options":["it reveals nothing meaningful about either text","it can reveal differing priorities, assumptions, or intended audiences between the two writers","evidence is identical in all persuasive texts","comparing evidence is only relevant in scientific writing, not persuasive writing"],"answer":1,"exp":"Examining each writer's choice of evidence (such as statistics, anecdotes, or expert opinions) can reveal differing priorities, assumptions, or intended audiences between the two texts."},{"id":"sde103007","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Literary Devices — Allegory","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E3","q":"Which best describes an 'allegory' in literature?","options":["a short poem with no deeper meaning","a narrative in which characters, events, or settings represent broader ideas or moral, political, or social concepts","a factual historical account","a story with no characters at all"],"answer":1,"exp":"An allegory is a narrative where characters, events, or settings represent broader ideas or concepts, often moral, political, or social in nature."},{"id":"sde103008","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Rhetorical Appeals","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E3","q":"What is 'pathos' as a persuasive or rhetorical appeal?","options":["an appeal based on logic and evidence","an appeal to the audience's emotions","an appeal based on the speaker's credibility or authority","an appeal that uses only statistics"],"answer":1,"exp":"Pathos is a rhetorical appeal that targets the audience's emotions, aiming to persuade through feelings rather than pure logic or authority."},{"id":"sde103009","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Rhetorical Appeals","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E3","q":"What is 'logos' as a persuasive or rhetorical appeal?","options":["an appeal to emotion","an appeal based on logic, reasoning, and evidence","an appeal based purely on the speaker's reputation","an appeal that relies entirely on humour"],"answer":1,"exp":"Logos is a rhetorical appeal based on logic, reasoning, and evidence, aiming to persuade through rational argument."},{"id":"sde103010","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Rhetorical Appeals","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E3","q":"What is 'ethos' as a persuasive or rhetorical appeal?","options":["an appeal to logic only","an appeal based on the speaker's credibility, character, or authority","an appeal based entirely on emotion","an appeal that uses only statistics"],"answer":1,"exp":"Ethos is a rhetorical appeal based on the speaker's credibility, character, or perceived authority, aiming to persuade by establishing trust."},{"id":"sde103011","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Literary Devices","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E3","q":"Which best describes 'foreshadowing' as a literary device?","options":["describing events that have already happened in great detail","hinting at events that will occur later in the narrative","using extremely long, complex sentences","writing a story with no plot at all"],"answer":1,"exp":"Foreshadowing is a literary device where a writer hints at events that will occur later in the narrative, often creating tension or anticipation."},{"id":"sde103012","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Literary Devices — Narrative Techniques","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E3","q":"Which best describes 'in medias res' as a narrative technique?","options":["beginning a story right in the middle of the action, rather than at the very start of events","ending a story without any resolution","writing a story entirely in the past tense","using only dialogue throughout an entire story"],"answer":0,"exp":"\"In medias res\" (Latin for 'into the middle of things') describes beginning a narrative in the middle of the action, rather than chronologically from the very start."},{"id":"sde103013","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Comparative Analysis","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E3","q":"When comparing the structure of two texts, what might differing paragraph lengths and sentence complexity reveal about each writer's intended audience?","options":["nothing meaningful at all","shorter, simpler structures often suggest a broader or younger audience, while longer, complex structures may suggest a more specialised or academic audience","sentence length has no connection to audience at all","all texts are written for exactly the same audience regardless of structure"],"answer":1,"exp":"Shorter, simpler sentence and paragraph structures often suggest a broader or younger intended audience, while longer, more complex structures may suggest a more specialised or academic audience."},{"id":"sde103014","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Literary Devices","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E3","q":"Which best describes 'understatement' as a literary or rhetorical device?","options":["deliberately exaggerating something far beyond its actual significance","deliberately representing something as less significant or serious than it actually is, often for ironic or humorous effect","stating something with complete neutrality and no particular effect","always speaking as loudly as possible"],"answer":1,"exp":"Understatement deliberately represents something as less significant than it actually is, often used for ironic, humorous, or restrained emotional effect."},{"id":"sde103015","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Literary Devices","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E3","q":"Which sentence demonstrates understatement?","options":["The hurricane caused unimaginable, catastrophic devastation across the entire region.","After losing both his arms in the accident, he remarked that it was 'a bit of a setback'.","The team celebrated wildly after their unexpected victory.","The weather forecast predicted clear skies for the entire week."],"answer":1,"exp":"Describing losing both arms as 'a bit of a setback' is a striking example of understatement, deliberately downplaying something extremely serious."},{"id":"sde103016","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Literary Devices — Satire","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E3","q":"Which best describes 'satire' using exaggeration, as commonly seen in political cartoons?","options":["depicting a subject with complete photographic realism","exaggerating specific features or behaviours of a subject to highlight and criticise particular flaws or absurdities","avoiding any criticism of public figures entirely","using only neutral, factual captions with no visual exaggeration"],"answer":1,"exp":"Satirical exaggeration, common in political cartoons, deliberately overstates specific features or behaviours to highlight and criticise particular flaws or absurdities in the subject."},{"id":"sde103017","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Comparative Analysis — Spoken Texts","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E3","q":"When analysing a persuasive speech, why might examining the speaker's use of pacing and repetition be useful, alongside the actual words used?","options":["pacing and repetition have no real persuasive effect","these techniques can build emotional intensity and emphasis, working alongside the literal content to strengthen the persuasive effect","only the literal meaning of words ever matters in a speech","pacing and repetition are only relevant in written texts, not spoken ones"],"answer":1,"exp":"Pacing and repetition can build emotional intensity and emphasis in a spoken text, working alongside the literal content of the words to strengthen the overall persuasive effect."},{"id":"sde103018","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Literary Devices — Narrative Techniques","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E3","q":"Which best describes a 'frame narrative' (a story within a story)?","options":["a story with no characters","a narrative structure where one story contains, or 'frames', another story told within it","a story told entirely through dialogue","a story with no clear beginning or end"],"answer":1,"exp":"A frame narrative is a structure where one outer story contains, or 'frames', another story told within it, often by a character recounting events to another character."},{"id":"sde103019","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Literary Devices","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E3","q":"Which best describes 'juxtaposition' as a literary device, when comparing two texts?","options":["placing two contrasting ideas, characters, or images close together to highlight their differences","describing only one idea throughout an entire text","always placing similar ideas together to emphasise similarity","a technique used only in non-fiction writing"],"answer":0,"exp":"Juxtaposition places two contrasting ideas, characters, or images close together, highlighting their differences through direct comparison."},{"id":"sde103020","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Comparative Analysis — Context","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E3","q":"Which best explains why comparing the historical or cultural CONTEXT of two texts can deepen analysis?","options":["context never affects how a text should be interpreted","understanding the time, place, and circumstances in which each text was written can reveal why writers made certain choices or held certain assumptions","context is only relevant for ancient texts, not modern ones","comparing context is the same as comparing plot"],"answer":1,"exp":"Understanding the historical or cultural context surrounding a text's creation can reveal why a writer made certain choices, held certain assumptions, or addressed particular concerns relevant to their time."},{"id":"sde103021","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Literary Devices","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E3","q":"Which best describes a 'motif' that recurs across multiple texts being compared?","options":["a single, one-time image with no broader significance","a recurring image, symbol, or idea that appears across different points in a text, or even across multiple texts, often reinforcing a shared theme","a type of punctuation mark","a structural feature only found in poetry"],"answer":1,"exp":"A motif is a recurring image, symbol, or idea, which can reinforce a theme within a single text, or be compared across multiple texts addressing similar concerns."},{"id":"sde103022","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Literary Devices","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E3","q":"Which best describes 'black comedy' (dark humour) as a literary technique?","options":["humour that deals with serious, taboo, or tragic subjects in a way that provokes uneasy laughter","humour that only ever discusses cheerful, light topics","a complete absence of any comedic elements","humour used exclusively in children's literature"],"answer":0,"exp":"Black comedy (dark humour) deals with serious, taboo, or tragic subjects in a way that provokes uneasy or uncomfortable laughter, often used for social or psychological commentary."},{"id":"sde103023","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Comparative Analysis — Imagery","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E3","q":"When comparing two writers' use of imagery, what might a focus on harsh, jagged sensory descriptions (as opposed to soft, flowing ones) suggest about each writer's intended mood?","options":["imagery has no connection to mood at all","harsh, jagged imagery often suggests tension, conflict, or unease, while soft, flowing imagery often suggests calm or harmony","both types of imagery always create exactly the same mood","imagery only matters in poetry, never in prose"],"answer":1,"exp":"Harsh, jagged sensory descriptions often suggest tension, conflict, or unease, while soft, flowing imagery often suggests calm or harmony, giving clues about each writer's intended mood."},{"id":"sde103024","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Literary Devices — Narrative Techniques","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E3","q":"Which best describes an 'unreliable narrator'?","options":["a narrator whose credibility is compromised, whether through bias, limited knowledge, or deliberate deception, requiring readers to question their account","a narrator who always tells the complete, objective truth","a narrator who never speaks in the first person","a narrator only found in non-fiction writing"],"answer":0,"exp":"An unreliable narrator's credibility is compromised in some way, whether through personal bias, limited knowledge, or deliberate deception, requiring readers to critically question their account of events."},{"id":"sde103025","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Literary Devices","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E3","q":"Which best describes 'pathetic fallacy' as a literary device?","options":["attributing human emotions to nature or the environment, often to reflect a character's inner state","a logical error in an argument","a type of formal apology within a text","a narrative told entirely without any descriptive language"],"answer":0,"exp":"Pathetic fallacy attributes human emotions to nature or the environment (such as a 'gloomy sky' or 'angry sea'), often used to reflect or amplify a character's inner emotional state."},{"id":"sde104001","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Author's Purpose","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E4","q":"Read: 'Why We Should Reconsider the Four-Day School Week\n\nFor more than a century, the five-day school week has been treated as an unquestioned fixture of education, as natural and immovable as the existence of summer holidays. Yet a small but growing number of schools, both in Australia and internationally, have begun trialling a four-day model — and the results deserve more serious attention than they have so far received.\n\nThe most common objection is immediate and intuitive: less time in school must surely mean less learning. This assumes, however, that classroom hours translate directly and proportionally into educational outcomes — an assumption that several trials have begun to complicate. Schools adopting a four-day week typically extend each remaining day, preserving most or all instructional hours rather than simply cutting them. Early results from several such trials suggest that student engagement and teacher retention improve, while academic outcomes remain largely stable rather than declining.\n\nCritics raise a fair point about working families: a missing school day creates genuine logistical and financial strain for parents who cannot simply rearrange their own work schedules to match. This is not a trivial concern, and any serious four-day proposal must address it directly, whether through subsidised care programs on the off day or partnerships with community organisations. Dismissing the four-day model on this basis alone, however, mistakes a solvable logistical problem for a fundamental flaw in the underlying idea.\n\nA subtler argument concerns teacher wellbeing and retention, an issue rarely placed at the centre of these debates despite its obvious downstream importance for students. Teacher burnout and attrition have reached levels that many education systems openly acknowledge as a crisis, and the four-day model — even accounting for longer remaining days — appears in early data to meaningfully reduce burnout indicators among trial participants. A school that cannot retain experienced, well-supported teachers is unlikely to serve its students well regardless of how many days it operates.\n\nNone of this constitutes definitive proof that every school should adopt a four-day model immediately. The trials remain small, relatively recent, and not yet replicated at sufficient scale to draw firm conclusions. What they do suggest is that an assumption many of us have never seriously questioned — that more days in the classroom straightforwardly means better outcomes — deserves rather more scrutiny than the reflexive dismissal it usually receives.'\n\nWhat assumption does the writer challenge in the second paragraph?","options":["that students always prefer shorter school weeks","that classroom hours translate directly and proportionally into educational outcomes","that teachers are always overworked","that four-day school weeks are illegal"],"answer":1,"exp":"The writer explicitly challenges 'an assumption... that classroom hours translate directly and proportionally into educational outcomes'."},{"id":"sde104002","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E4","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nHow do schools adopting a four-day week typically address the reduction in days, according to the passage?","options":["they simply cut total instructional hours","they extend each remaining day, preserving most or all instructional hours","they eliminate all extracurricular activities","they reduce the number of subjects taught"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage states these schools 'typically extend each remaining day, preserving most or all instructional hours rather than simply cutting them'."},{"id":"sde104003","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E4","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat concern about working families does the writer acknowledge in the third paragraph?","options":["families cannot afford school fees","a missing school day creates genuine logistical and financial strain for parents","families disagree with the entire concept of school","working families have no children in school"],"answer":1,"exp":"The writer acknowledges this creates 'genuine logistical and financial strain for parents who cannot simply rearrange their own work schedules'."},{"id":"sde104004","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Persuasive Techniques","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E4","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat does the writer suggest in response to this concern about working families?","options":["the concern should be completely dismissed as irrelevant","any serious proposal must address it directly, such as through subsidised care programs","working families should simply quit their jobs","the four-day model should never be implemented anywhere"],"answer":1,"exp":"The writer states 'any serious four-day proposal must address it directly, whether through subsidised care programs... or partnerships with community organisations'."},{"id":"sde104005","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E4","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat issue does the fourth paragraph argue is 'rarely placed at the centre of these debates', despite its importance?","options":["school transport logistics","teacher wellbeing and retention","the cost of textbooks","the length of school holidays"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage states 'teacher wellbeing and retention, an issue rarely placed at the centre of these debates despite its obvious downstream importance for students'."},{"id":"sde104006","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Author's Purpose","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E4","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat is the writer's overall conclusion in the final paragraph?","options":["every school should immediately adopt a four-day model","the trials prove definitively that four-day weeks always work","the underlying assumption about classroom days deserves more scrutiny, though the evidence isn't yet conclusive","four-day school weeks have been proven to be a complete failure"],"answer":2,"exp":"The writer concludes that 'an assumption... deserves rather more scrutiny', while explicitly noting 'none of this constitutes definitive proof' and that trials remain small and not yet replicated at scale."},{"id":"sde104007","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Vocabulary in Context","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E4","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat does the word 'reflexive' mean in the final sentence ('the reflexive dismissal it usually receives')?","options":["carefully considered after lengthy debate","automatic and unthinking, without careful consideration","extremely rare and unusual","based on strong scientific evidence"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Reflexive\" means automatic and unthinking, similar to a reflex action — suggesting the dismissal of this idea often happens without careful consideration."},{"id":"sde104008","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Persuasive Techniques","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E4","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhich best describes the persuasive strategy the writer uses throughout this passage?","options":["dismissing all opposing concerns without any acknowledgment","presenting a carefully qualified case, acknowledging genuine concerns while arguing the issue deserves more serious consideration","using purely emotional appeals with no evidence at all","refusing to take any position on the issue"],"answer":1,"exp":"Throughout the passage, the writer acknowledges genuine concerns (working families, limited trial evidence) while still arguing the underlying issue deserves more serious consideration than it typically receives."},{"id":"sde104009","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Literal Comprehension","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E4","q":"Read: 'Inheritance\n\nMy grandfather's hands, in the one photograph\nthat survived the move, the flood, the decade\nnobody photographed anything —\nthick-knuckled, holding a wrench\nthe way some men hold a child,\ncareful and absent-minded at once.\n\nI never knew him well enough\nto inherit anything specific —\nno trade, no specific skill passed down\nhand to hand across a workbench.\nAnd yet, my own hands, lately,\ndoing something as ordinary as fixing a hinge,\nmove in a way I don't recognise as mine,\na kind of muscle memory\nfor a memory I don't actually have.\n\nIs this what inheritance means,\nonce you strip away the house, the money,\nthe things you can argue over in a lawyer's office?\nSome residue of a person\nsettling, uninvited, into your own gestures,\nyour own quiet competence with tools\nyou were never taught to use\nby the man whose hands you apparently borrowed\nwithout either of you agreeing to the loan.\n\nI don't believe in ghosts, particularly.\nBut I believe, now, in this —\nthat something of a person\ncan survive in the angle of a wrist,\nthe unconscious choice\nto hold a tool a particular way,\npassed down through no mechanism\nanyone has ever managed to properly explain.'\n\nWhat does the speaker say they 'never knew well enough' to directly inherit?","options":["any money or property","a trade or specific skill passed down hand to hand","their grandfather's name","a house"],"answer":1,"exp":"The poem states 'I never knew him well enough to inherit anything specific — no trade, no specific skill passed down hand to hand across a workbench'."},{"id":"sde104010","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Inference","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E4","q":"Read the same poem.\n\nWhat surprising observation does the speaker make about their own hands in the second stanza?","options":["their hands are identical in appearance to their grandfather's","their hands move in an unfamiliar way while doing ordinary tasks, as if remembering something the speaker never actually learned","their hands are unable to do any practical tasks","their hands have been injured in an accident"],"answer":1,"exp":"The speaker describes their hands moving 'in a way I don't recognise as mine, a kind of muscle memory for a memory I don't actually have'."},{"id":"sde104011","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Inference","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E4","q":"Read the same poem.\n\nIn the third stanza, what does the speaker suggest 'inheritance' might really mean, beyond material possessions?","options":["inheritance is purely about legal documents and money","some intangible trace of a person settling into one's own unconscious gestures and habits","inheritance always requires direct teaching","inheritance is entirely imaginary and meaningless"],"answer":1,"exp":"The speaker suggests inheritance might involve 'some residue of a person settling, uninvited, into your own gestures', beyond 'the house, the money'."},{"id":"sde104012","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Writer's Craft","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E4","q":"Read the same poem.\n\nWhat is the effect of the phrase 'without either of you agreeing to the loan' at the end of the third stanza?","options":["it suggests a formal legal contract was involved","it extends the financial metaphor (borrowing/loan) in an unexpected, slightly humorous way to describe an involuntary, unspoken inheritance","it suggests the grandfather was angry about the inheritance","it has no real literary effect"],"answer":1,"exp":"This phrase extends the metaphor of 'borrowing' hands into financial language ('loan', 'agreeing'), creating a slightly wry, unexpected way of describing something entirely involuntary and unspoken."},{"id":"sde104013","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Inference","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E4","q":"Read the same poem.\n\nWhat does the speaker mean by saying 'I don't believe in ghosts, particularly. / But I believe, now, in this' in the final stanza?","options":["the speaker has become religious","the speaker is drawing a deliberate contrast between supernatural belief and a more grounded, but still mysterious, sense of inherited trace or memory","the speaker is afraid of ghosts","the speaker no longer believes in their grandfather's existence"],"answer":1,"exp":"This contrast positions the speaker's experience as something real and felt, yet still mysterious and hard to explain — distinct from supernatural belief, but just as difficult to fully account for."},{"id":"sde104014","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Writer's Craft","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E4","q":"Read the same poem.\n\nWhich literary device is most prominent in the poem's central conceit of inherited physical gestures?","options":["onomatopoeia","an extended metaphor exploring inheritance as something physical and unconscious, rather than purely material","alliteration","a strict, traditional rhyme scheme"],"answer":1,"exp":"The poem develops an extended metaphor throughout, exploring 'inheritance' as something physical and unconscious (gestures, muscle memory) rather than purely material (money, property)."},{"id":"sde104015","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Writer's Craft","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E4","q":"Read the same poem.\n\nWhich best describes the overall structure of the poem, in terms of free verse versus strict form?","options":["the poem follows a strict, traditional rhyme scheme and fixed metre throughout","the poem is written in free verse, without a fixed rhyme scheme, allowing flexible, conversational phrasing","the poem is written entirely in rhyming couplets","the poem follows a strict haiku structure"],"answer":1,"exp":"The poem is written in free verse, without a fixed rhyme scheme or strict metre, allowing for flexible, conversational phrasing that suits its reflective, exploratory tone."},{"id":"sde104016","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Author's Purpose","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E4","q":"Read the same poem.\n\nWhich best describes the overall theme explored across this poem?","options":["the practical steps involved in fixing household objects","the mysterious, intangible ways a person's influence can persist in another's body and habits, beyond direct teaching or material inheritance","the importance of taking family photographs","a factual biography of the speaker's grandfather"],"answer":1,"exp":"The poem explores the mysterious, intangible ways a person's influence might persist in another's unconscious gestures and habits, distinct from direct teaching or material inheritance."},{"id":"sde104017","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Poetry Terms","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E4","q":"What is a 'volta' in a sonnet?","options":["the title of the poem","a turn or shift in argument, tone, or perspective, typically occurring partway through the poem","the final word of the poem","a type of rhyme scheme found only in haiku"],"answer":1,"exp":"A volta is a turn or shift in argument, tone, or perspective within a sonnet, typically occurring around the eighth or ninth line."},{"id":"sde104018","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Poetry Terms","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E4","q":"What is 'caesura' in poetry?","options":["a strong pause or break occurring within a line of poetry, often marked by punctuation","the very last line of a poem","a type of rhyme scheme","a poem with no title"],"answer":0,"exp":"A caesura is a strong pause or break occurring within a line of poetry, often created by punctuation, which can affect the poem's rhythm and emphasis."},{"id":"sde104019","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Literary Devices — Narrative Techniques","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E4","q":"What does it mean for a poem to use 'free indirect discourse'?","options":["a technique blending a character's inner thoughts with the narrator's voice, without using direct quotation","a poem written entirely in dialogue","a poem with no punctuation at all","a strict, traditional poetic form with fourteen lines"],"answer":0,"exp":"Free indirect discourse blends a character's inner thoughts or speech with the narrator's voice, without using direct quotation marks, creating a subtle blending of perspectives."},{"id":"sde104020","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Literary Devices","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E4","q":"Which best describes 'anaphora' as a literary device?","options":["the repetition of a word or phrase at the beginning of successive clauses or lines","a single use of alliteration","a type of question that doesn't expect an answer","the use of footnotes in formal writing"],"answer":0,"exp":"Anaphora is the repetition of a word or phrase at the beginning of successive clauses or lines, often used for emphasis or rhythmic effect."},{"id":"sde104021","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Poetry Terms","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E4","q":"Which best describes 'enjambment' and its typical effect on a poem's pacing?","options":["it always slows a poem down dramatically","it allows a sentence or phrase to continue onto the next line without a pause, which can create a sense of momentum or urgency","it has no real effect on pacing","it only occurs in poems with strict rhyme schemes"],"answer":1,"exp":"Enjambment allows a sentence or phrase to continue onto the next line without a pause, which can create a sense of momentum, urgency, or natural, conversational flow."},{"id":"sde104022","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Literary Devices","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E4","q":"Which best describes a 'conceit' in literary terms, particularly in poetry?","options":["a character's excessive pride","an extended, often elaborate metaphor that structures a significant portion of a poem or piece of writing","a brief, one-line simile","a type of formal apology"],"answer":1,"exp":"A conceit is an extended, often elaborate metaphor that structures a significant portion of a poem, exploring a comparison in depth rather than mentioning it briefly."},{"id":"sde104023","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Poetry Terms","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E4","q":"Which best describes 'consonance' as a sound device in poetry?","options":["the repetition of consonant sounds, often within or at the end of words, not necessarily at the start","the repetition of vowel sounds only","a strict rhyme scheme used in every stanza","the complete absence of any sound repetition"],"answer":0,"exp":"Consonance is the repetition of consonant sounds, often within or at the end of words, distinct from alliteration (which specifically repeats sounds at the START of words)."},{"id":"sde104024","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Poetry Terms","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E4","q":"Which best describes 'assonance' as a sound device in poetry?","options":["the repetition of vowel sounds within nearby words","the repetition of consonant sounds at the start of words","a type of strict rhyme scheme","the complete absence of rhythm"],"answer":0,"exp":"Assonance is the repetition of vowel sounds within nearby words, which can create internal rhyme-like effects without true rhyme."},{"id":"sde104025","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Literary Devices","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E4","q":"Which best describes the effect of an 'extended metaphor' that runs throughout an entire poem, such as comparing memory to a physical inheritance?","options":["it creates a single, isolated comparison with no further development","it builds a sustained, layered comparison that deepens as the poem progresses, allowing for more nuanced exploration of the central idea","it has no real effect on a poem's meaning","it can only be used in very short poems"],"answer":1,"exp":"An extended metaphor builds a sustained, layered comparison across a poem, allowing the writer to explore different facets and nuances of the central idea as it develops."},{"id":"sde75001","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Inference","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E5","q":"Read: 'The Lighthouse Keeper's Daughter\n\nMara had grown up believing the lighthouse was simply a tall white tower that flashed at night, nothing more remarkable than the kettle that whistled each morning or the gate that creaked when the wind blew from the south. It was only when her father fell ill, and she had to climb the spiral stairs alone for the first time, that she understood what the lighthouse actually was: a promise.\n\nEvery ninety seconds, without fail, the great lens had to turn. Ships further out than the eye could see depended on that rhythm — on the certainty that somewhere on this rocky point, someone was awake, someone was watching, someone had not fallen asleep at the one job that could not afford a single missed rotation.\n\nMara wound the mechanism the way her father had shown her a hundred times without her ever really paying attention, and felt the gears catch and begin their slow, grinding turn. Outside, the storm threw itself against the windows, and somewhere beyond the spray and the dark, she imagined a fishing boat catching sight of the light's return and adjusting its course, the way it had every night for sixty years.\n\nShe stayed at the top until dawn, not because the mechanism needed constant attention, but because she found she could not leave. There was something in standing watch — in being the one thing in the world that did not waver — that made the cold and the noise and her aching arms feel like the smallest part of what she was actually doing.'\n\nWhat does Mara come to understand about the lighthouse, after climbing the stairs alone?","options":["that it is simply a tall white tower","that it represents a promise — a dependable presence that ships rely on","that her father had been exaggerating its importance","that the mechanism is too complicated for her to operate"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage states Mara understood 'what the lighthouse actually was: a promise', referring to the dependable presence ships rely on."},{"id":"sde75002","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Author's Purpose","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E5","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhy does the writer mention that the lens 'had to turn' every ninety seconds 'without fail'?","options":["to show that the mechanism is unreliable","to emphasise the critical importance of consistency and reliability for the ships depending on it","to suggest that ninety seconds is an unusually long time","to indicate that Mara finds the job boring"],"answer":1,"exp":"This detail emphasises the critical importance of unwavering consistency, since ships depend entirely on this dependable rhythm."},{"id":"sde75003","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Inference","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E5","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhy does Mara stay at the top of the lighthouse until dawn, even though 'the mechanism needed constant attention' is specifically said NOT to be the reason?","options":["she is trapped by the storm and cannot leave","she feels a sense of purpose and connection to the act of 'standing watch' that goes beyond the mechanical task itself","she has fallen asleep and doesn't realise dawn has come","she is afraid of the dark stairwell"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage explains she stays because of 'something in standing watch... that made the cold and noise... feel like the smallest part of what she was actually doing', suggesting a deeper sense of purpose."},{"id":"sde75004","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Vocabulary in Context","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E5","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat does the word 'wavered' mean as used in the final paragraph?","options":["moved quickly","stayed completely still and unchanging","became uncertain or unsteady","made a loud noise"],"answer":2,"exp":"\"Wavered\" means to become uncertain or unsteady. Here, it describes how Mara wanted to be the one constant, unwavering thing in a chaotic storm."},{"id":"sde75005","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Interpreting Mood","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E5","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhich best describes the overall mood created in this passage?","options":["lighthearted and comedic","tense and quietly reverent","angry and confrontational","confused and chaotic"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage combines the tension of the storm with a quiet, reverent tone toward the responsibility Mara has taken on, creating a tense yet respectful mood."},{"id":"sde75006","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Punctuation — Apostrophes","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E5","q":"Which sentence correctly uses an apostrophe to show possession?","options":["The dogs bone was buried in the yard.","The dog's bone was buried in the yard.","The dogs' bone was buried in the yard, since there is only one dog.","The dog bone's was buried in the yard."],"answer":1,"exp":"Since there is one dog, the apostrophe goes before the 's': \"The dog's bone\"."},{"id":"sde75007","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Active and Passive Voice","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E5","q":"Which sentence is written in the active voice?","options":["The cake was baked by Maria.","Maria baked the cake.","The cake had been baked.","The cake was being baked."],"answer":1,"exp":"In active voice, the subject performs the action directly: \"Maria baked the cake\" — Maria is the one doing the baking."},{"id":"sde75008","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Parts of Speech — Conjunctions","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E5","q":"Which word is a conjunction in this sentence: 'I wanted to go outside, but it was raining.'","options":["wanted","outside","but","raining"],"answer":2,"exp":"\"But\" is a conjunction, joining the two parts of the sentence together while showing contrast."},{"id":"sde75009","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Punctuation — Semicolons","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E5","q":"Which sentence correctly uses a semicolon?","options":["I love reading; especially mystery novels.","I love reading; my sister prefers movies.","I love reading, my sister; prefers movies.","I; love reading my sister prefers movies."],"answer":1,"exp":"A semicolon correctly joins two independent, related clauses: \"I love reading\" and \"my sister prefers movies\" are both complete sentences."},{"id":"sde75010","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E5","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'reluctant'?","options":["eager","unwilling","confident","curious"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Unwilling\" matches the meaning of 'reluctant', describing hesitation or unwillingness to do something."},{"id":"sde75011","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E5","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'meticulous'?","options":["careless","extremely careful and precise","very fast","disorganised"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Extremely careful and precise\" matches the meaning of 'meticulous'."},{"id":"sde75012","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Word Origins — Roots","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E5","q":"What is the root word in 'unbreakable'?","options":["un","break","able","unbreak"],"answer":1,"exp":"The root word is 'break', with the prefix 'un-' and suffix '-able' added to it."},{"id":"sde75013","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Word Origins — Prefixes","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E5","q":"Which prefix means 'before', as in 'precede' or 'preview'?","options":["pre-","post-","sub-","inter-"],"answer":0,"exp":"The prefix 'pre-' means 'before', as seen in words like 'precede' (to go before) and 'preview' (to view beforehand)."},{"id":"sde75014","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Figurative Language","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E5","q":"Which sentence contains a simile?","options":["The wind howled like a wolf.","The wind was the wolf's howl.","The wind howled loudly.","The wind made a howling noise."],"answer":0,"exp":"A simile makes a comparison using 'like' or 'as'. \"The wind howled like a wolf\" compares the wind's sound to a wolf using 'like'."},{"id":"sde75015","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Figurative Language","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E5","q":"Which sentence contains a metaphor?","options":["Her smile was like sunshine.","Her smile was sunshine.","Her smile looked happy.","Her smile reminded him of sunshine."],"answer":1,"exp":"A metaphor directly states one thing IS another, without using 'like' or 'as'. \"Her smile was sunshine\" directly equates the smile with sunshine."},{"id":"sde75016","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Direct and Indirect Speech","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E5","q":"Which sentence uses indirect (reported) speech correctly?","options":["She said, \"I am tired.\"","She said that she was tired.","She said \"that she is tired\".","She is tired, she said."],"answer":1,"exp":"Indirect speech reports what was said without quotation marks, often shifting the tense: \"She said that she was tired.\""},{"id":"sde75017","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Parts of Speech — Adverbs","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E5","q":"Which word in this sentence is an adverb: 'She spoke quietly during the meeting.'","options":["spoke","quietly","during","meeting"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Quietly\" is an adverb, describing HOW she spoke."},{"id":"sde75018","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Grammar — Subject-Verb Agreement","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E5","q":"Which sentence demonstrates correct subject-verb agreement?","options":["The group of students are studying.","The group of students is studying.","The group of students were study.","The group of student is studying."],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Group\" is a singular collective noun, so it takes the singular verb \"is\": \"The group of students is studying.\""},{"id":"sde75019","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Author's Purpose","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E5","q":"Which best describes the purpose of a persuasive text?","options":["to simply entertain the reader","to convince the reader to accept a particular viewpoint or take a specific action","to provide only neutral, factual information with no viewpoint","to confuse the reader intentionally"],"answer":1,"exp":"A persuasive text aims to convince the reader to accept a particular viewpoint or take a specific action, using techniques like evidence, emotional appeals, and rhetorical questions."},{"id":"sde75020","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Punctuation — Quotation Marks","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E5","q":"Which sentence correctly uses quotation marks?","options":["She said I am hungry.","She said, \"I am hungry.\"","She said, I am hungry.","She said \"I am hungry\"."],"answer":1,"exp":"Direct speech requires quotation marks around the exact words spoken, with a comma before the opening quotation mark: She said, \"I am hungry.\""},{"id":"sde75021","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E5","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'persevere'?","options":["to give up easily","to continue trying despite difficulty","to celebrate success","to ignore a problem"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"To continue trying despite difficulty\" matches the meaning of 'persevere'."},{"id":"sde75022","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Sentence Types","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E5","q":"Which sentence is a compound sentence (joining two independent clauses)?","options":["She ran quickly to the store.","She ran to the store, and she bought some milk.","Running quickly, she went to the store.","She ran to the store because she needed milk."],"answer":1,"exp":"A compound sentence joins two independent clauses (each a complete sentence) with a coordinating conjunction: \"She ran to the store\" and \"she bought some milk\", joined by \"and\"."},{"id":"sde75023","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Word Origins — Suffixes","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E5","q":"What is the suffix in the word 'happiness'?","options":["happi-","-ness","happy","-ess"],"answer":1,"exp":"The suffix '-ness' is added to the root 'happy' (with a spelling change) to form 'happiness', meaning the state of being happy."},{"id":"sde75024","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E5","q":"Which word is most similar in meaning to 'enormous'?","options":["tiny","massive","average","fragile"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Massive\" is most similar in meaning to 'enormous', both describing something very large."},{"id":"sde75025","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Text Structure","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E5","q":"Which best describes the structure of a narrative text?","options":["it always presents only factual arguments","it typically follows a sequence of events involving characters, setting, and a problem or conflict","it never includes any dialogue","it must always be written in the present tense"],"answer":1,"exp":"A narrative text typically follows a sequence of events involving characters and a setting, often built around a problem or conflict that drives the story forward."},{"id":"sde76001","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Author's Purpose","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E6","q":"Read: 'Why Every School Should Have a Vegetable Garden\n\nPicture this: a patch of dirt behind the school hall, transformed over a single term into rows of lettuce, tomatoes, and herbs, all grown and harvested by students themselves. It sounds simple, even small. But the truth is, a school vegetable garden might be one of the most valuable additions any school could make.\n\nConsider the facts. Studies consistently show that students who grow their own food are significantly more likely to actually eat vegetables — not just tolerate them, but genuinely enjoy them. When you've spent six weeks watching a carrot grow from a tiny seed, pulling it from the ground yourself feels like an achievement worth tasting.\n\nBeyond nutrition, a garden teaches patience in a world that rarely allows for it. Nothing about growing vegetables can be rushed. Seeds don't sprout because you're impatient for results, and tomatoes don't ripen on command. Students who spend time in a garden learn, almost without realising it, that some of the best things in life simply cannot be hurried.\n\nCritics might argue that schools already have too much on their plates (no pun intended) without adding garden maintenance to the list. But a garden need not be a burden. With student rosters, a few enthusiastic teachers, and perhaps a handful of parent volunteers, the workload becomes entirely manageable — and the rewards, both nutritional and educational, are simply too significant to ignore.\n\nIt's time for every school to dig in.'\n\nWhat is the writer's main contention in this passage?","options":["that vegetable gardens are too expensive for schools to maintain","that every school should have a vegetable garden, due to its nutritional and educational benefits","that students dislike growing their own vegetables","that gardens should replace all other subjects in school"],"answer":1,"exp":"The writer's main contention, stated directly in the title and reinforced throughout, is that every school should have a vegetable garden due to its benefits."},{"id":"sde76002","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Persuasive Techniques","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E6","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhich persuasive technique is used in the opening line, 'Picture this: a patch of dirt behind the school hall...'?","options":["statistics","a rhetorical question","an invitation for the reader to visualise a scenario","a direct quote from an expert"],"answer":2,"exp":"\"Picture this\" directly invites the reader to visualise the scenario being described, drawing them into the idea before the argument is fully presented."},{"id":"sde76003","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Persuasive Techniques","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E6","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhy does the writer address the counterargument that 'schools already have too much on their plates'?","options":["to abandon the original argument entirely","to acknowledge a likely objection and then explain why it doesn't outweigh the benefits, strengthening the overall argument","because the writer agrees completely with this objection","this detail has no persuasive purpose"],"answer":1,"exp":"By acknowledging this objection and then countering it, the writer demonstrates awareness of practical concerns while reinforcing that the benefits still outweigh the workload — a common persuasive strategy."},{"id":"sde76004","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Writer's Craft","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E6","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat does the phrase 'too much on their plates (no pun intended)' demonstrate about the writer's tone?","options":["the writer is being entirely serious and formal throughout","the writer uses light humour and wordplay, given the relevant pun about food, to keep the tone engaging","the writer is criticising schools harshly","the writer has made an accidental error"],"answer":1,"exp":"This phrase uses a deliberate pun (relating to both 'too busy' and literally 'plates' of food), demonstrating the writer's light, engaging humour within an otherwise persuasive piece."},{"id":"sde76005","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Writer's Craft","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E6","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhich best describes the final line, 'It's time for every school to dig in'?","options":["a literal instruction to start digging immediately","a call to action, using a pun on 'dig in' (both gardening and committing enthusiastically) to reinforce the central message","an unrelated, random comment","a direct quote from a study"],"answer":1,"exp":"This final line is a call to action, cleverly using the dual meaning of 'dig in' (literally gardening, and figuratively committing wholeheartedly) to reinforce the passage's central message memorably."},{"id":"sde76006","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Persuasive Techniques","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E6","q":"Which persuasive technique involves citing numbers or research findings to support an argument?","options":["rhetorical question","statistics","anecdote","repetition"],"answer":1,"exp":"Statistics involve citing numbers or research findings to support an argument with seemingly objective evidence."},{"id":"sde76007","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Persuasive Techniques","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E6","q":"Which sentence uses a rhetorical question for persuasive effect?","options":["The weather is quite cold today.","Don't we all deserve a cleaner environment?","I went to the store yesterday.","The cat sat on the windowsill."],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Don't we all deserve a cleaner environment?\" is a rhetorical question, asked to make a persuasive point rather than to genuinely seek an answer."},{"id":"sde76008","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E6","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'significant'?","options":["unimportant","important or noteworthy","tiny","uncertain"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Important or noteworthy\" matches the meaning of 'significant'."},{"id":"sde76009","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E6","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'manageable'?","options":["impossible","able to be handled or controlled","extremely difficult","unnecessary"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Able to be handled or controlled\" matches the meaning of 'manageable'."},{"id":"sde76010","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Punctuation — Colons","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E6","q":"Which sentence correctly uses a colon?","options":["She needed three things: milk, eggs, and bread.","She needed: three things, milk, eggs, and bread.","She needed three things; milk, eggs, and bread.","She needed three: things milk, eggs, and bread."],"answer":0,"exp":"A colon correctly introduces a list after a complete independent clause: \"She needed three things: milk, eggs, and bread.\""},{"id":"sde76011","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Punctuation — Commas","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E6","q":"Which sentence correctly uses commas in a list?","options":["I bought apples bananas and oranges.","I bought apples, bananas, and oranges.","I bought, apples bananas and oranges.","I bought apples, bananas and, oranges."],"answer":1,"exp":"Commas should separate each item in a list: \"I bought apples, bananas, and oranges.\""},{"id":"sde76012","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Parts of Speech — Prepositions","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E6","q":"Which word in this sentence is a preposition: 'The cat jumped over the fence.'","options":["jumped","over","fence","cat"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Over\" is a preposition, showing the relationship between the cat's jump and the fence."},{"id":"sde76013","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Sentence Types","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E6","q":"Which sentence correctly identifies a simple sentence (one independent clause)?","options":["The dog barked loudly.","The dog barked loudly, and the cat ran away.","Because the dog barked, the cat ran away.","The dog, which was barking loudly, scared the cat."],"answer":0,"exp":"\"The dog barked loudly\" is a simple sentence, containing exactly one independent clause with a single subject and verb."},{"id":"sde76014","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Persuasive Techniques","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E6","q":"Which best describes 'emotive language' as a persuasive technique?","options":["language with no emotional content at all","words specifically chosen to provoke a strong emotional response in the reader","a type of formal, technical vocabulary","language used only in scientific writing"],"answer":1,"exp":"Emotive language uses words specifically chosen to provoke a strong emotional response in the reader, such as fear, excitement, or sympathy."},{"id":"sde76015","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E6","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'enthusiastic'?","options":["bored","showing great excitement or interest","angry","confused"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Showing great excitement or interest\" matches the meaning of 'enthusiastic'."},{"id":"sde76016","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Word Origins — Roots","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E6","q":"What is the root word in 'disagreement'?","options":["dis","agree","ment","disagree"],"answer":1,"exp":"The root word is 'agree', with the prefix 'dis-' and suffix '-ment' added to it."},{"id":"sde76017","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Word Origins — Suffixes","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E6","q":"Which suffix, added to a verb, often creates a noun meaning 'the act of doing something', as in 'movement' or 'agreement'?","options":["-ment","-ish","-ful","-less"],"answer":0,"exp":"The suffix '-ment' added to a verb often creates a noun describing the act or result of that action, as in 'move'→'movement'."},{"id":"sde76018","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Figurative Language","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E6","q":"Which sentence contains personification (giving human qualities to a non-human thing)?","options":["The wind blew strongly.","The wind whispered through the trees.","The wind was very cold.","The wind moved the leaves."],"answer":1,"exp":"\"The wind whispered\" gives the wind a human quality (whispering), which is an example of personification."},{"id":"sde76019","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Persuasive Techniques","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E6","q":"Which best describes the purpose of including statistics in a persuasive text?","options":["statistics have no real persuasive function","statistics lend an air of objective, factual credibility to an argument, making it seem more convincing","statistics are only used to confuse readers","statistics always make an argument weaker"],"answer":1,"exp":"Including statistics lends an air of objective, factual credibility to an argument, often making it seem more convincing and well-researched to readers."},{"id":"sde76020","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Commonly Confused Words","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E6","q":"Which sentence correctly uses 'their', 'there', or 'they're'?","options":["Their going to the park later.","There going to the park later.","They're going to the park later.","Theyre going to the park later."],"answer":2,"exp":"\"They're\" is the correct contraction of 'they are': \"They're going to the park later.\""},{"id":"sde76021","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E6","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'tremendous'?","options":["tiny","very great in amount or extent","disappointing","ordinary"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Very great in amount or extent\" matches the meaning of 'tremendous'."},{"id":"sde76022","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Author's Purpose","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E6","q":"Which best describes the difference between a fact and an opinion in persuasive writing?","options":["facts and opinions are exactly the same thing","a fact can be objectively verified as true, while an opinion expresses a personal belief or judgement","opinions are always more reliable than facts","facts are never used in persuasive writing"],"answer":1,"exp":"A fact can be objectively verified as true (such as a measurable statistic), while an opinion expresses a personal belief or judgement that others might reasonably disagree with."},{"id":"sde76023","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Punctuation — Commas","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E6","q":"Which sentence demonstrates correct use of a comma after an introductory phrase?","options":["After the rain stopped we went outside.","After the rain stopped, we went outside.","After, the rain stopped we went outside.","After the rain, stopped we went outside."],"answer":1,"exp":"A comma should follow an introductory phrase before the main clause begins: \"After the rain stopped, we went outside.\""},{"id":"sde76024","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E6","q":"Which word is an antonym (opposite) of 'reluctant'?","options":["hesitant","unwilling","eager","nervous"],"answer":2,"exp":"\"Eager\" is the opposite of 'reluctant' — one describes enthusiasm, the other describes unwillingness."},{"id":"sde76025","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"7","topic":"Persuasive Techniques","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G7-E6","q":"Which best describes an effective concluding statement in a persuasive text?","options":["it should introduce a brand new, unrelated argument","it should reinforce the central message, often with a memorable final thought or call to action","it should simply repeat the title word for word","conclusions are unnecessary in persuasive writing"],"answer":1,"exp":"An effective conclusion reinforces the central message, often ending with a memorable final thought or a clear call to action, leaving a lasting impression on the reader."},{"id":"sde85001","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Inference","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E5","q":"Read: 'The Last Bus\n\nTheo had missed the last bus exactly once before, when he was eleven, and his father had driven forty minutes through the rain to collect him without a single word of complaint. He had assumed, in the careless way children assume things, that this kind of rescue would always be available — that there would always be someone on the other end of a phone call, ready to come.\n\nStanding now at the empty bus stop at sixteen, watching the taillights of the 9:47 disappear around the corner three minutes before he'd actually arrived, Theo understood with sudden, uncomfortable clarity that his father was seventy minutes away on a work trip, that his mother's phone had been switched off for the night, and that the only person who could solve this particular problem was, for the first time in his memory, himself.\n\nHe sat down on the cold metal bench and considered his actual options. He had eleven dollars. He had a phone with twelve percent battery. He had legs that could, technically, walk the nine kilometres home, though probably not before sunrise. None of these felt like solutions exactly, but laid out together, they felt like something — the beginning, at least, of a plan he would have to build by himself, out of whatever he actually had, rather than what he wished he had.\n\nIt wasn't a comfortable feeling. But walking the first kilometre toward the all-night service station, his phone's torch cutting a small circle of light ahead of him, Theo noticed something else underneath the discomfort: something that, if he was honest, felt almost like the beginning of being trusted with himself.'\n\nWhat assumption did Theo previously hold, based on his experience at age eleven?","options":["that he would never miss a bus again","that someone would always be available to rescue him from this kind of problem","that his father disliked driving in the rain","that buses always run late"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage states he assumed 'this kind of rescue would always be available', based on his father's earlier response."},{"id":"sde85002","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Inference","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E5","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat does Theo realise with 'sudden, uncomfortable clarity' at the bus stop?","options":["that he has plenty of money for a taxi","that, for the first time, he must solve this problem entirely on his own","that the bus driver made a mistake","that his parents will be very angry with him"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage states he realises 'the only person who could solve this particular problem was... himself', a new and uncomfortable realisation."},{"id":"sde85003","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Writer's Craft","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E5","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhy does the writer list Theo's specific resources (eleven dollars, twelve percent battery, legs that could walk) in such precise detail?","options":["to make the passage longer with no real purpose","to emphasise the limited, concrete reality Theo must work with, rather than an idealised solution","to show that Theo is wealthy","to suggest that Theo has given up entirely"],"answer":1,"exp":"Listing these specific, limited resources emphasises the concrete reality Theo actually has to work with, grounding the story in believable, practical detail rather than an idealised rescue."},{"id":"sde85004","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Interpreting Mood","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E5","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat does the phrase 'the beginning of being trusted with himself' suggest about Theo's emotional state by the end of the passage?","options":["he feels only fear and regret","alongside discomfort, he senses an unexpected, positive feeling of growing independence and self-reliance","he feels nothing at all","he wishes his father were there to rescue him"],"answer":1,"exp":"This phrase suggests that, alongside the discomfort, Theo senses a positive, unexpected feeling — a growing sense of independence and self-trust."},{"id":"sde85005","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Author's Purpose","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E5","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhich best describes the central theme of this passage?","options":["the unreliability of public transport","the unexpected discovery of self-reliance through a difficult, unplanned situation","the importance of always having a fully charged phone","the dangers of walking at night"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage centres on Theo's unexpected discovery of self-reliance and independence, prompted by an unplanned, difficult situation he must navigate alone."},{"id":"sde85006","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Grammar — Gerunds","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E5","q":"Which sentence correctly demonstrates a gerund (a verb form acting as a noun)?","options":["She is running quickly.","Running is her favourite exercise.","She will run tomorrow.","She ran very fast."],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Running\" in \"Running is her favourite exercise\" acts as a noun (the subject of the sentence) — this is a gerund."},{"id":"sde85007","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Grammar — Appositives","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E5","q":"Which sentence correctly uses an appositive (a phrase that renames or describes a noun, set off by commas)?","options":["My brother who lives in Sydney visited last week.","My brother, a doctor in Sydney, visited last week.","My brother is a doctor and lives in Sydney.","My brother lives, in Sydney, as a doctor."],"answer":1,"exp":"\"A doctor in Sydney\" is an appositive, renaming/describing 'my brother', set off correctly by commas."},{"id":"sde85008","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Grammar — Verb Tense","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E5","q":"Which sentence is written in the past perfect tense?","options":["She had finished her homework before dinner.","She finishes her homework before dinner.","She will finish her homework before dinner.","She is finishing her homework before dinner."],"answer":0,"exp":"\"Had finished\" is the past perfect tense, describing an action completed before another past action (dinner)."},{"id":"sde85009","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Grammar — Parallel Structure","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E5","q":"Which sentence correctly demonstrates parallel structure?","options":["She likes hiking, swimming, and to bike.","She likes hiking, swimming, and biking.","She likes to hike, swimming, and biking.","She likes hiking, to swim, and biking."],"answer":1,"exp":"Parallel structure requires matching grammatical forms in a list: \"hiking, swimming, and biking\" all use the consistent '-ing' form."},{"id":"sde85010","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Grammar — Who vs Whom","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E5","q":"Which sentence correctly uses 'who' versus 'whom'?","options":["Whom is going to the party?","Who is going to the party?","To who should I give this?","Who did you give this to him?"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Who\" is used as the subject of a sentence: \"Who is going to the party?\" (who is doing the action, going)."},{"id":"sde85011","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Punctuation — Comma Splices","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E5","q":"Which sentence correctly uses a comma splice's CORRECTED version (joining two independent clauses properly)?","options":["I was tired, I went to bed early.","I was tired; I went to bed early.","I was tired I went to bed early.","I was tired, and I went, to bed early."],"answer":1,"exp":"A semicolon correctly joins two independent clauses without needing a conjunction: \"I was tired; I went to bed early.\""},{"id":"sde85012","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Punctuation — Dashes","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E5","q":"Which sentence correctly uses an em dash for emphasis or interruption?","options":["She was, surprisingly calm about it.","She was — surprisingly — calm about it.","She was; surprisingly calm; about it.","She was: surprisingly calm: about it."],"answer":1,"exp":"Em dashes can be used to set off an interrupting phrase for emphasis: \"She was — surprisingly — calm about it.\""},{"id":"sde85013","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Punctuation — Ellipses","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E5","q":"Which sentence correctly uses an ellipsis to show an omission or trailing thought?","options":["She said, \"I don't know if...\"","She said, \"I don't know if,,,\"","She said \"I don't know if...\" the end.","She said, I don't... know if."],"answer":0,"exp":"An ellipsis (three dots) correctly shows a trailing or incomplete thought: \"I don't know if...\""},{"id":"sde85014","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E5","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'ambiguous'?","options":["perfectly clear","open to more than one interpretation","extremely confident","completely false"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Open to more than one interpretation\" matches the meaning of 'ambiguous'."},{"id":"sde85015","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E5","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'inevitable'?","options":["avoidable","certain to happen","extremely unlikely","completely random"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Certain to happen\" matches the meaning of 'inevitable'."},{"id":"sde85016","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Word Origins — Roots","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E5","q":"What is the root word in 'transportation'?","options":["trans","port","ation","transport"],"answer":3,"exp":"The root word is 'transport', with the suffix '-ation' added to form the noun 'transportation'."},{"id":"sde85017","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Literary Terms","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E5","q":"Which sentence correctly identifies an example of irony?","options":["The fire station burned down.","The fire station was painted red.","The fire station had new equipment.","The fire station was very busy."],"answer":0,"exp":"It's ironic that a fire station — designed to prevent fires — burned down itself, since this directly contradicts its very purpose."},{"id":"sde85018","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Grammar — Modifiers","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E5","q":"Which sentence demonstrates correct modifier placement?","options":["Running quickly, the bus was missed by Theo.","Running quickly, Theo missed the bus.","Theo missed the bus, running quickly.","The bus running quickly was missed by Theo."],"answer":1,"exp":"The modifying phrase 'Running quickly' should describe the person actually doing the running (Theo), not the bus: \"Running quickly, Theo missed the bus.\""},{"id":"sde85019","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Evaluating Evidence","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E5","q":"Which best describes the purpose of evaluating evidence in a non-fiction text?","options":["evidence should always be accepted without question","to assess whether the evidence is relevant, credible, and sufficient to support the claim being made","evaluating evidence is unnecessary in non-fiction writing","evidence is only relevant in scientific writing"],"answer":1,"exp":"Evaluating evidence involves assessing whether it is relevant, credible, and sufficient to genuinely support the claim being made, rather than simply accepting it at face value."},{"id":"sde85020","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E5","q":"Which word is most similar in meaning to 'candid'?","options":["secretive","honest and straightforward","aggressive","confused"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Honest and straightforward\" matches the meaning of 'candid'."},{"id":"sde85021","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Grammar — Mood","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E5","q":"Which sentence demonstrates correct use of the subjunctive mood (expressing a hypothetical or wish)?","options":["If I was rich, I would travel.","If I were rich, I would travel.","If I am rich, I would travel.","If I will be rich, I would travel."],"answer":1,"exp":"The subjunctive mood uses 'were' (not 'was') for hypothetical situations: \"If I were rich, I would travel.\""},{"id":"sde85022","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Figurative Language","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E5","q":"Which sentence contains a metaphor?","options":["Time flew by quickly.","Time is a thief, stealing moments we never get back.","Time passed slowly today.","Time felt like it was moving fast."],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Time is a thief\" directly equates time with a thief, without using 'like' or 'as' — this is a metaphor."},{"id":"sde85023","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E5","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'autonomy'?","options":["dependence","independence and self-governance","confusion","weakness"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Independence and self-governance\" matches the meaning of 'autonomy'."},{"id":"sde85024","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Word Origins — Suffixes","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E5","q":"What is the suffix in the word 'resourceful'?","options":["re-","source","-ful","-source"],"answer":2,"exp":"The suffix '-ful' means 'full of', added to 'resource' to mean 'full of resourcefulness or ingenuity'."},{"id":"sde85025","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Text Structure","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E5","q":"Which best describes the structure typically used in narrative non-fiction (such as a personal recount)?","options":["it never follows any chronological order","events are usually presented in a sequence, often building toward a reflection or realisation at the end","it must always be written in the third person","it never includes the writer's own thoughts or feelings"],"answer":1,"exp":"Narrative non-fiction typically presents events in a sequence, often building toward a reflection, insight, or realisation by the end of the piece."},{"id":"sde86001","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Author's Purpose","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E6","q":"Read: 'Should Homework Be Optional?\n\nFor generations, homework has been treated as an unquestioned fixture of school life — assigned nightly, expected without debate, and rarely interrogated for whether it actually achieves what it claims to. It might be time to ask a genuinely uncomfortable question: what if making homework optional would benefit students more than mandating it?\n\nProponents of mandatory homework typically argue that it reinforces classroom learning and builds discipline. There is some truth here. Practice does matter for skill retention, particularly in subjects like mathematics. But this argument quietly assumes that all homework is well-designed, purposeful, and genuinely connected to what was taught — an assumption that doesn't survive contact with how homework is often actually assigned: as a default, a habit, rather than a deliberate pedagogical choice.\n\nConsider the alternative. If homework were optional, but genuinely well-designed and clearly valuable, students motivated by mastery (rather than mere compliance) would still choose to do it. Teachers, meanwhile, would face real pressure to ensure their assigned work was worth a student's voluntary time — a check on quality that mandatory homework, precisely because it requires no buy-in, currently lacks entirely.\n\nCritics will object that many students, given the choice, would simply do nothing. This is probably true for some. But it raises an uncomfortable question of its own: if homework only \"works\" because students have no choice in the matter, what does that suggest about whether the homework itself was ever actually worth doing?\n\nNone of this proves optional homework is straightforwardly better. But it does suggest the current mandatory default deserves more scrutiny than it typically receives.'\n\nWhat is the writer's main contention in this passage?","options":["that homework should be banned entirely","that the assumption homework should be mandatory deserves more scrutiny than it typically receives","that all homework is poorly designed","that only mathematics homework has any value"],"answer":1,"exp":"The writer's main contention, stated in the final paragraph, is that 'the current mandatory default deserves more scrutiny than it typically receives' — a more nuanced position than simply banning homework."},{"id":"sde86002","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Persuasive and Rhetorical Techniques","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E6","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhy does the writer acknowledge that 'practice does matter for skill retention' before continuing the argument?","options":["to abandon the argument and agree with mandatory homework entirely","to demonstrate balance by conceding a genuine point, before explaining why it doesn't fully justify the current mandatory approach","because this detail is irrelevant to the argument","to confuse the reader deliberately"],"answer":1,"exp":"By conceding this genuine point before continuing, the writer demonstrates balance and fairness, which can strengthen the overall argument's credibility before explaining why it doesn't fully justify the current approach."},{"id":"sde86003","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Persuasive and Rhetorical Techniques","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E6","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhich rhetorical technique is used in the question, 'what does that suggest about whether the homework itself was ever actually worth doing?'","options":["a statistic","a rhetorical question, prompting the reader to question the underlying assumption","a direct quote from a study","an example of emotive language only"],"answer":1,"exp":"This is a rhetorical question, not seeking a literal answer but instead prompting the reader to critically question the underlying assumption about homework's value."},{"id":"sde86004","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Vocabulary in Context","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E6","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat does the word 'scrutiny' mean as used in the final paragraph?","options":["careless approval","close, critical examination","complete rejection","enthusiastic support"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Scrutiny\" means close, critical examination. The writer suggests the mandatory homework default deserves more careful, critical examination."},{"id":"sde86005","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Comparative Analysis","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E6","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhich best describes the overall structure of this argumentative passage?","options":["it presents only one side of the argument with no acknowledgment of counterarguments","it raises a question, considers and partially concedes a counterargument, presents an alternative, addresses an objection, then offers a carefully qualified conclusion","it is a simple narrative with no argumentative structure","it presents only statistics with no analysis"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage moves through raising a question, conceding a genuine counterpoint, presenting an alternative, addressing an objection, and arriving at a carefully qualified conclusion — a structured argumentative progression."},{"id":"sde86006","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Grammar — Absolute Phrases","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E6","q":"Which sentence correctly uses an absolute phrase (a phrase modifying an entire sentence, not just one word)?","options":["Her hands trembling, she opened the letter.","She opened the letter with her hands trembling.","Her hands were trembling as she opened the letter.","She, trembling, opened the letter."],"answer":0,"exp":"\"Her hands trembling\" is an absolute phrase, modifying the entire main clause (\"she opened the letter\") rather than just a single word within it."},{"id":"sde86007","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Grammar — Infinitives","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E6","q":"Which sentence correctly uses an infinitive (the base form of a verb with 'to')?","options":["She enjoys swimming.","She wants to swim.","She is swimming.","She swam yesterday."],"answer":1,"exp":"\"To swim\" is an infinitive — the base form of the verb 'swim' preceded by 'to'."},{"id":"sde86008","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Grammar — Pronoun Reference","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E6","q":"Which sentence demonstrates correct pronoun reference (a clear, unambiguous antecedent)?","options":["When Sarah met Anna, she was nervous.","Sarah was nervous when she met Anna.","Sarah met Anna, and she was nervous, though it's unclear who.","When Sarah and Anna met, she was nervous."],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Sarah was nervous when she met Anna\" clearly establishes that 'she' refers to Sarah, avoiding ambiguity about who the pronoun refers to."},{"id":"sde86009","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Grammar — Sentence Fragments","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E6","q":"Which of these is a sentence fragment (an incomplete sentence)?","options":["She ran to the store.","Running to the store quickly.","She ran to the store quickly.","She ran, and she was quick."],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Running to the store quickly\" lacks a subject and complete verb structure, making it an incomplete sentence (a fragment)."},{"id":"sde86010","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Grammar — Subjunctive Mood","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E6","q":"Which sentence correctly uses the subjunctive mood?","options":["I wish I was taller.","I wish I were taller.","I wish I am taller.","I wish I will be taller."],"answer":1,"exp":"The subjunctive mood uses 'were' (not 'was') for hypothetical wishes: \"I wish I were taller.\""},{"id":"sde86011","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Literary Terms","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E6","q":"Which best describes a 'logical fallacy' in an argument?","options":["a perfectly valid form of reasoning","a flaw in reasoning that undermines an argument's logical validity","a type of literary device","a factual error unrelated to logic"],"answer":1,"exp":"A logical fallacy is a flaw in reasoning that undermines an argument's logical validity, even if it might seem persuasive on the surface."},{"id":"sde86012","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Literary Terms","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E6","q":"Which sentence demonstrates an example of a straw man fallacy?","options":["My opponent wants better school funding; clearly they think money fixes everything, which is absurd.","My opponent wants better school funding and provided supporting research.","My opponent disagrees, but offers no real evidence.","My opponent and I actually agree on this point."],"answer":0,"exp":"This statement misrepresents the opponent's actual position (wanting better funding) into an exaggerated, easier-to-attack claim (that money fixes everything) — a straw man fallacy."},{"id":"sde86013","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E6","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'scrutiny'?","options":["careless glance","close, critical examination","complete ignorance","enthusiastic praise"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Close, critical examination\" matches the meaning of 'scrutiny'."},{"id":"sde86014","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E6","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'pedagogical'?","options":["relating to teaching or education","relating to cooking","relating to sports","relating to finance"],"answer":0,"exp":"\"Relating to teaching or education\" matches the meaning of 'pedagogical'."},{"id":"sde86015","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Word Origins — Roots","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E6","q":"What is the root word in 'interrogated'?","options":["inter","rogat","ed","interrogate"],"answer":3,"exp":"The root word is 'interrogate', with the suffix '-ed' added to form the past tense."},{"id":"sde86016","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Punctuation — Ellipses","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E6","q":"Which sentence correctly uses an ellipsis to indicate hesitation or trailing thought?","options":["I'm not sure... maybe we should wait.","I'm not sure, maybe, we should wait.","I'm not sure: maybe we should wait.","I'm not sure; maybe we should wait."],"answer":0,"exp":"An ellipsis (three dots) effectively conveys hesitation or a trailing thought: \"I'm not sure... maybe we should wait.\""},{"id":"sde86017","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Punctuation — Semicolons","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E6","q":"Which sentence correctly uses a semicolon to join two related independent clauses?","options":["She studied hard; she passed the exam.","She studied hard, she passed the exam.","She studied hard; and she passed the exam.","She studied; hard she passed the exam."],"answer":0,"exp":"A semicolon correctly joins two related, independent clauses without needing a conjunction: \"She studied hard; she passed the exam.\""},{"id":"sde86018","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Vocabulary in Context","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E6","q":"Which best describes 'compliance' as opposed to genuine motivation?","options":["compliance and genuine motivation are exactly the same thing","compliance involves following a rule simply because it's required, while genuine motivation comes from internal interest or value placed on the task","compliance is always a stronger driver of effort than genuine motivation","genuine motivation only applies to adults, not students"],"answer":1,"exp":"Compliance involves following a rule simply because it's required (often without internal buy-in), while genuine motivation comes from an internal sense of interest or value placed on the task itself."},{"id":"sde86019","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E6","q":"Which word is most similar in meaning to 'mandate'","options":["suggestion","an official requirement or order","an optional choice","a casual request"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"An official requirement or order\" matches the meaning of 'mandate'."},{"id":"sde86020","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Clauses","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E6","q":"Which sentence demonstrates correct comma usage with a nonessential clause?","options":["My teacher who is very strict gave us extra homework.","My teacher, who is very strict, gave us extra homework.","My teacher who, is very strict, gave us extra homework.","My teacher, who is very strict gave us, extra homework."],"answer":1,"exp":"A nonessential clause (extra information not essential to the sentence's basic meaning) should be set off by commas on both sides: \"My teacher, who is very strict, gave us extra homework.\""},{"id":"sde86021","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Clauses","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E6","q":"Which best describes the difference between an essential and nonessential clause?","options":["they mean exactly the same thing","an essential clause is necessary to identify the noun it describes, while a nonessential clause simply adds extra, removable information","nonessential clauses are always longer than essential clauses","essential clauses are always set off by commas"],"answer":1,"exp":"An essential clause is necessary to identify which specific noun is being discussed, while a nonessential clause adds extra information that could be removed without changing the sentence's core meaning."},{"id":"sde86022","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E6","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'uncomfortable', as used to describe a confronting question?","options":["pleasant","causing unease or discomfort","entirely irrelevant","extremely boring"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Causing unease or discomfort\" matches the meaning of 'uncomfortable' in this context."},{"id":"sde86023","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Essay Structure — Counter-Arguments","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E6","q":"Which best describes the purpose of presenting a counterargument before refuting it, within a persuasive essay?","options":["counterarguments should never be included in persuasive writing","addressing a counterargument demonstrates awareness of opposing views and can strengthen the writer's own position when effectively countered","including a counterargument always weakens the writer's case","counterarguments are only used in narrative writing"],"answer":1,"exp":"Addressing a counterargument demonstrates awareness of opposing views and can actually strengthen the writer's own position when that counterargument is effectively and convincingly countered."},{"id":"sde86024","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Grammar — Gerunds","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E6","q":"Which word in this sentence functions as a gerund: 'Reading before bed helps me relax.'","options":["before","helps","Reading","relax"],"answer":2,"exp":"\"Reading\" functions as a gerund here, acting as the subject (a noun) of the sentence."},{"id":"sde86025","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"8","topic":"Grammar — Participial Phrases","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard","paper":"G8-E6","q":"Which sentence demonstrates correct use of a participial phrase (a phrase starting with a verb's -ing or -ed form, acting as an adjective)?","options":["Exhausted from the long day, Maria collapsed onto the couch.","Maria, exhausted, the long day collapsed onto the couch.","Maria collapsed the long day onto the couch exhausted.","Exhausted, the long day Maria collapsed onto the couch."],"answer":0,"exp":"\"Exhausted from the long day\" is a participial phrase, describing Maria, correctly placed at the start of the sentence next to the noun it modifies."},{"id":"sde95001","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Inference","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E5","q":"Read: 'The Cartographer's Apprentice\n\nElin had spent three years learning to draw coastlines that did not yet exist on any map, copying her master's careful lines until her own hand could no longer tell the difference between his certainty and her imitation of it. It was only when he sent her, alone, to survey the eastern headland — a stretch of coast he himself had never walked — that she understood the difference between drawing a map and making one.\n\nThe cliffs did not match his teaching. The currents pulled wrong, against everything the old charts implied about that stretch of water. For a full day, Elin stood at the headland's edge, paralysed by a question she had never had to ask before: when the evidence in front of you contradicts everything you were taught to trust, which do you believe?\n\nShe chose, eventually, to believe the cliffs. She redrew the coastline as it actually was, not as her master's training said it should be, and felt something close to fear as she did it — not because she doubted her own eyes, but because she understood, perhaps for the first time, that a map is not a neutral record of the world. It is an argument about what the world is, made by whoever holds the pen.\n\nWhen she returned and showed her master the corrected chart, he studied it for a long time without speaking. Then he said only this: \"I drew that coastline forty years ago, from a ship too far out to see it properly. I have been waiting a long time for someone willing to tell me I was wrong.\"\n\nIt was not the apology Elin had expected. It was, she realised, something better: an admission that the map had always been waiting for someone braver than its original author.'\n\nWhat does Elin come to understand about the difference between 'drawing a map and making one'?","options":["that drawing and making are exactly the same skill","that drawing involves copying existing knowledge, while making one requires trusting her own direct observation, even against established authority","that her master never actually taught her anything useful","that maps are entirely arbitrary with no connection to reality"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage shows Elin moving from copying her master's lines (drawing) to trusting her own observation of the cliffs over established teaching (making) — a deeper, more independent form of understanding."},{"id":"sde95002","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Inference","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E5","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhy does Elin feel 'something close to fear' when redrawing the coastline?","options":["she is afraid of the cliffs themselves","she realises a map is an argument about reality made by whoever draws it, not a neutral fact, and this responsibility feels significant","she doubts her own observational skills","she is afraid her master will be impressed"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage explains her fear comes from understanding 'that a map is not a neutral record... It is an argument about what the world is', a significant responsibility she hadn't previously grasped."},{"id":"sde95003","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Inference","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E5","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat does the master's response reveal about his own character?","options":["he is angry and defensive about being corrected","he demonstrates humility and has been hoping, for decades, that someone would have the courage to challenge his error","he refuses to accept that he was wrong","he is indifferent to the discovery"],"answer":1,"exp":"His statement that he has 'been waiting a long time for someone willing to tell me I was wrong' reveals humility and a genuine, long-held hope for correction, rather than defensiveness."},{"id":"sde95004","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Author's Purpose","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E5","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhich best describes the central theme of this passage?","options":["the unreliability of all maps","the courage required to trust direct evidence over inherited authority, and the humility required to welcome being corrected","the importance of never questioning one's teachers","the technical difficulty of cartography"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage centres on two related ideas: the courage required to trust direct evidence over inherited authority (Elin's choice), and the humility required to welcome being corrected (the master's response)."},{"id":"sde95005","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Writer's Craft","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E5","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat is the effect of ending the passage with the description of the map 'waiting for someone braver than its original author'?","options":["it suggests the map was always flawed and worthless","it reframes the correction not as a failure, but as a fulfilment of the map's deeper purpose — to eventually reflect the truth, regardless of who achieves that","it has no particular significance","it suggests the master will redraw the map himself"],"answer":1,"exp":"This ending reframes the correction positively — not as exposing a failure, but as fulfilling the map's deeper purpose of eventually reflecting the truth, regardless of who ultimately achieves that."},{"id":"sde95006","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Grammar — Absolute Phrases","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E5","q":"Which sentence correctly demonstrates an absolute phrase?","options":["Her courage tested, Elin made her decision.","Elin, her courage was tested, made her decision.","Elin's courage tested her, and made her decision.","Tested, her courage Elin made her decision."],"answer":0,"exp":"\"Her courage tested\" is an absolute phrase, modifying the entire main clause that follows."},{"id":"sde95007","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Grammar — Subjunctive Mood","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E5","q":"Which sentence demonstrates correct subjunctive mood usage?","options":["If she was wrong, she would admit it.","If she were wrong, she would admit it.","If she is wrong, she would admit it.","If she will be wrong, she would admit it."],"answer":1,"exp":"The subjunctive mood uses 'were' for hypothetical situations: \"If she were wrong, she would admit it.\""},{"id":"sde95008","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Grammar — Sentence Fragments","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E5","q":"Which sentence contains a sentence fragment?","options":["She walked to the headland.","Walking slowly toward the cliffs.","She walked slowly toward the cliffs.","She walked, and the wind was strong."],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Walking slowly toward the cliffs\" lacks a clear subject and complete verb structure, making it an incomplete sentence fragment."},{"id":"sde95009","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Literary Terms","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E5","q":"Which best describes the literary term 'foil', as applied to two contrasting characters?","options":["a character with no particular function in the plot","a character whose contrasting traits highlight or emphasise the qualities of another character","a synonym for the protagonist","a character who always agrees with the protagonist"],"answer":1,"exp":"A foil is a character whose contrasting traits highlight or emphasise the qualities of another character, often the protagonist."},{"id":"sde95010","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Literary Terms","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E5","q":"Which best describes 'dramatic irony', as a literary technique?","options":["when a character tells a joke","when the audience knows something a character does not, creating tension about how the character will react upon learning it","a synonym for a plot twist","a technique used only in comedic writing"],"answer":1,"exp":"Dramatic irony occurs when the audience knows something a character does not, creating tension or anticipation about how the character will react upon discovering the truth."},{"id":"sde95011","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Vocabulary in Context","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E5","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'paralysed', as used to describe Elin standing at the headland?","options":["energised","unable to act or move, due to fear or uncertainty","extremely excited","completely confident"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Unable to act or move, due to fear or uncertainty\" matches the meaning of 'paralysed' in this emotional context."},{"id":"sde95012","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Vocabulary in Context","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E5","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'authority', as used in the context of established teaching?","options":["confusion","an accepted source of expertise or trusted knowledge","complete uncertainty","a minor detail"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"An accepted source of expertise or trusted knowledge\" matches the meaning of 'authority' in this context."},{"id":"sde95013","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Punctuation — Commas","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E5","q":"Which sentence demonstrates correct comma usage with an introductory absolute phrase?","options":["Her hands steady she began to draw.","Her hands steady, she began to draw.","Her hands, steady she began, to draw.","Her, hands steady she began to draw."],"answer":1,"exp":"An introductory absolute phrase should be followed by a comma before the main clause begins: \"Her hands steady, she began to draw.\""},{"id":"sde95014","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Punctuation — Dashes","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E5","q":"Which sentence correctly uses an em dash to set off a dramatic or emphasised point?","options":["She had one fear — being wrong.","She had one fear, being wrong.","She had one fear; being wrong.","She had one fear: being, wrong."],"answer":0,"exp":"An em dash can dramatically set off a final, emphasised point: \"She had one fear — being wrong.\""},{"id":"sde95015","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Word Origins — Roots","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E5","q":"What is the root word in 'cartographer'?","options":["carto","graph","er","cartograph"],"answer":3,"exp":"The root combines 'carto' (map) and 'graph' (writing/drawing), with '-er' added to mean 'one who draws maps'."},{"id":"sde95016","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Evaluating Evidence","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E5","q":"Which best describes the purpose of 'evaluating evidence' when reading a persuasive or informational text?","options":["evidence should always be accepted without question, regardless of source","to assess the credibility, relevance, and sufficiency of evidence before accepting a claim it supports","evaluating evidence is unnecessary for skilled readers","evidence evaluation only applies to scientific texts"],"answer":1,"exp":"Evaluating evidence involves assessing its credibility, relevance, and sufficiency before accepting the claim it's meant to support, rather than taking it at face value."},{"id":"sde95017","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Clauses","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E5","q":"Which sentence demonstrates a clause functioning as a sentence fragment when written incorrectly?","options":["Because the evidence contradicted her training.","Because the evidence contradicted her training, she redrew the map.","The evidence contradicted her training.","She redrew the map because the evidence contradicted her training."],"answer":0,"exp":"\"Because the evidence contradicted her training\" is a dependent clause on its own, which is a sentence fragment without an attached independent clause."},{"id":"sde95018","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E5","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'humility', as demonstrated by the master's response?","options":["arrogance","a modest, unassuming attitude, especially about one's own importance or correctness","extreme confidence","indifference"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"A modest, unassuming attitude, especially about one's own importance or correctness\" matches the meaning of 'humility'."},{"id":"sde95019","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Grammar — Absolute Phrases","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E5","q":"Which best describes 'absolute phrases' and their typical function in a sentence?","options":["they always function as the main verb of a sentence","they add descriptive detail about a condition related to the entire main clause, without being grammatically connected by a conjunction","they can only appear at the very end of a sentence","they always require a comma before AND after, regardless of position"],"answer":1,"exp":"Absolute phrases add descriptive detail about a condition related to the entire main clause, without needing a connecting conjunction, often appearing at the start or end of a sentence."},{"id":"sde95020","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Punctuation — Comma Splices","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E5","q":"Which sentence demonstrates a comma splice (an error joining two independent clauses)?","options":["She redrew the map, it took several hours.","She redrew the map; it took several hours.","She redrew the map, and it took several hours.","Redrawing the map took several hours."],"answer":0,"exp":"\"She redrew the map, it took several hours\" incorrectly joins two independent clauses with only a comma — this is a comma splice error."},{"id":"sde95021","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Literary Terms","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E5","q":"Which best describes 'allegory' as a literary form?","options":["a narrative in which characters, events, or settings symbolically represent broader ideas","a single, brief metaphor used once in a text","a strictly factual historical account","a type of unreliable narration"],"answer":0,"exp":"An allegory is a narrative in which characters, events, or settings symbolically represent broader ideas, often moral, political, or social, extending across the entire work."},{"id":"sde95022","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E5","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'imitation', as used to describe Elin's early map-copying?","options":["an original creation","a copy or reproduction of something else","a complete rejection","an improvement"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"A copy or reproduction of something else\" matches the meaning of 'imitation'."},{"id":"sde95023","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Sentence Types","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E5","q":"Which sentence correctly uses a subordinating conjunction to form a complex sentence?","options":["She was nervous, but she continued.","Although she was nervous, she continued.","She was nervous, and she continued.","She was nervous; she continued."],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Although\" is a subordinating conjunction, creating a complex sentence by joining a dependent clause to an independent one."},{"id":"sde95024","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Evaluating Evidence","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E5","q":"Which best describes the function of 'evaluating evidence' specifically when a text presents competing claims?","options":["always trust whichever claim was stated first","weigh the relative credibility, relevance, and strength of evidence behind each competing claim before reaching a conclusion","evidence evaluation is unnecessary if both claims sound confident","always trust whichever source uses more emotional language"],"answer":1,"exp":"When a text presents competing claims, careful evaluation involves weighing the relative credibility, relevance, and strength of evidence behind each one, rather than simply trusting confidence or emotional appeal."},{"id":"sde95025","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Literary Terms","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E5","q":"Which best describes 'pathetic fallacy' as a literary technique?","options":["attributing human emotions to nature or the weather, often to reflect a character's internal state","a factual error made by the author","a type of rhyme scheme","dialogue that reveals a character is lying"],"answer":0,"exp":"Pathetic fallacy attributes human emotions to nature or weather (such as a 'gloomy sky'), often used to reflect or reinforce a character's internal emotional state."},{"id":"sde96001","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Author's Purpose","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E6","q":"Read: 'On the Myth of the \"Natural\" Talent\n\nWe tell a particular story about achievement that sounds generous but is, on closer inspection, quietly cruel: the idea that exceptional people were simply born that way, touched early by a gift the rest of us were never given. It is a comforting story for those who never try, since it removes the sting of comparison. But it is a deeply inaccurate one, and worse, it actively discourages the very effort that produces what we mistake for natural talent.\n\nConsider what actually lies behind almost every example of apparent \"natural\" ability: thousands of hours of deliberate, often unglamorous practice, usually beginning so early in childhood that the effort itself becomes invisible to observers who only encounter the finished result. We see the violinist's effortless performance; we do not see the eight years of scales that preceded it. We see the novelist's seemingly natural voice; we do not see the drawers full of rejected drafts.\n\nThis is not to say that innate variation plays no role whatsoever — clearly, starting points differ, and some capacities are more easily developed than others for different people. But the dominant explanatory weight we assign to \"natural talent\" is wildly disproportionate to the evidence, and that disproportion has a real cost: it teaches people, especially young people, that struggling with a new skill is evidence they lack some essential, unteachable quality, rather than evidence that they are simply early in a process every expert also had to pass through.\n\nIf we told the truth about effort instead — that exceptional ability is, overwhelmingly, the visible residue of invisible practice — we might produce fewer people who give up at the first sign of difficulty, mistaking a normal stage of learning for proof that they were never cut out for it in the first place.'\n\nWhat is the writer's central contention in this passage?","options":["that natural talent does not exist in any form","that the dominant cultural narrative overstates 'natural talent' and understates the role of deliberate practice, with real costs for learners","that practice is unnecessary for achieving expertise","that all people have exactly equal natural ability"],"answer":1,"exp":"The writer's central contention is that we overstate 'natural talent' relative to deliberate practice, and this has a real cost in discouraging learners — while still acknowledging some role for innate variation."},{"id":"sde96002","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Persuasive and Rhetorical Techniques","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E6","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhy does the writer include the concession that 'innate variation plays' some role?","options":["to abandon the original argument entirely","to demonstrate intellectual honesty and nuance, avoiding an overstated claim, before reinforcing the main point about disproportionate emphasis","because the writer secretly disagrees with the whole argument","this detail has no persuasive purpose"],"answer":1,"exp":"This concession demonstrates intellectual honesty and nuance, avoiding an overstated claim, which can strengthen the argument's credibility before reinforcing the main point about disproportionate emphasis."},{"id":"sde96003","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Vocabulary in Context","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E6","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat does the phrase 'visible residue of invisible practice' suggest about the relationship between talent and effort?","options":["that talent and effort are completely unrelated","that what looks like natural talent is actually the visible result of effort that mostly went unseen by observers","that effort is irrelevant once talent is established","that visible practice is more valuable than invisible practice"],"answer":1,"exp":"This phrase suggests that what we perceive as natural talent is actually the visible result ('residue') of extensive practice that mostly happened unseen ('invisible') by those observing only the finished outcome."},{"id":"sde96004","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Persuasive and Rhetorical Techniques","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E6","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhich rhetorical technique is used in the repeated structure: 'We see the violinist's effortless performance; we do not see the eight years of scales...'?","options":["a rhetorical question","parallel structure, contrasting what is visible with what is hidden, to reinforce the argument's central point","a logical fallacy","an unsupported statistic"],"answer":1,"exp":"This repeated parallel structure contrasts what is visible (the performance) with what is hidden (the practice), reinforcing the argument's central point through repetition and pattern."},{"id":"sde96005","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Interpreting Mood","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E6","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhich best describes the writer's tone throughout this passage?","options":["purely celebratory of natural talent","critical of the 'natural talent' narrative, while remaining measured and intellectually careful rather than dismissive","angry and inflammatory","entirely neutral with no discernible position"],"answer":1,"exp":"The writer maintains a measured, intellectually careful tone — acknowledging nuance — while still clearly criticising the dominant 'natural talent' narrative throughout."},{"id":"sde96006","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Persuasive and Rhetorical Techniques","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E6","q":"Which best describes 'ethos' as a mode of persuasion?","options":["an appeal based on logic","an appeal based on the credibility or character of the speaker","an appeal based on emotion","an appeal based on humour"],"answer":1,"exp":"Ethos is an appeal based on the credibility, character, or authority of the speaker, encouraging the audience to trust their judgement."},{"id":"sde96007","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Persuasive and Rhetorical Techniques","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E6","q":"Which best describes 'logos' as a mode of persuasion?","options":["an appeal based on the speaker's character","an appeal based on logical reasoning and evidence","an appeal based on emotion","an appeal based on humour"],"answer":1,"exp":"Logos is an appeal based on logical reasoning, evidence, and structured argument, appealing to the audience's rational judgement."},{"id":"sde96008","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Persuasive and Rhetorical Techniques","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E6","q":"Which best describes 'pathos' as a mode of persuasion?","options":["an appeal based on logic","an appeal based on credibility","an appeal based on emotion","an appeal based on statistics only"],"answer":2,"exp":"Pathos is an appeal based on emotion, designed to evoke feelings in the audience."},{"id":"sde96009","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Punctuation — Semicolons","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E6","q":"Which sentence demonstrates correct use of a semicolon to join two related independent clauses?","options":["Practice matters; talent alone is not enough.","Practice matters, talent alone is not enough.","Practice matters: talent alone is not enough is true.","Practice matters; and talent alone is not enough."],"answer":0,"exp":"A semicolon correctly joins two related, independent clauses: \"Practice matters; talent alone is not enough.\""},{"id":"sde96010","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Grammar — Nominalisation","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E6","q":"Which sentence demonstrates correct use of nominalisation (turning a verb or adjective into a noun)?","options":["She decided quickly.","Her quick decision surprised everyone.","She will decide soon.","Deciding is hard for her."],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Decision\" is a nominalisation of the verb 'decide', turning the action into a noun: \"Her quick decision surprised everyone.\""},{"id":"sde96011","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E6","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'disproportionate'?","options":["perfectly balanced","excessive or out of proportion relative to something else","extremely small","entirely absent"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Excessive or out of proportion relative to something else\" matches the meaning of 'disproportionate'."},{"id":"sde96012","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E6","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'innate', as used to describe natural ability?","options":["learned through practice","existing from birth, rather than acquired","completely random","extremely rare"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Existing from birth, rather than acquired\" matches the meaning of 'innate'."},{"id":"sde96013","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Logical Fallacies","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E6","q":"Which best describes the logical fallacy of 'hasty generalisation'?","options":["drawing a broad conclusion from a very small or unrepresentative sample","providing a well-supported statistic from a large, representative survey","acknowledging the limits of a small sample explicitly","citing a peer-reviewed academic study"],"answer":0,"exp":"A hasty generalisation draws a broad conclusion about an entire group based on a very small or unrepresentative sample."},{"id":"sde96014","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Logical Fallacies","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E6","q":"Which best describes the logical fallacy of 'false cause' (correlation implies causation)?","options":["assuming that because one event preceded another, it must have caused it, without sufficient evidence","providing a well-documented causal mechanism supported by evidence","acknowledging that correlation does not necessarily indicate causation","conducting a controlled experiment to test causation directly"],"answer":0,"exp":"A false cause fallacy assumes that because one event preceded another, it must have caused it, without sufficient supporting evidence."},{"id":"sde96015","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Academic Writing — Hedging","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E6","q":"Which sentence correctly demonstrates academic hedging language (avoiding overly absolute claims)?","options":["This always happens to everyone.","This appears to happen in many, though not all, cases.","This never happens to anyone.","This definitely happens to everyone, without exception."],"answer":1,"exp":"\"This appears to happen in many, though not all, cases\" uses hedging language ('appears', 'many, though not all') to avoid an overly absolute, unsupportable claim."},{"id":"sde96016","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Academic Writing — Hedging","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E6","q":"Which best describes the purpose of academic hedging language, such as 'may suggest' or 'it is possible that'?","options":["hedging language weakens an argument with no real benefit","hedging language allows a writer to make a claim with appropriate caution, avoiding overstatement beyond what the evidence actually supports","hedging language is only used by uncertain or poorly informed writers","hedging language should never appear in academic writing"],"answer":1,"exp":"Hedging language allows a writer to make a claim with appropriate caution, avoiding overstatement beyond what the actual evidence supports, which is a hallmark of careful, credible academic writing."},{"id":"sde96017","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E6","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'residue', as used to describe what remains after a process?","options":["the original starting material","what remains or is left behind after a process","a complete absence of anything","the most important part of something"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"What remains or is left behind after a process\" matches the meaning of 'residue'."},{"id":"sde96018","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Logical Fallacies","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E6","q":"Which sentence demonstrates a logical fallacy known as a 'false dichotomy'?","options":["You're either with us completely, or you're against us entirely.","There are several possible positions on this complex issue.","I disagree with this specific point, though I respect the overall argument.","This issue requires careful, nuanced consideration."],"answer":0,"exp":"\"You're either with us completely, or you're against us entirely\" presents only two extreme options, ignoring the likely existence of a middle ground — a false dichotomy."},{"id":"sde96019","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Persuasive and Rhetorical Techniques","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E6","q":"Which best describes why the writer's repeated use of 'we see... we do not see...' is rhetorically effective?","options":["it has no particular rhetorical effect","the repeated, parallel structure builds a memorable, cumulative contrast between visible outcomes and invisible effort","it confuses the reader through unnecessary repetition","it is a logical fallacy"],"answer":1,"exp":"The repeated, parallel structure builds a memorable, cumulative contrast between visible outcomes and invisible effort, reinforcing the argument through pattern and repetition."},{"id":"sde96020","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Vocabulary in Context","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E6","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'cruel', as used ironically to describe a 'comforting' story?","options":["kind and generous","causing pain or harm, often unintentionally","extremely helpful","completely neutral"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Causing pain or harm, often unintentionally\" matches the meaning of 'cruel' here, describing how a seemingly comforting story can actually cause harm."},{"id":"sde96021","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Persuasive and Rhetorical Techniques","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E6","q":"Which best describes the rhetorical technique of 'concession-rebuttal', as used in sophisticated argumentative writing?","options":["simply ignoring all opposing viewpoints entirely","acknowledging a valid point from an opposing view, before systematically countering it to reinforce the writer's overall position","abandoning one's own argument after hearing a counterpoint","repeating the same point multiple times without variation"],"answer":1,"exp":"A concession-rebuttal structure acknowledges a valid point from an opposing view, before systematically countering it, which can reinforce the writer's overall position by demonstrating fairness."},{"id":"sde96022","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E6","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'deliberate', as used to describe practice?","options":["accidental and unplanned","done with careful intention and purpose","extremely rare","completely passive"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Done with careful intention and purpose\" matches the meaning of 'deliberate'."},{"id":"sde96023","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Grammar — Appositives","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E6","q":"Which sentence demonstrates correct use of an appositive phrase?","options":["The author who wrote many books was famous.","The author, a prolific writer, was famous.","The author was, a prolific writer famous.","The author a prolific writer was famous."],"answer":1,"exp":"\"A prolific writer\" is an appositive, renaming/describing 'the author', correctly set off by commas."},{"id":"sde96024","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Persuasive and Rhetorical Techniques","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E6","q":"Which best describes why writers sometimes use rhetorical questions, such as 'which do you believe?', within an argumentative passage?","options":["rhetorical questions always require a direct written answer from the reader","they prompt the reader to actively engage with and reflect on the argument being made, rather than simply receiving information passively","rhetorical questions have no real persuasive function","rhetorical questions are only appropriate in casual conversation, never formal writing"],"answer":1,"exp":"Rhetorical questions prompt the reader to actively engage with and reflect on the argument being made, rather than simply receiving information passively, making the argument more personally engaging."},{"id":"sde96025","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"9","topic":"Persuasive and Rhetorical Techniques","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G9-E6","q":"Which best describes 'litotes' as a rhetorical device, often used for understated emphasis?","options":["a deliberate exaggeration for dramatic effect","a deliberate understatement, often using a negative construction, to express a point with restrained or ironic effect","a direct, unqualified statement of fact","a repeated rhyme pattern"],"answer":1,"exp":"Litotes uses deliberate understatement, often via a negative construction, to express a point with restrained or ironic effect (e.g. 'not bad' to mean 'very good')."},{"id":"sde105001","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Literary Devices — Satire","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E5","q":"Read: 'From \"The Committee for the Preservation of Things As They Are\" (satirical extract)\n\nThe Committee convened, as it always did, to discuss the alarming proposal that something, somewhere, might need to change. Chairperson Wexford-Ainsley called the meeting to order with his customary opening remark — \"I trust nothing of consequence has happened since we last met\" — and was visibly relieved when the Secretary confirmed that, indeed, nothing had.\n\nThe first item of business concerned a junior clerk who had suggested, with what the Committee generously agreed to call \"enthusiasm rather than malice,\" that the filing system might benefit from alphabetical rather than chronological-by-the-clerk's-mood ordering. The Committee debated this proposal for six hours, eventually concluding that while the clerk's suggestion was not, strictly speaking, wrong, it would set an unacceptable precedent: if filing could be improved, what else might people start suggesting could be improved? The proposal was filed under \"Matters Requiring Further Indefinite Consideration,\" a drawer that had not been opened since 1987.\n\nChairperson Wexford-Ainsley closed the meeting with his customary reminder that the Committee's founding motto — \"It Has Always Been Done This Way, And That Has Always Been Sufficient Reason\" — remained as true today as it had been entirely unexamined for the past forty years. The clerk, it was noted in the minutes, appeared to be quietly updating his résumé.'\n\nWhat is the writer satirising in this passage?","options":["the dangers of frequent organisational change","bureaucratic resistance to even minor, sensible change, and the absurd lengths institutions go to in order to avoid it","the importance of proper filing systems","the personal failings of a single junior clerk"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage satirises bureaucratic resistance to even minor, sensible change, exaggerating the absurd lengths an institution goes to in order to avoid any alteration to the status quo."},{"id":"sde105002","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Literary Devices — Irony","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E5","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhich best describes the irony in the Committee's founding motto, 'It Has Always Been Done This Way, And That Has Always Been Sufficient Reason'?","options":["there is no irony in this statement","the motto presents an unexamined assumption as though it were a carefully reasoned conclusion, highlighting the Committee's lack of genuine critical thought","the motto is a sincere, well-justified principle","the motto was written by the junior clerk"],"answer":1,"exp":"The irony lies in presenting a completely unexamined assumption (\"it's always been done this way\") as though it were a carefully reasoned conclusion, highlighting the Committee's actual lack of genuine critical thought."},{"id":"sde105003","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Literary Devices — Satire","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E5","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat does the detail of filing the proposal in a drawer 'not... opened since 1987' suggest about the Committee's true intentions?","options":["the Committee plans to revisit the proposal very soon","the Committee has no genuine intention of ever actually considering the proposal, despite the polite bureaucratic language used","the drawer is simply too full to open","the Committee values historical record-keeping"],"answer":1,"exp":"This detail reveals that the Committee has no genuine intention of ever considering the proposal — the polite bureaucratic process is simply a way of permanently burying it without appearing to outright reject it."},{"id":"sde105004","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Inference","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E5","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhat does the closing detail about the clerk 'updating his résumé' suggest?","options":["the clerk is satisfied with the Committee's decision","the clerk has likely concluded the organisation is too resistant to change and is considering leaving","the clerk is preparing for a promotion within the Committee","this detail has no particular significance"],"answer":1,"exp":"This closing detail suggests the clerk has likely concluded the organisation is too resistant to change, and is now considering leaving for somewhere more receptive to improvement."},{"id":"sde105005","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Interpreting Mood","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E5","q":"Read the same passage.\n\nWhich best describes the overall tone of this passage?","options":["earnest and emotional","drily satirical, using exaggeration and irony to mock institutional resistance to change","aggressive and openly hostile","completely neutral and factual"],"answer":1,"exp":"The passage maintains a drily satirical tone throughout, using exaggeration (six hours debating filing) and irony (the founding motto) to mock institutional resistance to change."},{"id":"sde105006","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Literary Devices — Satire","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E5","q":"Which best describes 'satire' as a literary technique?","options":["a sincere expression of admiration","using humour, irony, or exaggeration to criticise or expose flaws in individuals, society, or institutions","a strictly factual historical account","a type of formal academic essay"],"answer":1,"exp":"Satire uses humour, irony, or exaggeration to criticise or expose flaws in individuals, society, or institutions, often with a moral or corrective purpose."},{"id":"sde105007","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Literary Devices — Irony","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E5","q":"Which best describes 'situational irony'?","options":["when a speaker says the opposite of what they mean","when an outcome is strikingly different from what would normally be expected","a character telling a lie","a narrator addressing the reader directly"],"answer":1,"exp":"Situational irony occurs when an outcome is strikingly different from, or contrary to, what would normally be expected."},{"id":"sde105008","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Comparative Analysis","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E5","q":"Which best describes a key purpose of comparative analysis between two texts?","options":["to determine which text is objectively 'better' written","to explore how each text treats a shared idea or theme differently, deepening understanding of both","to summarise both plots side by side with no further analysis","comparison should be avoided in serious literary analysis"],"answer":1,"exp":"Comparative analysis explores how different texts treat a shared idea or theme, often in contrasting ways, deepening understanding of both texts rather than simply ranking them."},{"id":"sde105009","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Comparative Analysis — Imagery","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E5","q":"Which best describes why comparing two texts' use of IMAGERY around a shared theme can be analytically valuable?","options":["imagery has no real connection to a text's themes","different imagery choices can reveal different underlying attitudes or perspectives each text holds toward the shared theme","only one text can ever use imagery effectively","imagery comparison is only relevant for poetry"],"answer":1,"exp":"Different imagery choices can reveal different underlying attitudes or perspectives each text holds toward a shared theme, making such comparisons analytically valuable."},{"id":"sde105010","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Essay Structure","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E5","q":"Which best describes an effective thesis statement for an essay analysing satire in a text?","options":["it should simply state 'this text uses satire' with no further development","it should identify what specifically is being satirised and the techniques used to achieve this critique","it should summarise the entire plot of the text","it should avoid mentioning satire at all"],"answer":1,"exp":"An effective thesis statement should identify what specifically is being satirised (the target) and the techniques used to achieve this critique, providing a clear analytical focus for the essay."},{"id":"sde105011","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Essay Structure","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E5","q":"Which best describes the purpose of including specific textual evidence (such as a brief quote) when analysing satire?","options":["evidence is unnecessary when analysing humour","specific evidence demonstrates precisely how the satirical technique operates within the text, rather than making a vague, unsupported claim","quotes should always be avoided in essays about satire","textual evidence only matters for serious, non-humorous texts"],"answer":1,"exp":"Specific textual evidence demonstrates precisely how a satirical technique operates within the text, providing concrete support rather than a vague, unsupported claim about the text's humour or critique."},{"id":"sde105012","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Literary Devices","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E5","q":"Which best describes 'hyperbole' as a literary and rhetorical device?","options":["deliberate understatement for ironic effect","deliberate exaggeration, not meant to be taken literally, used for emphasis or comic effect","a direct, literal statement of fact","a type of rhyme scheme"],"answer":1,"exp":"Hyperbole is deliberate exaggeration, not meant to be taken literally, used for emphasis, emotional effect, or humour."},{"id":"sde105013","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E5","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'bureaucratic', as used to describe excessive procedural process?","options":["spontaneous and informal","characterised by excessive, rigid official procedure","extremely efficient and fast","entirely undocumented"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Characterised by excessive, rigid official procedure\" matches the meaning of 'bureaucratic'."},{"id":"sde105014","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E5","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'precedent', as used in the passage's discussion of the filing proposal?","options":["a future possibility with no historical basis","an earlier decision or action used as an example or justification for future decisions","a type of formal document","an unrelated coincidence"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"An earlier decision or action used as an example or justification for future decisions\" matches the meaning of 'precedent'."},{"id":"sde105015","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Rhetorical Appeals","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E5","q":"Which best describes the rhetorical appeal of 'ethos' when an organisation cites its long history to justify a current practice?","options":["this is an example of logos, since it relies purely on logical reasoning","this is an example of ethos, since it relies on established authority and tradition to lend credibility to the practice","this is an example of pathos, since it relies purely on emotional appeal","citing history has no connection to any rhetorical appeal"],"answer":1,"exp":"Citing a long history relies on ethos — established authority, tradition, and credibility — to lend legitimacy to a current practice, regardless of whether the practice is actually still justified."},{"id":"sde105016","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Logical Fallacies","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E5","q":"Which best describes the logical fallacy of 'appeal to tradition', sometimes used to resist change?","options":["arguing that something is correct or justified simply because it has traditionally been done that way","providing strong, current evidence to support a practice","acknowledging that traditions can sometimes be outdated","testing whether a tradition still serves its original purpose"],"answer":0,"exp":"An appeal to tradition fallacy argues that something is correct or justified simply because it has traditionally been done that way, without providing further substantive justification."},{"id":"sde105017","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Literary Devices — Satire","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E5","q":"Which best describes the difference between satire and simple mockery or insult?","options":["satire and mockery are exactly the same thing","satire typically aims at exposing or critiquing genuine flaws (often in systems or behaviours), often with a corrective purpose, while simple mockery may lack this deeper critical intent","mockery is always more sophisticated than satire","satire never involves any humour at all"],"answer":1,"exp":"Satire typically aims at exposing or critiquing genuine flaws (often in systems, institutions, or behaviours), often with an implicit corrective purpose, while simple mockery may lack this deeper critical intent."},{"id":"sde105018","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Essay Structure","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E5","q":"Which best describes an effective concluding paragraph for an essay analysing a satirical text?","options":["it should introduce an entirely new satirical technique not previously discussed","it should synthesise the essay's analysis, reflecting on the broader significance of what the satire reveals or critiques","it should simply restate the introduction word for word","conclusions are unnecessary in essays about satire"],"answer":1,"exp":"An effective conclusion synthesises the essay's analysis, reflecting on the broader significance of what the satire actually reveals or critiques about its target, rather than merely restating earlier points."},{"id":"sde105019","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Literary Devices — Irony","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E5","q":"Which best describes 'verbal irony', as distinct from situational irony?","options":["when an outcome contradicts expectations","when a speaker's words mean the opposite of, or contrast sharply with, their literal meaning","a coincidental event with no deeper meaning","a type of narrative structure"],"answer":1,"exp":"Verbal irony occurs when a speaker's words mean the opposite of, or contrast sharply with, their literal meaning — distinct from situational irony, which concerns outcomes rather than statements."},{"id":"sde105020","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Literary Devices — Satire","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E5","q":"Which best describes why analysing the NARRATIVE VOICE used in a satirical passage (such as a formal, deadpan tone describing absurd events) matters for understanding the satire's effect?","options":["narrative voice has no connection to satirical effect","the contrast between a serious, formal tone and the absurd content being described is often central to how the satire achieves its comic and critical effect","satire never uses a formal narrative voice","only the content of a satirical passage matters, never how it's narrated"],"answer":1,"exp":"The contrast between a serious, formal narrative tone and the genuinely absurd content being described is often central to how satire achieves its comic and critical effect, making narrative voice an important analytical focus."},{"id":"sde105021","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Poetry Terms","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E5","q":"Which best describes a 'villanelle' as a poetic form?","options":["a 19-line poem with two repeating rhymes and two refrains","a poem with absolutely no fixed structure","a type of persuasive essay","a synonym for free verse"],"answer":0,"exp":"A villanelle is a 19-line poem with a specific structure: two repeating rhymes and two refrains that recur throughout the poem in a set pattern."},{"id":"sde105022","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E5","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'absurd', as used to describe the Committee's exaggerated behaviour?","options":["completely logical and sensible","wildly unreasonable or ridiculous","extremely formal","entirely accurate"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Wildly unreasonable or ridiculous\" matches the meaning of 'absurd'."},{"id":"sde105023","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Logical Fallacies","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E5","q":"Which best describes the logical fallacy of 'slippery slope', sometimes used to resist even minor changes?","options":["arguing that a small, reasonable change will inevitably lead to a series of increasingly extreme and unlikely consequences","providing a step-by-step explanation of a genuinely connected process","acknowledging a range of possible outcomes with appropriate uncertainty","citing a specific, well-documented example"],"answer":0,"exp":"A slippery slope fallacy argues that a relatively small, reasonable change will inevitably lead to a chain of increasingly extreme and often unlikely consequences, without sufficient justification for that chain."},{"id":"sde105024","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Rhetorical Appeals","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E5","q":"Which best describes 'rhetorical appeals' (ethos, logos, pathos) when used in combination within a single persuasive text?","options":["only one rhetorical appeal can ever be used in a single text","combining multiple rhetorical appeals can address different aspects of a reader's judgement simultaneously, often strengthening the overall persuasive effect","using more than one rhetorical appeal always weakens an argument","rhetorical appeals are mutually exclusive and cannot be combined"],"answer":1,"exp":"Combining multiple rhetorical appeals (such as credibility, logic, and emotion) can address different aspects of a reader's judgement simultaneously, often strengthening the overall persuasive effect of a text."},{"id":"sde105025","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Literary Devices","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E5","q":"Which best describes a 'frame narrative' (a story within a story), sometimes used to add ironic distance in satirical writing?","options":["it has no real structural purpose","it can provide context, create distance or perspective, and sometimes allow the outer narrative to comment on the inner story's meaning","frame narratives are never used in satirical writing","a frame narrative always confuses readers with no benefit"],"answer":1,"exp":"A frame narrative provides context for an inner story, can create distance or a particular perspective, and sometimes allows the outer narrative to comment on the meaning of the inner story — a technique occasionally used in satire."},{"id":"sde106001","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Comparative Analysis — Spoken Texts","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E6","q":"Read this extract from a graduation speech: 'Extract from a graduation speech\n\n\"They told us, back in Year 7, that these would be the best years of our lives. I remember thinking that was a terrifying thing to hear at twelve years old — if this is the best it gets, I thought, I am in serious trouble.\n\nThey were wrong, by the way. Not because these years weren't good — they were, in ways I didn't always notice while they were happening — but because 'best years of your life' implies a kind of ceiling, a peak you pass on your way down. I don't think that's how it works. I think we just leave one room and walk into a bigger one, and the room we're leaving looks small only because we're finally standing somewhere that lets us see it properly.\n\nI won't stand up here and pretend every day of the last six years was meaningful. Plenty of it was standing in a corridor wondering if double maths would ever actually end. But somewhere in among the corridors and the double maths, something else was happening that none of us were really paying attention to: we were becoming whoever we are about to walk out of here as.\n\nSo no — I don't think these were the best years of our lives. I think they were the years that built whatever the best years are eventually going to be made of. And for that, however much double maths it took, I think we should be grateful.\"'\n\nWhat is the speaker's main argument about the claim that school represents 'the best years of your life'?","options":["that this claim is completely accurate","that this claim is wrong, since school years are better understood as building toward future 'best years', rather than being a peak in themselves","that school years were entirely wasted","that nothing meaningful happened during school"],"answer":1,"exp":"The speaker argues this claim is wrong because it 'implies a kind of ceiling, a peak you pass on your way down', proposing instead that school years build toward future best years."},{"id":"sde106002","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Comparative Analysis — Spoken Texts","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E6","q":"Read the same extract.\n\nWhat is the effect of the speaker's admission that 'plenty of it was standing in a corridor wondering if double maths would ever actually end'?","options":["it undermines the speech's credibility entirely","it adds humour and honesty, making the speech feel genuine rather than overly idealised, before pivoting to the deeper point","it suggests the speaker disliked school entirely","it has no particular rhetorical effect"],"answer":1,"exp":"This honest, humorous admission makes the speech feel genuine and relatable rather than overly idealised, which makes the subsequent deeper point land more effectively by contrast."},{"id":"sde106003","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Literary Devices","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E6","q":"Read the same extract.\n\nWhich best describes the metaphor of leaving 'one room and walk[ing] into a bigger one'?","options":["a literal description of changing classrooms","a metaphor suggesting that growth involves gaining a broader perspective on what came before, rather than reaching a final peak","a description of moving to a new school","an unrelated, random detail"],"answer":1,"exp":"This metaphor suggests that personal growth involves gaining an increasingly broader perspective on what came before (the smaller room), rather than reaching a single final peak."},{"id":"sde106004","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Persuasive and Rhetorical Techniques","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E6","q":"Read the same extract.\n\nWhich rhetorical technique is most evident in the repeated structure: 'I don't think these were the best years... I think they were the years that built...'?","options":["a logical fallacy","parallel structure, used to clearly contrast and reframe the initial claim into the speaker's own perspective","an unsupported statistic","a direct quote from another source"],"answer":1,"exp":"This repeated parallel structure ('I think...') clearly contrasts the initial claim with the speaker's own reframed perspective, reinforcing the central message through structural repetition."},{"id":"sde106005","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Comparative Analysis — Spoken Texts","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E6","q":"Read the same extract.\n\nHow might this spoken graduation speech be compared to a written reflective essay on a similar theme, in terms of tone and structure?","options":["spoken and written texts on the same theme would always be identical in style","a spoken speech often uses more conversational, direct address (like 'I won't stand up here and pretend') and rhetorical repetition, while a written essay might develop the same idea with more formal, extended analysis","spoken texts can never include personal reflection","written essays never use rhetorical techniques"],"answer":1,"exp":"A spoken speech often uses conversational, direct address and rhetorical repetition suited to a listening audience, while a written essay on the same theme might develop the idea with more formal, extended analytical structure suited to a reader."},{"id":"sde106006","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Literary Devices — Narrative Techniques","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E6","q":"Which best describes 'narrative techniques' such as flashback, used to alter the chronological structure of a story?","options":["narrative techniques have no real effect on a story's meaning","they can shape how readers understand cause, motivation, and significance by altering the order in which events are revealed","flashback is the only narrative technique that exists","narrative techniques are only relevant in poetry, not prose"],"answer":1,"exp":"Narrative techniques like flashback can shape how readers understand cause, motivation, and significance by altering the order in which events are revealed, rather than presenting them strictly chronologically."},{"id":"sde106007","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Literary Devices — Narrative Techniques","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E6","q":"Which best describes 'in medias res' as a narrative technique?","options":["beginning a story in the middle of the action, rather than at a strictly chronological starting point","ending a story with no resolution","writing entirely in dialogue","a synonym for flashback"],"answer":0,"exp":"\"In medias res\" (Latin for 'into the middle of things') is a technique of beginning a narrative in the middle of the action, rather than at a strictly chronological starting point."},{"id":"sde106008","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Comparative Analysis","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E6","q":"Which best describes the purpose of comparing how two different texts (one spoken, one written) approach a similar theme?","options":["comparison across different text TYPES has no analytical value","it can reveal how the specific demands and conventions of each medium (spoken versus written) shape the way a shared theme is communicated","only texts of the exact same type can ever be meaningfully compared","spoken and written texts can never share a common theme"],"answer":1,"exp":"Comparing a spoken and written text on a similar theme can reveal how the specific demands and conventions of each medium shape the way that shared theme is actually communicated to its audience."},{"id":"sde106009","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Essay Structure — Cohesion","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E6","q":"Which best describes 'cohesion' as a quality of effective essay writing?","options":["cohesion refers only to a text's length","cohesion refers to how clearly and smoothly ideas connect and flow together throughout a piece of writing","cohesion is a synonym for vocabulary difficulty","cohesion only matters in the introduction of an essay"],"answer":1,"exp":"Cohesion refers to how clearly and smoothly ideas connect and flow together throughout a piece of writing, helping a reader follow the logical progression of an argument."},{"id":"sde106010","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Essay Structure — Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E6","q":"Which best describes the use of varied, precise vocabulary as a feature of strong essay writing?","options":["vocabulary choice has no real bearing on essay quality","precise vocabulary allows a writer to express ideas with greater accuracy and nuance, avoiding vague or repetitive language","essays should always use the simplest possible vocabulary, regardless of precision","varied vocabulary always makes an essay harder to understand"],"answer":1,"exp":"Precise vocabulary allows a writer to express ideas with greater accuracy and nuance, avoiding vague or repetitive language that might weaken the overall clarity and impact of an essay."},{"id":"sde106011","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Essay Structure — Counter-Arguments","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E6","q":"Which best describes a 'counter-argument' paragraph within a persuasive or analytical essay?","options":["a paragraph that abandons the essay's original argument entirely","a paragraph that acknowledges an opposing viewpoint, before responding to it, strengthening the overall argument's credibility","counter-arguments should never appear in essays","a paragraph that simply repeats the thesis statement"],"answer":1,"exp":"A counter-argument paragraph acknowledges an opposing viewpoint and then responds to it, which can strengthen the overall argument's credibility by demonstrating awareness of alternative perspectives."},{"id":"sde106012","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E6","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'idealised', as used to describe an overly positive portrayal?","options":["realistically flawed","represented as perfect or more positive than reality, often unrealistically so","extremely negative","entirely accurate"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Represented as perfect or more positive than reality, often unrealistically so\" matches the meaning of 'idealised'."},{"id":"sde106013","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Vocabulary in Context","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E6","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'ceiling', as used metaphorically to describe a limit?","options":["a floor or foundation","an upper limit or maximum point","a type of room","an entrance or beginning point"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"An upper limit or maximum point\" matches the metaphorical meaning of 'ceiling' here, describing a peak beyond which things decline."},{"id":"sde106014","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Persuasive and Rhetorical Techniques","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E6","q":"Which best describes 'direct address' as a technique in spoken texts, such as a speech?","options":["a technique exclusively used in written essays","speaking directly to the audience, often using 'you' or addressing them as a group, to create personal connection and engagement","a synonym for a rhetorical question","a technique that always alienates the audience"],"answer":1,"exp":"Direct address involves speaking directly to the audience, often using 'you' or addressing them as a group, creating a sense of personal connection and engagement appropriate to a live, spoken context."},{"id":"sde106015","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Comparative Analysis — Spoken Texts","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E6","q":"Which best describes how a graduation speech's PURPOSE (celebrating, reflecting, encouraging) typically shapes its structure and tone?","options":["purpose has no real influence on a speech's structure or tone","a speech aiming to inspire and reflect often combines personal anecdote, humour, and a clear, memorable closing message, suited to a celebratory live audience","all speeches must follow exactly the same structure regardless of purpose","graduation speeches never include any personal reflection"],"answer":1,"exp":"A speech aiming to inspire and reflect often combines personal anecdote, humour, and a clear, memorable closing message, all suited to engaging a celebratory live audience in a way a formal essay might not need to."},{"id":"sde106016","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Essay Structure","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E6","q":"Which best describes why ending a speech with a strong, memorable final statement (such as 'I think we should be grateful') is an effective structural choice?","options":["endings have no particular significance in spoken texts","a strong final statement leaves a lasting impression, reinforcing the speech's central message at the moment the audience is most likely to remember it","speeches should never have a clear ending","the ending is the least important part of any speech"],"answer":1,"exp":"A strong final statement leaves a lasting impression, reinforcing the speech's central message at precisely the moment — the very end — when the audience is most likely to remember what was said."},{"id":"sde106017","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Persuasive and Rhetorical Techniques","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E6","q":"Which best describes the effect of using a personal, reflective anecdote (such as 'I remember thinking that was a terrifying thing to hear') at the start of a speech?","options":["it has no real effect on audience engagement","it immediately establishes a relatable, personal connection with the audience before developing the speech's broader argument","personal anecdotes always weaken a speech's credibility","anecdotes should only appear at the end of a speech, never the beginning"],"answer":1,"exp":"Opening with a personal, reflective anecdote immediately establishes a relatable, personal connection with the audience, drawing them in before the speech develops its broader argument or message."},{"id":"sde106018","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Literary Devices","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E6","q":"Which best describes 'pastiche' as a literary technique?","options":["a work that imitates the style of another work or genre, sometimes affectionately, sometimes critically","a strictly autobiographical account","a type of unreliable narrator","a single, isolated metaphor"],"answer":0,"exp":"Pastiche is a literary technique that imitates the style of another work, author, or genre, which can be done affectionately, critically, or simply as stylistic homage."},{"id":"sde106019","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Vocabulary in Context","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E6","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'reframed', as used to describe the speaker's alternative interpretation?","options":["completely ignored","presented from a new or different perspective","made more confusing","left entirely unchanged"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Presented from a new or different perspective\" matches the meaning of 'reframed', describing the speaker's act of presenting the same idea in a new light."},{"id":"sde106020","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Logical Fallacies","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E6","q":"Which best describes the logical fallacy of 'appeal to emotion', when used to substitute for genuine evidence?","options":["relying primarily on evoking feelings rather than providing logical reasoning or factual evidence to support a claim","providing a well-reasoned argument supported by relevant facts","acknowledging that emotion can play a legitimate role alongside evidence","a technique never found in persuasive speeches"],"answer":0,"exp":"An appeal to emotion fallacy relies primarily on evoking feelings rather than providing logical reasoning or factual evidence, attempting to persuade through emotional manipulation rather than substance."},{"id":"sde106021","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Essay Structure","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E6","q":"Which best describes the structural device of 'circular structure' in a speech or narrative, where the ending echoes the opening?","options":["it has no particular effect on a text's meaning","it can create a sense of closure and reinforce the central theme by returning to where the text began, often with a new layer of meaning","circular structure is only used in poetry","this device always indicates a poorly planned text"],"answer":1,"exp":"Circular structure can create a sense of closure and reinforce the central theme by returning to the text's opening, often with a deepened or transformed meaning given everything that came in between."},{"id":"sde106022","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E6","q":"Which word means almost the same as 'mundane', as used to describe ordinary, unremarkable daily details?","options":["extraordinary and exciting","ordinary, commonplace, and unremarkable","extremely rare","deeply mysterious"],"answer":1,"exp":"\"Ordinary, commonplace, and unremarkable\" matches the meaning of 'mundane'."},{"id":"sde106023","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Persuasive and Rhetorical Techniques","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E6","q":"Which best describes why a speaker might deliberately include both humour and genuine reflection within the same speech?","options":["combining humour and reflection always confuses the audience","balancing humour with genuine reflection can keep an audience engaged while still conveying a meaningful, memorable message","speeches should only ever contain humour, never serious reflection","speeches should only ever be entirely serious, with no humour at all"],"answer":1,"exp":"Balancing humour with genuine reflection can keep an audience engaged and entertained, while still successfully conveying a meaningful, memorable message by the speech's end."},{"id":"sde106024","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Literary Devices","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E6","q":"Which best describes a 'bildungsroman' as a literary genre, sometimes relevant to graduation or coming-of-age reflections?","options":["a novel focused on a detective solving a crime","a novel focused on the moral and psychological growth of a protagonist from youth to adulthood","a novel told entirely through letters","a novel with no clear protagonist"],"answer":1,"exp":"A bildungsroman is a novel focused on the moral and psychological growth and development of a protagonist, typically from youth into adulthood — a theme often echoed in graduation speeches reflecting on personal growth."},{"id":"sde106025","state":"AU","section":"sec_english","grade":"10","topic":"Comparative Analysis — Spoken Texts","difficulty":"hard","style":"standard","paper":"G10-E6","q":"Which best describes why a writer or speaker might choose to address a popular misconception (such as the 'best years of your life' claim) directly, before offering an alternative view?","options":["addressing misconceptions has no persuasive value","directly naming and engaging with a familiar misconception gives the speaker a clear, relatable starting point before reframing it, making the alternative view land more effectively","misconceptions should always be ignored rather than addressed","this approach only works in written essays, never speeches"],"answer":1,"exp":"Directly naming and engaging with a familiar misconception gives the speaker a clear, relatable starting point that the audience already recognises, making the subsequent reframing or alternative view land more effectively by contrast."},{"id":"se7v001","q":"Which word is an abstract noun?","options":["River","Freedom","Tiger","Chair"],"answer":1,"topic":"Grammar","exp":"Abstract nouns name ideas, qualities, or states: freedom, love, courage. Concrete nouns name things you can see or touch.","section":"sec_english","grade":7,"state":"AU","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard"},{"id":"se8v001","q":"Which word is an abstract noun?","options":["River","Freedom","Tiger","Chair"],"answer":1,"topic":"Grammar","exp":"Abstract nouns name ideas, qualities, or states: freedom, love, courage. Concrete nouns name things you can see or touch.","section":"sec_english","grade":8,"state":"AU","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard"},{"id":"se7v002","q":"What is a 'clause'?","options":["A punctuation mark","A group of words containing a subject and a verb","A type of paragraph","A sentence fragment without a verb"],"answer":1,"topic":"Grammar","exp":"A clause has a subject and verb. Independent clauses can stand alone; dependent clauses cannot ('because she smiled' — needs more).","section":"sec_english","grade":7,"state":"AU","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard"},{"id":"se8v002","q":"What is a 'clause'?","options":["A punctuation mark","A group of words containing a subject and a verb","A type of paragraph","A sentence fragment without a verb"],"answer":1,"topic":"Grammar","exp":"A clause has a subject and verb. Independent clauses can stand alone; dependent clauses cannot ('because she smiled' — needs more).","section":"sec_english","grade":8,"state":"AU","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard"},{"id":"se7v003","q":"Choose the correctly punctuated sentence.","options":["The dog wagged it's tail.","The dog wagged its tail.","The dogs wagged its' tail.","The dog wagged its' tail."],"answer":1,"topic":"Punctuation","exp":"'Its' (possessive pronoun, no apostrophe). 'It's' = 'it is'. Possessive pronouns never take apostrophes: his, her, its, their, our.","section":"sec_english","grade":7,"state":"AU","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard"},{"id":"se8v003","q":"Choose the correctly punctuated sentence.","options":["The dog wagged it's tail.","The dog wagged its tail.","The dogs wagged its' tail.","The dog wagged its' tail."],"answer":1,"topic":"Punctuation","exp":"'Its' (possessive pronoun, no apostrophe). 'It's' = 'it is'. Possessive pronouns never take apostrophes: his, her, its, their, our.","section":"sec_english","grade":8,"state":"AU","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard"},{"id":"se7v004","q":"What is the purpose of an adverb?","options":["To name a person or thing","To describe or modify a verb, adjective, or other adverb","To join clauses","To name an action"],"answer":1,"topic":"Grammar","exp":"Adverbs answer: How? (quickly), When? (yesterday), Where? (here), To what extent? (very). They modify verbs (ran quickly), adjectives (very tall), other adverbs (almost never).","section":"sec_english","grade":7,"state":"AU","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard"},{"id":"se8v004","q":"What is the purpose of an adverb?","options":["To name a person or thing","To describe or modify a verb, adjective, or other adverb","To join clauses","To name an action"],"answer":1,"topic":"Grammar","exp":"Adverbs answer: How? (quickly), When? (yesterday), Where? (here), To what extent? (very). They modify verbs (ran quickly), adjectives (very tall), other adverbs (almost never).","section":"sec_english","grade":8,"state":"AU","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard"},{"id":"se7v005","q":"Read: 'The abandoned warehouse echoed with the sound of dripping water.'\nWhat mood does this create?","options":["Cheerful","Eerie and tense","Peaceful","Humorous"],"answer":1,"topic":"Literary Devices","exp":"'Abandoned', 'echoed', 'dripping water' — these sensory details create an eerie, tense atmosphere suggesting danger or mystery.","section":"sec_english","grade":7,"state":"AU","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard"},{"id":"se8v005","q":"Read: 'The abandoned warehouse echoed with the sound of dripping water.'\nWhat mood does this create?","options":["Cheerful","Eerie and tense","Peaceful","Humorous"],"answer":1,"topic":"Literary Devices","exp":"'Abandoned', 'echoed', 'dripping water' — these sensory details create an eerie, tense atmosphere suggesting danger or mystery.","section":"sec_english","grade":8,"state":"AU","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard"},{"id":"se7v006","q":"What is the difference between 'imply' and 'infer'?","options":["They mean the same","The speaker/writer implies; the reader/listener infers","The reader implies; the writer infers","Both mean to state clearly"],"answer":1,"topic":"Vocabulary","exp":"Imply: to suggest without stating directly. Infer: to deduce from evidence. 'She implied he was wrong' → 'He inferred from her tone that she disagreed.'","section":"sec_english","grade":7,"state":"AU","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard"},{"id":"se8v006","q":"What is the difference between 'imply' and 'infer'?","options":["They mean the same","The speaker/writer implies; the reader/listener infers","The reader implies; the writer infers","Both mean to state clearly"],"answer":1,"topic":"Vocabulary","exp":"Imply: to suggest without stating directly. Infer: to deduce from evidence. 'She implied he was wrong' → 'He inferred from her tone that she disagreed.'","section":"sec_english","grade":8,"state":"AU","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard"},{"id":"se7v007","q":"What is 'alliteration'?","options":["Repetition of vowel sounds","Repetition of the same initial consonant sound in nearby words","Words that rhyme","A comparison using 'like' or 'as'"],"answer":1,"topic":"Literary Devices","exp":"Alliteration: 'Peter Piper picked a peck of pickled peppers.' The repeated 'p' sound creates rhythm and is memorable. Common in poetry and advertising.","section":"sec_english","grade":7,"state":"AU","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard"},{"id":"se8v007","q":"What is 'alliteration'?","options":["Repetition of vowel sounds","Repetition of the same initial consonant sound in nearby words","Words that rhyme","A comparison using 'like' or 'as'"],"answer":1,"topic":"Literary Devices","exp":"Alliteration: 'Peter Piper picked a peck of pickled peppers.' The repeated 'p' sound creates rhythm and is memorable. Common in poetry and advertising.","section":"sec_english","grade":8,"state":"AU","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard"},{"id":"se7v008","q":"Which is the BEST definition of 'theme' in literature?","options":["The main character","The setting of the story","The central message or insight about life conveyed by a text","The plot summary"],"answer":2,"topic":"Literary Devices","exp":"Theme: the universal idea or truth explored in a work. Not just 'love' but 'love can cause both joy and suffering'. Distinct from topic (what it's about) and plot (what happens).","section":"sec_english","grade":7,"state":"AU","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard"},{"id":"se8v008","q":"Which is the BEST definition of 'theme' in literature?","options":["The main character","The setting of the story","The central message or insight about life conveyed by a text","The plot summary"],"answer":2,"topic":"Literary Devices","exp":"Theme: the universal idea or truth explored in a work. Not just 'love' but 'love can cause both joy and suffering'. Distinct from topic (what it's about) and plot (what happens).","section":"sec_english","grade":8,"state":"AU","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard"},{"id":"se7v009","q":"What is 'jargon'?","options":["Rude language","Specialised vocabulary used by a particular profession or group","Words from another language","Old-fashioned expressions"],"answer":1,"topic":"Vocabulary","exp":"Jargon: technical terms understood by experts in a field (medical, legal, computing jargon). Can clarify within a group but excludes outsiders. Context determines whether it's appropriate.","section":"sec_english","grade":7,"state":"AU","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard"},{"id":"se8v009","q":"What is 'jargon'?","options":["Rude language","Specialised vocabulary used by a particular profession or group","Words from another language","Old-fashioned expressions"],"answer":1,"topic":"Vocabulary","exp":"Jargon: technical terms understood by experts in a field (medical, legal, computing jargon). Can clarify within a group but excludes outsiders. Context determines whether it's appropriate.","section":"sec_english","grade":8,"state":"AU","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard"},{"id":"se7v010","q":"What is 'bias' in media or non-fiction texts?","options":["Factual error","A balanced, objective perspective","An unfair preference or prejudice that influences the presentation of information","Deliberate lying"],"answer":2,"topic":"Reading Skills","exp":"Bias: perspective that unfairly favours one side. Can be explicit (direct statements) or subtle (word choice, selective omission of facts, image selection). Critical readers identify bias.","section":"sec_english","grade":7,"state":"AU","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard"},{"id":"se8v010","q":"What is 'bias' in media or non-fiction texts?","options":["Factual error","A balanced, objective perspective","An unfair preference or prejudice that influences the presentation of information","Deliberate lying"],"answer":2,"topic":"Reading Skills","exp":"Bias: perspective that unfairly favours one side. Can be explicit (direct statements) or subtle (word choice, selective omission of facts, image selection). Critical readers identify bias.","section":"sec_english","grade":8,"state":"AU","difficulty":"medium","style":"standard"},{"q":"What is 'plot' in narrative fiction?","options":["The setting","The sequence of events including the problem, rising action, climax, falling action and resolution","The theme","The point of view"],"answer":1,"topic":"Text Structure","exp":"Freytag's Pyramid: exposition→rising action→climax→falling action→resolution. Most narratives follow some version of this structure.","difficulty":"easy","id":"seceF60000060","section":"sec_english","state":"VIC","grade":"selective","style":"standard"},{"q":"What is 'tone' in a piece of writing?","options":["The volume","The writer's attitude toward the subject, conveyed through word choice and style","The length","The main character's feelings"],"answer":1,"topic":"Literary Devices","exp":"Tone: sarcastic, earnest, melancholic, playful, authoritative. Different from mood (how the reader feels). Authors control tone through diction, syntax and imagery.","difficulty":"medium","id":"seceF60000061","section":"sec_english","state":"VIC","grade":"selective","style":"standard"},{"q":"What is the 'climax' of a narrative?","options":["The beginning","The turning point or moment of highest tension, after which events resolve","The ending","The main character's introduction"],"answer":1,"topic":"Text Structure","exp":"The climax is the most intense moment. After it, the story's central conflict begins to resolve (falling action). It must feel earned through rising action.","difficulty":"easy","id":"seceF60000062","section":"sec_english","state":"VIC","grade":"selective","style":"standard"},{"q":"What does it mean to write a 'response to text'?","options":["Copy the text","Analyse, interpret or evaluate a text, supporting claims with evidence from the text","Summarise the text","Describe the characters"],"answer":1,"topic":"Writing","exp":"A text response: thesis → body paragraphs (topic sentence, evidence, analysis, link) → conclusion. PETAL or TEEL paragraph structure.","difficulty":"medium","id":"seceF60000063","section":"sec_english","state":"VIC","grade":"selective","style":"standard"},{"q":"What is a 'complex sentence'?","options":["A very long sentence","A sentence with one independent clause and at least one dependent (subordinate) clause","A sentence with two independent clauses","A sentence without any punctuation"],"answer":1,"topic":"Grammar","exp":"Complex: 'Although she was tired, she kept reading.' (dependent: 'Although she was tired'; independent: 'she kept reading'). Creates nuance and variety.","difficulty":"medium","id":"seceF60000064","section":"sec_english","state":"VIC","grade":"selective","style":"standard"},{"q":"What is 'symbolism'?","options":["Using symbols like punctuation marks","Using a concrete object, person or event to represent an abstract idea","Making things sound bigger than they are","A type of metaphor comparing two people"],"answer":1,"topic":"Literary Devices","exp":"Symbolism: the green light in 'The Great Gatsby' = Gatsby's dreams; white whale in 'Moby Dick' = obsession and the unknowable. Symbols enrich meaning.","difficulty":"medium","id":"seceF60000065","section":"sec_english","state":"VIC","grade":"selective","style":"standard"},{"q":"What is 'genre' in literature?","options":["The length of a text","A category of literature defined by style, form and subject matter","The author's purpose","The setting"],"answer":1,"topic":"Text Types","exp":"Genre: mystery (suspense, detective), romance, science fiction, horror, fantasy. Each has conventions. Subverting genre expectations creates interesting effects.","difficulty":"easy","id":"seceF60000066","section":"sec_english","state":"VIC","grade":"selective","style":"standard"},{"q":"What is 'diction'?","options":["A dictionary","An author's choice of words to create tone, mood and meaning","Correct pronunciation","A type of metaphor"],"answer":1,"topic":"Literary Devices","exp":"Diction: formal vs informal, simple vs complex, latinate vs Anglo-Saxon, emotive vs neutral. Hemingway's simple diction vs Henry James's elaborate diction.","difficulty":"medium","id":"seceF60000067","section":"sec_english","state":"VIC","grade":"selective","style":"standard"},{"q":"What is the 'narrative arc'?","options":["A shape in geometry","The overall shape or progression of a story from beginning through conflict to resolution","The narrator's personality","A type of metaphor"],"answer":1,"topic":"Text Structure","exp":"Narrative arc: introduction → complication → rising action → climax → falling action → resolution. Short stories may compress or omit stages.","difficulty":"easy","id":"seceF60000068","section":"sec_english","state":"VIC","grade":"selective","style":"standard"},{"q":"What is a 'persuasive text'?","options":["A text that tells a story","A text that aims to change the reader's opinion or behaviour on an issue","A text that describes an experience","A text that gives instructions"],"answer":1,"topic":"Text Types","exp":"Persuasive texts: essays, speeches, advertisements, letters to editor. Techniques: rhetorical questions, emotional appeal, statistics, expert opinion, repetition.","difficulty":"easy","id":"seceF60000069","section":"sec_english","state":"VIC","grade":"selective","style":"standard"}];